1. d4( { Hello! I'm the Grand Master Àlvar Alonso and here I am again with a new course for Chessable. After the delightful experience with the Catalan, I wanted to do a Black repertoire where I had added value out of the experience and I thought 'What could be better than the defense I used since I had my first rating of 2500'?. Let me elaborate on some of the reasons for my choice and also some insights:     1 . You cannot find a pure repertoire with the Benoni almost anywhere (Chessable included 🙂). You mostly see a complementary defense if you already know the Nimzoindian. After the following move order: }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { here against }3.Nc3 Bb4 { the Nimzo, and if }{   }3.Nf3 { or }3.g3 { we can go for }3...c5 { to get into a Benoni.      Why is that? Because it has been widely considered that pure Benoni suffers against  Nc3 - e4 - f4 - Bb5 +. Not gonna lie, it is by far the riskier variation, but by no means kills the Defense yet, and it was a huge effort to find the correct ways.     You need to think about your opponent, after having something against the Nimzoindian, the Orthodox, the Slav, the Semislav, the QGA, Kings Indian, Grunfeld, and the Dutch 🙂 do you think they have time to also check something super deep against the Benoni? From my experience, playing it for years most of my opponents would be playing the Benoni structures for the first time, and it is not an easy task.       2 . With }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 { we don't allow White to have second thoughts as it happens the conventional move order. Most of my games after }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 c5 { were sadly followed by }4.g3 { , }4.Nc3 { or even }4.e3 { , which doesn't correlate at all with everything you learn with the Benoni as the fianchetto on  g7 , is never happening in those variations.     After }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nf3 cxd4! 4.Nxd4 e5! 5.Nb5 d5! { we immediately seize the center and get into a sharp position. If White deviates from this path we achieve significantly better positions as we did not commit to  e7 -... e6 , thus we have much more flexibility. I think those lines are quite insightful, as you will learn many themes in 1.  d4  structures.       3 . You are starting to see how we are taking no prisoners here. You need to realize that most people prevent chaos or are uncomfortable with sharp variations. I recently faced Dreev and Tomashevsky in a rapid event and they both went for safe approaches with  d4 - Nf3 - c3  and  d4 - Nf3 - e3  respectively, so you equalize immediately on move 3, and you'll have many weapons to counter these setups. Especially in faster time controls, this repertoire shines.     So our go-to against setup-enjoyers like the London will be the same }1.d4 Nf6 { and }2.Bf4 c5 { no matter what. Most of the courses I've checked on the London (and believe me here, I checked EVERY course on Chessable in the London) try to give a sharp sideline to counter 2... c5  with }3.d5 { , this for me is a weird concept, as it just changes completely the approach of the rest of those courses.     I mean, 15–20 years ago I was bored to play against the London as I was guaranteed pawns on  c3 - d4 - e3  and a bishop on  f4 , and it was hard to crack, but the modern era of chess doesn't have that consistency on the repertoires I would say, so we can get our opponent out of comfort very quickly.      Against }1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 { I chose }3...b5! { as well, in both cases to make sure we get some reasonable unbalance from the start with a degree of consistency.       A reasonable step in the ladder of knowledge would be to ONLY play the Benoni against something else than 2. c4 , so you get lots of practice on the sidelines. If you come from the Volga/Benko, this shall help you a lot.       4 . I played it. A lot. I was mostly clueless, to be honest. So I highly encourage you to focus on some simple patterns → Exchange on  d5 , castle quickly, try to exchange a couple of pieces as the  c8 -bishop }{ (usually  Bg4 ) }{ and the  b8 -knight are both fighting for squares to develop and then push the queenside.     I barely knew 0.1% of everything you have in this course so PLEASE for each hour you spend learning it, spend one playing at least }( { I'd say more, but okay you get the idea 🙂). It's a very practical weapon. You should have the following mentality:     a ) Look for chances and differences. The Benoni is excellent, as the cost of making a mistake against it can mean immediate defeat. Focus on understanding from the beginning, don't rely on memory as it is likely to get you into some trouble with the Benoni anyway, so the sooner you start thinking the better.     b ) It will force you to be thinking in sharp positions since move 3 or 4, so it shines considering the compound interest of calculation that has on chessplayers (Carlsen and Kasparov, to say a couple names, started with the Kings Indian and even the Benoni) that's why strong kids usually play sicilians, you get used to making important decisions often and calculate.    In my opinion, that's why I don't like when the dull London system version is taught to starters (I'm referring to the pre-move 15 moves-style of London) as it kills creativity and tends to make players very evasive of any complications, hence delaying any experience in complicated positions. Imagine a kid having the Berlin as the first defense ever. 🙂     c ) Since we have a lot of go-to plans ( ...a6-...Rb8-...b5; ...Qc7-...c4-...Nbd7-...Nc5 ) it's more important to have a light knowledge about all of our plans and choose which path to take according to our opponents' decisions.    I'll take the chance here to say something that I never get tired of saying: PLEASE think of what your opponent's next move is. Don't try to impose your plan, chess is a reactive game, so let your opponent make mistakes! I recently placed 4th in the European Blitz Championship.    Tell me, when you have 3 seconds on the clock if you don't instinctively check first what is your opponent's next move, how do you expect not to blunder? Look for opportunities, look for ways to make a decision complicated for your opponent. If you happen to excel at bullet, you will understand my point very well. 🙂    This course, I hope, is much more than an opening course. Take it as a position to think creatively to calculate sharp ... b5!  sacrifices, take it as an exercise book, so get used to pausing or just look at the board and tell yourself 'Let me think what I would do here before Àlvar tells me'.    The Benoni is not a defense to memorize and vomit. I give plenty of model games even in different lines that are not covered as the main repertoire, so you can experience the Benoni a bit the way you want. Maybe you despise ... b5  against  h3-Bd3  variation, maybe you fancy setups with  ...Na6-...Nc7  more, maybe you like ... Qh4+  against  Bb5+-...Nfd7  lines.    By the end of the course, the last phrase will make sense, trust me 🙂. Some chapters are there for the sake of completeness, and, likely, you never experience them, as some variations got old. Don't worry, I'll tell you tons of times in the chapters. 🙂     5 . Not convinced yet? We can talk about Indjic, Pantsulaia, Pouya, and Edouard Romain to name some names that happen to be very creative, and risk-lover players often use this weapon to create an imbalance.    Recently, Rapport found it a good option to go for in rapid time controls, Nakamura used it in the World Cup and, if we go a bit further into the past, Gashimov was consistently playing it with success at +2700 level and creative players like Morozevich often used it to spice things up too.     6 . It's a repertoire you can use with reversed colors. Especially, Pantsulaia has been playing it both ways from the Neo-Catalan (or Catalan without }d4 { ) his whole life. It's incredibly popular (specially to tease solid Orthodox - ...d5-...e6-...Nf6 - players to open up the position) and you will be like: What? Do I get to play it with 1 or 2 extra tempos? It's amazing!     7 . Alternatives. The last chapters will give you the variety required to fit every challenge.    - Are you worried about an opponent that plays  Bb5+  or  h3-Bf4  setup? No problem! Go for the delayed version and you counter it easily. I'm pretty sure you'll quickly become a fan of the … Rxe3+!  sacrifice. You'll see 😉    - Do you want to immediately play a sharp alternative, barely checking less than a hundred moves? Check the dark alternatives with }1...c5 { to break your opponent.    - Use the second degree of rationality. The Benoni has often been considered to be better for White if the pawn is on  c2  (as White can enjoy the  c4  square easily and the symmetry after taking on  d5  with the  e -pawn makes it harder for us to create counterplay) but we give it another twist, so we set up many traps and show them how 'It's supposed to be bad' is far from enough 🙂.     8 . It's fun. So much fun. I remember one experience from the World Youth U12 in 2004 where I finished 5th }{ (ahead of some names like Caruana and So, behind a certain Ding 😜).     I'd recommend you to set up the board, or follow along blindly if you can:) }( 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 c5 { of course }3.c3 { sad }3...e6 4.Bg5 cxd4 5.cxd4 Qa5+ { I'm a son of the Benoni- were you expecting something sound and logical? }6.Nbd2 Ne4 { ATTACK }7.Qc2 { I still remember the shivers down my spine after realizing my  c8 -bishop is in the air. New pattern acquired }7...Nxg5 { I might as well sink with the ship like a true captain }8.Qxc8+ Ke7 9.Nxg5 Qxg5 10.e4 {  Qxb7-Qd5  was terrible but not losing }10...g6 { see? it's a Benoni! 😁 }11.h4 { and here I'll stop and let you think how I forced the resignation of my opponent.     That game sums up my experience with the Benoni pretty well, you'll make mistakes, but you will hold yourself with all your strength into the board and FIGHT! } ) ) )
1. Nf6( 1...c5!? { this move order is covered in  chapters 18 & 19 . } )
2. c4( 2.Nf3 { is covered in  chapter 11 & 12 . } )( 2.Bf4 c5 { is covered in  chapter 13 . } )( 2.Nc3!? { is covered in  chapter 14 . } )( 2.Bg5 { is covered in  chapter 15 . } )
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6( 3...g6 4.Nc3 { is covered in  chapter 17 . } )
