7. Bf4{ This is often considered the best and most reliable plan for White. This is what I recommend in my 1.  d4  Chessable course as White focuses on development and pressure on the  d6  weak point.     It is like 'the London' of the Benoni, so we need to play precisely to not allow an easy play for White. The general aim for White is to go for a less ambitious but reliable  h3 ,  e3 ,  Be2 ,  Bh2 ,  Nd2 , and  Nc4  or  f4 ,  e4  to crush us with  e4 - e5 . }
7. a6( { We want to prevent the extra option for white after }7...Bg7 8.Qa4+!? { It is technically fine for black, but doesn't make much sense to cover both.     The extra option we get from delaying ... a6  is to play an eventual ... Na6  and I felt it wasn't that great, as I cover this line in my Chessable course with White. 🙂 } )
8. e4( 8.Qa4+ { runs into }8...b5! 9.Nxb5 Bd7! { and we can appreciate how having the bishop on  f8  prevents the only way out for white with 10. Nxd6+ . It's also relevant to notice  Qa4 + idea to force black to block on  d7  and then retreat on  b3  and the  d6 -pawn would be under attack, but here it is not the case, so even a move like: }8...Nbd7 { would work.       In this variation, White prefers to take the extra tempo in the center to play  e2 - e4  in one take. Usually, White is forced to play  e2 - e3  and if we castle quickly, White will suffer to hold the center. } )
8. b5{ Obviously, we accept the invitation and expand our dominance in the queenside. Now we need to play a bit precisely to compensate for White's presence in the center. }
9. Bd3{ White is so far ahead on development, and we need to be careful not to allow  h3 ,  a3 ,  Qd2 , and  b4  setups that counter how we expand on the queenside. }
9. Nh5( { In case of the usual }9...Bg4!? { I found a problem. After the logical }10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 Bg7 12.O-O O-O 13.a4! { is incredibly strong, as we have some issues securing the light-squares on the queenside. It isn't that weird of a move, and can leave us with a very uncomfortable position after something like }13...c4 14.Be2 b4 15.Na2 { taking soon enough on  c4  and placing an annoying bishop on  b5 . } )
10. Bg5{ This theme appears in many lines of the Benoni. We don't want to play  f7 -... f6  if ... f6 -... f5  is not feasible soon enough. }
10. Be7{ Since we have expanded on the Queenside, we can allow ourselves to break the golden rule of the bishop going to  g7  for now. White invested many moves as well without castling. }
11. Bh6{ Taking on  e7  would give us good control of the dark squares, as ... Bg4 ! or ... Nf4  are coming, so White would need to make a concession. }
11. Bg4{ The general idea would be to take on  f3  and look for ... Bg5 !?, to get all the dark squares and leave White with the least menacing pieces defending on light squares passively. }
12. Be2{ White wants to recapture on  f3  with the Bishop, so the knight on  h5  is a bit out of place. It is a known theme in the  h3 ,  Bd3 ,  Nf3  variation whenever White plays  Bg5 - Bf6 - Be3  and Black looks for ... Nd7 -... Ne5  and White delay the capture on  e5  to play  Be2  and threaten the  h5 -knight. }
12. Nd7{ If our opponent doesn't force us, we continue with this useful move before taking on  f3  and ... Bg5 . This line is grounded in the same principles as the usual Benoni, exchanging the  c8 -bishop and then looking for squares and using the expansion on the queenside. }( {  1-0   (36) Kovalenko, I (2515)-Savchenko, B (2637) Moscow 2011  continued with }13.O-O { and after }13...Bxf3 { followed by ... Bg5  Black would've been in an excellent position. } )
