9. Bd3{ I played this setup maybe 30 times, counting White and Black games. White has a very safe center, and the  c8 -bishop doesn't have an exit. Following it up with  O-O  and  Bf4  to have permanent pressure on  d6  is usually how it goes. }
9. b5{ The most direct and practical chance. We put into good use being castled fast, and White is one move short. I have plenty of games with ... a6 ,  a4 , and then ... Nh5  ideas, but I feel it was just pain and misery overall. White develops peacefully, and we have the  c8 -bishop stuck for a while without much chance to escape.      It is widely known as the best answer for black, and it is also the most played one. Now White can take on  b5  with both pieces, and we have different resources through the  e -file and with  Qa5 +. }
10. Nxb5{ The only reasonable chance for White to look for advantage. }( 10.O-O { I scored a couple of wins here with White, so it is not that stupid. White wants to play  a3 ,  Bf4 ,  Qd2 , and  b2 - b4  blocking the advance of our queenside. If we ever have ... a6 , ... b5 ,... c4 , imagine how sad the  c8 -bishop would be, }10...b4 { is the easiest and most consistent answer. We keep getting space on the queenside, and we'll exchange the annoying  c8 -bishop.     Our knight likely gets on an awkward spot on  a6 , don't mind playing ... Nb8  back and shifting to  d7 - b6  to control more light squares, as we have our pawn chain completely taking control of the dark ones.     Black has a very easy play going on, and White doesn't have any challenging plan to make use of the center pawn structure. } )( { In case of }10.a3 b4! { and the same idea with ... Ba6  works incredibly well. } )
10. Re8( 10...Nxe4 { now is flawed after }11.Bxe4 Re8 12.Ng5!+- { White will always have  Ne6  as a resource if the  g5 -knight is attacked. Instead we threaten the  e4 -pawn. } )( { White has some tries but only   }11.O-O { should worry us. } )
11. O-O
11. Nxe4{ We get the central pawn, so White has a worse pawn structure, and we have a very strong bishop. Our main concern remains to finish the queenside development and how White can make use of it. In general, we want to follow up with  a7 -... a6  to force the  b5 -knight away from  c3 , and then finish developing with ... Nd7 . }
12. Bf4{ White increases the pressure on  d6 , and we need to be careful as many obvious moves fail. }
12. a6{ As usual. }
13. Na3{ White tries to get fancy with the help of the engine. }( { As usual, against }13.Nc3 Nxc3 14.bxc3 Nd7 { is just fine for Black. } )
13. Nf6( { After }13...Bxb2 14.Nc4! { White has huge compensation through the dark squares and was basically winning after a few moves recently in  ½-½   (53) Abasov,N (2634)-Pantsulaia,L (2597) Baku 2023 . After ... Nf6  we play it safe. } )
14. Nc4
14. Bf8
15. Bc2{ Has already been played in correspondence chess. We need to keep developing, but playing something to  d7  would imply losing the  d6 -pawn. }
15. a5{ We'll play ... Ba6  and later on ... Nbd7 , and we solved everything. Considering this line is only expected to be faced against a well-prepared opponent, this final position is very safe and sound. }
