3. Bg7{ Finally, we are going to take a brief look at the Benoni options when our opponent plays  c4  anyway. This chapter is just an alternative, so you enjoy all the options through the Benoni.     Adding a chapter on the Benko/Volga would be a bit too out of topic, maybe if it is requested a lot we can dig into it, but this setup can be used to surprise someone. Recently, Magnus and our God in these setups, Pantsulaia, have been finding success with it. }
4. e4
4. d6{ We keep delaying the development of the  g8 -knight, so we have some extra options. Obviously, you can mix the move orders depending on what you like about these lines. }
5. Nf3
5. e6
6. h3{ As you can see, White needs to be incredibly aware of this ... Bxc3 +. }( 6.Nc3 Bxc3+ { we still get into our desired setup. We might be a tempo down, but it is the same in practice. } )
6. exd5
7. exd5
7. Nd7{ We take advantage of the move order and exchange a couple of pieces quickly with ... Ne5 . }
8. Nc3
8. Ne5
9. Nxe5
9. Bxe5
10. Bd3
10. Ne7
11. O-O
11. Nf5{ We prevent  Bh6 , and we have plenty of space for the rest of our pieces after ... O-O . White might have some precise and lightly better options, but I wanted you to see how playing obvious moves is not enough for White and the incredible practicality of these setups. }
