[White "1) Benoni With 6.e4 & 7.f4"]
[Black "7.f4 and 8.e5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. e5{ The first question. What now? }
8. Nfd7{ We don't want to trade pawns first. Opening the  d -file and letting the  c1 -bishop threaten a future  Bg5  are two simple ideas that justify it. But okay, get used to play the precise moves in this variation, sometimes there won't be a better explanation than 'it works, so we play it'. }
9. exd6{ This is too greedy and messes up with White's pawn structure. We keep up with development. }
9. O-O{ Now I really love the plan ... Nf6 -... Ne8 -... Nxd6 . With that we'll have an excellent blockade and our bishop on  g7  will have excellent views of the queenside. On top of that, we'll have an easier time looking for the typical queenside expansion with ... b5 . }
10. Nb5( { Basically any move is good here (let's say }10...Na6 { ), but again I use this opportunity to encourage you to try to look further down. White wants to go  Nc7 ? Okay, good luck getting out later on! } )
10. a6
11. Nc7{ This knight won't be coming back anytime soon. }
11. Ra7{ ... Nf6  and  Qxd6  is on our wishlist. What can white do? }
12. Qe2
12. Nf6
13. Qe7
13. b6( { Since exchanging queens doesn't really change the fact that we will take on  d6  and the knight on  c7  will perish, we threaten }.-- 14...Re8! { making good use of the pin on the  c7 -knight and white has no answer to that threat. } )
