[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. e5{ The first question. What now? }
8. Nfd7{ We don't want to trade pawns first. Opening the  d -file and letting the  c1 -bishop threaten a future  Bg5  are two simple ideas that justify it. But okay, get used to play the precise moves in this variation, sometimes there won't be a better explanation than 'it works, so we play it'. }
9. Nb5{ The main idea. }( 9.Ne4 { does the same effect. White gives up now the  e5 -pawn in exchange for making us lose the right to castle. It looks dangerous, but we also need to consider one thing: White is spending 4 tempos to exchange a piece that wasn't developed.     White gets far behind on development, and we have a tricky situation with our king, as white wants to castle and use the  f -file to create fireworks. } )
9. dxe5{ No fancy stuff. }
10. Nd6+
10. Ke7{ It's important to force the knight on  d6  out and look for the 'artificial' way to castle with ... Re8  and ... Kf8 . }
11. Nxc8+{ Otherwise we would follow with ... Re8  as said. }
11. Qxc8
12. Nf3( 12.d6+ { looks very tempting for white to deprive us of developing the rook, but it also enables our  b8 -knight so, overall, it's not worth for White. After }12...Kf8 { we have an easy development with ... Nc6  and an excellent control of the dark squares in the center. If White tries something fancy like }13.Nf3 e4! 14.Ne5 { (to open up our kingside) just }14...Nc6 { would give us a clear advantage. } )
12. Rd8( { I played }12...Re8 { I got crushed by a correspondence player many years ago:  1-0   (30) Moreto Quintana,A (2133)-Alonso Rosell,A (2180) Barbera del Valles 2006 . I wasn't lost immediately by any means but 12...  Rd8  is a bit more precise, and we simply focus on the  d5 -pawn. For starters, we want to go for ... Kf8 , obviously. } )
13. fxe5
13. Nxe5
14. Nxe5
14. Bxe5
15. Bc4
15. Rd6{ I love this setup. Looks so solid. After ... Nd7  and ... f6 , we have everything under control. Why ... Rd6 ? Because it prevents White from eventually sacrificing or pushing the  d -pawn to weaken our light squares, as we dominate only the dark squares.     After getting the mentioned setup, we could follow with ... Qc7 , ... Re8 , ... Kd8 !, and long castle! The blockade in the center allows us to be a bit more optimistic about our plans than usual. }
