7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. e5{ The first question. What now? }
8. Nfd7{ We don't want to trade pawns first. Opening the  d -file and letting the  c1 -bishop threaten a future  Bg5  are two simple ideas that justify it. But okay, get used to play the precise moves in this variation, sometimes there won't be a better explanation than 'it works, so we play it'. }
9. e6{ This would be an example of how White can easily overextend. }
9. fxe6
10. dxe6
10. Nb6{ Now imagine this position without the  f  and  d -pawns,  Qxd8 + and  Bg5 + would give white a terrifying initiative. In this case, Black will castle and likely eat the juicy  e6  pawn. }
11. f5( { White dreams to play }11...gxf5 12.Qh5+ { and give us an unpleasant surprise on  f7 . } )
11. O-O{ White is neglecting the development.     Another piece of advice: Be careful with playing a move solely because 'if he plays X move, I win!, so it must be good!', don't play 'tricky' for the sake of it, be smart about it!     It's like trying to do the Scholar's mate all the time, always expect the best from your opponent! }
12. fxg6
12. Bxe6
13. gxh7+
13. Kh8{ I want to give this positions as an example of a very important motif in the Benoni I experienced a lot while playing it. Your  g7 -bishop is a beast. Sometimes you'll find yourself with few pawns or even pawnless, like in here, but with a brave partner covering the key dark squares.     I'll take this moment to also reinforce a crucial idea in this course:  Dynamics . You'll need to be constantly thinking ahead, for instance in this position I see:      1 . White need 3 tempos to castle and I have almost everything developed, how can I make him suffer?      2 . White doesn't have easy moves, but it is quite predictable he will try to castle asap.      3 . Pawns (or even pieces) don't matter until the waters calm down. }
14. Nf3
14. Bg4
15. Be2
15. Bxf3
16. Bxf3
16. Bd4{ We basically negate white the right to castle, and we want to follow up with the development. }
17. Ne2{ White wants to castle! }( 17.Bxb7 { would be too greedy as }17...Qe7+ { just wins a piece. } )
17. Nc6{ Since we know 18.  Nxd4  is a must for white, we can set up a nice trap. }
18. Nxd4
18. Qh4+{ Checks, captures, threats! }
19. g3
19. Qxd4{ White won't be castling any time soon, and the final rook is coming into the action. This is a great example on how fast-paced can a Benoni be. We'll always be looking for what White wants to do and use that in our benefit. }
