[White "1) Benoni With 6.e4 & 7.f4"]
[Black "7.f4 with 8.Bb5+ and 9.Be2 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. Bb5+{ The main move. White gives a very annoying check as we cannot answer it with the two logical options (... Bd7  and ... Nbd7 ), as the push  e4 - e5  will threaten the  f6 -knight and the ideal square to back up ( d7 ) is occupied.      I want to add here some thoughts. Thinking deeply about what was the reason why I succeeded so much with the Benoni I found an interesting approach. White has plenty of space and usually doesn't have a direct way to win.     Our opponent needs to keep the balance between our counterplay and keeping the pressure up. As long as we don't make a blunder in one, we usually have very few moves available. Or we try to develop and do the 2–3 plans (or  Bg4  or  a6 - b5  or some funky  f5 , that's it), or we die.     This involves risk, but also involves often having only one reasonable option as it is easier to say 'Well, this line I basically die against  e4 - e5 , this should be the move'. It's a defense that benefits a lot from surviving one more move and always has counterplay. You'll see how basically all our moves make direct sense (you see the outcome or plan very quickly) and often our opponents' are the 'engine moves' that make sense 5–6 moves later for a tactical motif.      It was the pet opening of a young Kasparov, and more recently Gashimov demonstrated how it was possible to play it at the highest level. Even the new generation played it as Abdusattorov and Rapport have tested it recently and many 2600+ like Pouya, Indjic and Pantsulaia play it quite often these days with good results.      After all this long introduction, I hope you are ready for some of the most enjoyable lines I've ever witnessed as a student, coach, and player! }
8. Nfd7{ A sad must. }( 8...Nbd7 { or }8...Bd7 { basically lose to }9.e5 { . Time ago, when computers weren't that good, it was a decent try as white needed to calculate quite a lot, but now if the opponent knows slightly what he's doing it would mean a quick and painless defeat.     There is some hope as well for black, as usually we plan to go for ... a6 , ... b5 . White needs to invest a tempo, preventing it (9. a4 ), retreating (9. Be2  and 9. Bd3 ) or allow us to expand with ... a6 , ... b5 . } )
9. Be2{ This is maybe the most critical line in my honest opinion. The bishop has already accomplished a lot, as our development is far less smooth. }( { So going back to }e2 { shifts to the main old line after   }8.Nf3 { & 9.  Be2 . This was the line used by my first GM coach, Moskalenko, to actually beat me when I started to play the Benoni, so I will make sure we don't share that memory. } )
9. O-O( 9...Qh4+ { is an interesting approach, but we kinda force White to go for  f4 - f5  ideas and those are actually the scariest so, yeah, not sure. Also, it feels like cheating, we play the Benoni the brave way, or we don't. } )
10. Nf3
10. Na6{ As usual, we aim to develop the queenside first.  Be2  is better compared to  Bd3  as we cannot answer the same way. }
11. O-O
11. Nc7{ Now we don't have the  b4 -square, so we'll look for the usual plan with ... a6 , ... b5 . From now on, it doesn't matter much if White plays  a4  first or not, as we will go for ... a6 , ... Rb8  most of the time. }
12. Bd2{ White aims to reroute the bishop to  h4 . Going for  Be3  with or without  h4  has a similar outcome. You might be wondering why we don't go for ... Nc7  all the time instead of the risky ... Nb4  plan against an early 9.  a4 . White has the option to go for  Bd3 - f5  straight forward and can be annoying, certainly. }
12. a6
13. a4
13. Rb8
14. Be1{ The main hidden idea. White wants to reroute the bishop to  h4  or  g3  and push the center. Needs to be said that precisely  Bh4  on the next move is bad, so it's not easy and intuitive how to play with White. I'd say don't look too much at this move, it is pretty rare that White just lets us play ... b5  for fun. }( 14.a5 { White prevents us from getting an extended pawn chain. It is by far the most played move, but black is more than fine }14...b5 15.axb6 Nxb6 { we'll keep up with ... Nb5 , and we have a lot of space, counterplay and White's center is not scary. } )
14. b5
15. Bh4{ Moskalenko played twice this move and won both games, but I'd say it wasn't thanks to the opening. 🙂 }
15. Bf6
16. Bxf6
16. Nxf6
17. e5
17. b4{ White loses the  d5 -pawn or needs to give up his dreams of a strong center. }
18. exf6
18. bxc3
19. bxc3
19. Qxf6{ White has a very overextended pawn structure and worse minor pieces. The knight on  f3  doesn't jump anywhere, and the  e2 -bishop would be a very unpleasant responsibility for White.  1-0   (53) Moskalenko,V (2505) -Totsky,L (2435) Moscow 1992 . }
