10. b5
11. O-O
11. O-O{ White has plenty of moves. It is a pretty uncommon line, but I feel the more examples of counterplay, plans, and defenses you have on the Benoni, the more you would benefit in general. }
12. Kh1{ A very common move in the  f4  variation. White gets out of the exposed  a7 - g1  diagonal to get ahead of some forcing variations later on, in which we benefit from checks. }
12. b4{ This is a great example to show that 'active moves' doesn't correlate necessarily with 'good moves' even in dynamic defenses like the Benoni. }
13. Na4
13. a5{ We follow up a known plan to exchange the light-squared bishops. }( 13...Nb6 { would be answered similarly, }14.Nxb6 Qxb6 15.Nd2! { , and we will suffer as the queenside is closed. } )
14. Be3
14. Ba6
15. Bxa6
15. Nxa6
16. Qd3( { In comparison to   }12.a3 b4 { we don't have the follow-up ... bxa3 !, freeing the  b4 -square. Now we have a very dull knight on  a6 , and we cannot open the queenside to create the necessary counterplay. White would follow with  Nd2 - Nc4  and  Rad1 , and finally choose whether  e4 - e5  or  f4 - f5  is better. } )
