10. Bd3( { White can retreat now and force us to go for }10...b5 { . I mean, I like to play  b7 -... b5 , but here we don't have any other option as ... O-O  would run into  a4 , and we would be lacking the ... Na6  option.     I want to point out this obvious subtlety as when I started playing the Benoni in blitz I happened to play instinctively  a7 -... a6  in wrong situations. 🙂 } )
10. b5
11. O-O
11. O-O{ White has plenty of moves. It is a pretty uncommon line, but I feel the more examples of counterplay, plans, and defenses you have on the Benoni, the more you would benefit in general. }
12. Kh1{ A very common move in the  f4  variation. White gets out of the exposed  a7 - g1  diagonal to get ahead of some forcing variations later on, in which we benefit from checks. }
12. Re8
13. f5
13. Nf6( 13...Ra7 { to follow up with ... Ne5  is acceptable as well, but again, this variation after  Bd3  is designed to showcase all the thematic dangers you can face, so the more patterns the better. } )
14. Bg5{ This move looks menacing and makes sense, but White barely has a presence on dark-squares, so the pin is not that dangerous. }( { Funny how }14.Bf4 { runs into }14...Nbd7! { as well and if }15.Bxd6 b4! { and we will take the  e4 -pawn and our pieces are having a great time. } )
14. Nbd7
15. Qd2{ Here we do have a couple of ways to approach this position. }
15. gxf5{ This move is usually very tricky, as White can sacrifice another pawn (with a move like 16.  Nh4 ) and suddenly all minor pieces for White (and the  f1 -rook and the queen on  d1 ) are threatening our king.     It's a very common theme in the Grand Prix attack as well. In this specific case, it works, but only with precise play. }
16. exf5{ With this move, our castle is a bit weaker, but the dark squares are under control. We need to react quickly as  Qf4  and  Rae1  are very challenging ideas. }
16. c4{ We do an expansion we checked before. }
17. Bc2
17. b4
18. Ne2( { Now }18.Na4 { would be a bit useless, as ... Qa5  is one of our ideas. } )
18. h6{ This crazy position is the perfect example for the Benoni. }( { We make use of the  e2  knight as }19.Bxh6? { would run into }19...Rxe2! { and expel the bishop from the annoying pin +  h6  control. }( { If }19.Bf4 Bb7 { would allow us to pick up the  d5 -pawn and get a lot of presence in the center (to compensate our weak kingside). } )( { If }19.Bh4 Qa5! { would be great as well, with the same idea to tackle the  d5 -pawn. Following with ... Bb7  and even ... c4 -... c3 !  bxc3  ... Rc8 !, getting space, files, and diagonals for our pieces. You are playing the Benoni! You live by activity! } ) )
