1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. Bb5+{ The main move. White gives a very annoying check as we cannot answer it with the two logical options (... Bd7  and ... Nbd7 ), as the push  e4 - e5  will threaten the  f6 -knight and the ideal square to back up ( d7 ) is occupied.      I want to add here some thoughts. Thinking deeply about what was the reason why I succeeded so much with the Benoni I found an interesting approach. White has plenty of space and usually doesn't have a direct way to win.     Our opponent needs to keep the balance between our counterplay and keeping the pressure up. As long as we don't make a blunder in one, we usually have very few moves available. Or we try to develop and do the 2–3 plans (or  Bg4  or  a6 - b5  or some funky  f5 , that's it), or we die.     This involves risk, but also involves often having only one reasonable option as it is easier to say 'Well, this line I basically die against  e4 - e5 , this should be the move'. It's a defense that benefits a lot from surviving one more move and always has counterplay. You'll see how basically all our moves make direct sense (you see the outcome or plan very quickly) and often our opponents' are the 'engine moves' that make sense 5–6 moves later for a tactical motif.      It was the pet opening of a young Kasparov, and more recently Gashimov demonstrated how it was possible to play it at the highest level. Even the new generation played it as Abdusattorov and Rapport have tested it recently and many 2600+ like Pouya, Indjic and Pantsulaia play it quite often these days with good results.      After all this long introduction, I hope you are ready for some of the most enjoyable lines I've ever witnessed as a student, coach, and player! }
8. Nfd7{ A sad must. }( 8...Nbd7 { or }8...Bd7 { basically lose to }9.e5 { . Time ago, when computers weren't that good, it was a decent try as white needed to calculate quite a lot, but now if the opponent knows slightly what he's doing it would mean a quick and painless defeat.     There is some hope as well for black, as usually we plan to go for ... a6 , ... b5 . White needs to invest a tempo, preventing it (9. a4 ), retreating (9. Be2  and 9. Bd3 ) or allow us to expand with ... a6 , ... b5 . } )
9. a4{ As David Martinez says in his 1.  d4  course, Benoni is a Hebrew name that means son of my pain, which is quite a convenient way to talk about 9.  a4  variation. White gets ahead of our intents to expand with ... a6 -... b5  and leaves us with all the pieces gathered as if a toddler packed together all the toys in a box.     We are required to make sense of those pieces and, at the same time, be careful about White's attack in the center and the kingside. It has the fame of being the hardest line for a reason. }
9. O-O( 9...Qh4+ { is a very interesting try but both }10.Kf1 { and }10.g3 { are a real challenge to face as well. If I felt the mainline was a bit more shaky, I would've given it as an alternative, but I consider 9...  O-O  very reasonable and we create lots of chances for White to make a mistake. } )
10. Nf3
10. Na6{ We make use of the only drawback of this  Bb5 +- Ba4  idea, which is accessing to  b4  with the passive  b8 -knight. Usually, White plays  a2 - a4  only when black is threatening ... b5  with  a7 -... a6 , so here we see a smart workaround for black. Again, we keep prioritizing development. }
11. O-O{ The knight on  a6  shouldn't be captured at all. Remember, we have problems with space and also we want to open the queenside. Basically, white would make us a huge favor here.     In my 1.  d4  course, I recommend a line in the Benoni where we take on  c6 , but our focus is on the  d6 -pawn and basically changes the picture of the position. Here, White NEEDS to dominate and crush our counterplay. }
11. Nb4{ After getting this nice square for the knight we will follow up with ... a6  now, expelling the bishop, and depending on the different attacking plans White chooses we will react accordingly.     The knight looks very nice but also can have some issues related to being irrelevant and just 'covering air' so, for now, it is great but don't get too comfortable with it. }
12. h3{ White gets ahead of the ... Bg4  threat and enables an extra way to play. It has been recently used by Eirigaisi, and it is definitely one of the most challenging ones. }
12. a6
13. Bc4{ Now ... Nb6  followed by ... Bg4  is not possible, so we need to consider a different path. }
13. f5{ It is usually not too safe to play this move with the bishop already on  c4 , but on the other hand, we have a very nice 'free move' with ... Nb6  later on threatening directly the bishop, so we have everything under control. }
14. Ng5{ Looks like the most challenging threat. }
14. Nb6
15. Bb3
15. a5{ A great idea used by none other than Topalov! We prevent  a4 - a5 , and we will be always threatening ... c4  and ... Nd3  ideas. Usually, we would hate to prevent ourselves from playing  b7 -... b5 , but having the knight on  b6  makes it very hard to do, and we need to adapt! }
16. Be3
16. fxe4{ We want to follow with ... Nd3  or ... Bf5 . }( { Forcing  g2-g4  might come in handy to counterattack later on, even something like }17.Qd2 Bf5 18.g4 h6!?!?!? { might be an incredibly unbalanced, where we enjoy an excellent bishop on  g7  and White has all his minor pieces on awkward passive spots.  0-1   (46) Bareev,E (2726) -Topalov,V (2745) Dortmund 2002 . } )
