17. Qf6
18. Nxg7{ White claims that the long-term weakness of dark-squares will pay off. It is a very reasonable approach. I fear more the positions that have some midterm progress into them than the ones that require very precise and imaginative gameplay, we could lose without even allowing White to make a mistake! }
18. Nb6{ It feels great to counter such a nice idea with an intermediate move!  Be3  was coming, so we needed to play this move first instead. }( 18...Qxg7?! { even our God Indjic couldn't handle this position. }19.Be3 { now ... Nb6  is impossible, so we barely cannot move }19...b6 20.Nd5 Nxd5 21.Bxd5 { followed by  b4 ! And we are done on the dark-squares. White bishops are fantastic.  1-0   (51) Erigaisi,A (2689)-Indjic,A (2613) Abu Dhabi 2022 . }( 18...Kxg7 { has a similar outcome. } ) )
19. Be2{ White covers the  d3 -square, so we won't have an answer to  Be3 . }( 19.Bb3 Kxg7 20.Be3 Nd3 { here we can appreciate how everything changes if we add a couple of moves. We justify our beautiful  h7 - e4  pawn chain, and we hold on to the dark-squares. } )
19. Qd4+{ Again, we look forward to conquering the dark-squares. }
20. Qxd4
20. cxd4
21. a5{ Only move!, otherwise our center would flood White's position. I feel some people might be scared to take on  d4 , so 20.  Kh1  or 20.  Kh2  could be played. The key idea is that we will have access to the  d5 -square after taking on  g7  and White playing the usual  a4 - a5 . }
21. Kxg7( 21...Nd7 { allows }22.Ne6! { and we can resign. } )
22. axb6
22. dxc3
23. bxc3
23. Nd3
24. Bxd3
24. exd3{ I'd say this was one of the most challenging lines for black, but here we have a relatively easy opposite-squared bishop endgame to defend. }
25. Ra5{ This creative move allows white to play  Ba3  without closing the rook and also looks for  Re5  or  Rc5  ideas. }( 25.Rd1 { falls short against }25...Re8 { and the usual ... Bd7  and ... Rac8 , we might even catch a pawn on the way as white is a bit less coordinated. } )
25. Rd8
26. Ba3
26. Bd7{ We aim for ... Rac8 , ... Re8 ,  Kf7 ,  and I don't see a way for White to crack open our position as we are incredibly strong on light squares, and all the menacing pawns are well-blocked. }
