12. Re1{ ALL DONE The main move. White makes room for the bishop after a very useful job, annoying our optimal development. At the same time, the rook puts more pressure on the  e4 - e5  push. }
12. a6{ We kick the bishop as usual. Since we are aiming to follow up with ... Re8 , it doesn't make much sense to take any unnecessary risk pinning the  d7 -knight. }
13. Bf1
13. Re8{ Now White has 3 relevant moves. }( 14.h3 { gets ahead of our plan and prevents eventual ... Bg4 . }( 14.Be3 { to reroute the bishop through  f2  to  h4 . } )( 14.Bd2 { to just develop the last piece. } ) )
14. Bd2{ This move is incredibly smart and has been played recently by strong Grand Masters. White knows we want to play ... Nf6  and delays  h3  just in case we play it. In comparison to 14.  Be3  the  e4 -pawn is extra defended, so we have no threat that allows us to gain a tempo. We need to go for  f5 , but white did not spend a tempo with  h2 - h3 . }( { I highly recommend looking at }14.h3 { first, as everything would be more comprehensible in comparison, and I don't see the point of repeating White's ideas. } )
14. f5{ ... Nf6  followed by ... Rb8  could be an option, but I'd rather keep it simple and solve it the same way. }
15. Qb3{ The only critical line. }
15. fxe4
16. Nxe4
16. Nf6
17. Nxf6+
17. Bxf6
18. Rxe8+
18. Qxe8
19. Re1{ Thanks to the optimized move order, White seizes the open file and gets the  a1 -rook into action faster. }
19. Qd8
20. Ng5{ A common plan for white to seize the  e6  square. }( { In case of }20.Bc3 Bf5! { , and white doesn't have the  g2 - g4  follow-up in comparison to 14.  h3 . } )( 20.Bxb4 cxb4 21.Qxb4 { until here we followed our contemporary god in the Benoni and basically the only +2600 GM that plays it consistently nowadays }21...b5 { we just want to accelerate the development with  Bd7  or  Qb6 + opening the queenside and making the  a8  rook useful.     White would need to be very careful with the weak dark squares. }{ Indjic tried }21...Bg4 { but after }22.Ng5! Bxg5 23.fxg5 Qxg5 24.Qxd6 Rf8 25.Qg3! { the dust has settled and black faces a very bad endgame as we are left with the bad bishop.  1-0   (30) Zhou,J (2462)-Indjic,A (2643) Riga 2021 . } )
20. Bf5
21. Ne6
21. Qd7
22. Bxb4
22. cxb4
23. Qxb4
23. b5{ White has a nice knight on  e6 , but has very little control of the drak-squares. We will activate our rook and have good counterplay. Taking on  b5  would give us access through the  b -file. }
