12. Re1{ ALL DONE The main move. White makes room for the bishop after a very useful job, annoying our optimal development. At the same time, the rook puts more pressure on the  e4 - e5  push. }
12. a6{ We kick the bishop as usual. Since we are aiming to follow up with ... Re8 , it doesn't make much sense to take any unnecessary risk pinning the  d7 -knight. }
13. Bf1
13. Re8{ Now White has 3 relevant moves. }( 14.h3 { gets ahead of our plan and prevents eventual ... Bg4 . }( 14.Be3 { to reroute the bishop through  f2  to  h4 . } )( 14.Bd2 { to just develop the last piece. } ) )
14. h3{ This is the main old move. I faced it when I was twelve years old, and the oldest game is from 1970. }
14. f5{ White spent so many tempos to prevent our bishop from going to  g4 , and we are in time to break through the center. }( { I was about to write down that }14...Nf6 { is not great, since White can now play }15.Bc4 { (now that ... Nb6  followed by ... Bg4  is not a threat) and push for  e4 - e5 , but I realized that Black can 'tease' White with a move like }15...h6 { . The logical follow-up }16.e5 { runs into }16...Nd7! { and suddenly White cannot make any profit out of the intimidating center. If }17.e6 Nf6! { and Black is doing great (see how the  h6 -pawn covers the jump  Ng5 ). }( { In case of }17.Ne4 Nb6! 18.Nxd6 Nxc4 { and we will take on  d5  a move later with the Queen.      If White is a bit more patient with something like }{   }16.g4 { or even flexible moves like  Kh2  or  Bd2  we will eventually run out of teasing moves and end up playing ... Nd7  again. 🙂     I thought it was nice for you to be more wary of your opponent's intentions and try to play a bit around what your opponent wants to do! With that approach, I came out with tons of novelties and interesting ideas.  White has 5 different tries here but only 2 concerning ones. } ) )
15. exf5{ We weaken our kingside but take a look at White's pieces, how are both bishops and the  c3 -knight creating any kind of danger? On the other side, we take out White's intimidating center and get some valuable space for our pieces. }
15. Rxe1{ The key idea. White doesn't have a pleasant recapture. }
16. Qxe1( 16.Nxe1 gxf5 { from now on it is very easy. We just want to play ... Nf6 , ... Bd7  and look for  b7 -... b5  with the eventual  h7 -... h6  to prevent  Ng5 - Ne6  from happening. White doesn't have any appealing plans, and this has been very successful for Black in practice. } )
16. Nc2{ This line was extremely fascinating for me when I was just starting to play the Benoni with 12 y.o. It is not that bad technically, but the variations following are incredibly beautiful and definitely had an impact on my style. }
17. Qe6+
17. Kh8
18. Ng5{ White threatens  Nf7 + so we need to do something about it. }
18. Bd4+{ We make some room for the king before an interesting surprise. This is also a very common theme that you should pay attention to, sometimes this intermediate check can save the day! }
19. Kh1
19. Ne5{ Suddenly our opponent's Queen is trapped! }
20. fxe5{ I cannot describe how many hours of enjoyment this position gave me. Checking all the ideas on the board, admiring the coordination and fluency of White minor pieces and the three pawns.     Engines weren't that great at the moment, and mostly I did not care much about the evals (otherwise this course would've never happened. 😁 }
20. Bxe6
21. dxe6{ White is threatening  Nf7 + again, so we need to react. }
21. Qa5{ I know I'm sidetracking a bit here, Black is busted in many ways, but I wanted to show a line I remembered that left me in awe. }
22. Nf7+
22. Kg8
23. Nd5{ If I could give one thousand exclamation signs, I would. It's not about how great is the move it is about how it helped me admire the beauty of chess and maybe this was one of the most exciting and enjoyable lines I ever discovered messing around with a portable chessboard on my sofa after going to school. White just goes for the kill and doesn't care about the silly rook on  a1 . }
23. Nxa1
24. Bh6{ This position looks like a football match where the lineup is 1-1-9. Mate is coming. }
24. Qd8{ Only move. }
25. Nxd8{ White still threatens mate. }
25. Rxd8
26. f6{ How can I put into words the joy of a child trying this move and seeing that it works? }
26. Bxe5
27. f7+{ I wasn't really looking for the 'quickest mate' we are talking about beauty and symbolism here. 🙂 }
27. Kh8
28. e7{ Perfectly showcasing the power of the unstoppable pawns. The perfectly placed bishop on  h6  and knight on  d5 , both controlling dark weak squares on the pawn chain, makes it for me. The poor knight on  a1  felt like a lost crusader.     I don't think I ever saw material imbalances the same way after this cathartic experience. Well, sorry for the detour, but I hope you could FEEL the place of this defense in my heart, and it was fun for you. Let's get back to the theory! }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Benoni With 6.e4 & 7.f4"]
[Black "7.f4 with 8.Bb5+, 9.a4 and 12.Re1 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. f4{ Here we are. The most challenging line when we are playing the Benoni. Usually it's the reason people combine Nimzo-Indian and Benoni. }( { When white plays   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 { and here dodges the Nimzo with  Nf3  or  g3 , if we go for the Benoni with ... c5  here we directly avoid this line (and the rest of the lines without  Nf3  basically). White tries to get his central pawn majority going right away and already threatens  e4 - e5 . ¿Are you ready to fight? } )
7. Bg7( { Trying to be 'smart' with }7...a6 { would only lead to pain and misery after }8.e5 { and White is not even forced to sacrifice the pawn as after 7... Bg7 .  Nf3  would follow and white will be able to keep up with a flashy center and an easy follow-up with  Bc4  and  O-O . } )
8. Bb5+{ The main move. White gives a very annoying check as we cannot answer it with the two logical options (... Bd7  and ... Nbd7 ), as the push  e4 - e5  will threaten the  f6 -knight and the ideal square to back up ( d7 ) is occupied.      I want to add here some thoughts. Thinking deeply about what was the reason why I succeeded so much with the Benoni I found an interesting approach. White has plenty of space and usually doesn't have a direct way to win.     Our opponent needs to keep the balance between our counterplay and keeping the pressure up. As long as we don't make a blunder in one, we usually have very few moves available. Or we try to develop and do the 2–3 plans (or  Bg4  or  a6 - b5  or some funky  f5 , that's it), or we die.     This involves risk, but also involves often having only one reasonable option as it is easier to say 'Well, this line I basically die against  e4 - e5 , this should be the move'. It's a defense that benefits a lot from surviving one more move and always has counterplay. You'll see how basically all our moves make direct sense (you see the outcome or plan very quickly) and often our opponents' are the 'engine moves' that make sense 5–6 moves later for a tactical motif.      It was the pet opening of a young Kasparov, and more recently Gashimov demonstrated how it was possible to play it at the highest level. Even the new generation played it as Abdusattorov and Rapport have tested it recently and many 2600+ like Pouya, Indjic and Pantsulaia play it quite often these days with good results.      After all this long introduction, I hope you are ready for some of the most enjoyable lines I've ever witnessed as a student, coach, and player! }
8. Nfd7{ A sad must. }( 8...Nbd7 { or }8...Bd7 { basically lose to }9.e5 { . Time ago, when computers weren't that good, it was a decent try as white needed to calculate quite a lot, but now if the opponent knows slightly what he's doing it would mean a quick and painless defeat.     There is some hope as well for black, as usually we plan to go for ... a6 , ... b5 . White needs to invest a tempo, preventing it (9. a4 ), retreating (9. Be2  and 9. Bd3 ) or allow us to expand with ... a6 , ... b5 . } )
9. a4{ As David Martinez says in his 1.  d4  course, Benoni is a Hebrew name that means son of my pain, which is quite a convenient way to talk about 9.  a4  variation. White gets ahead of our intents to expand with ... a6 -... b5  and leaves us with all the pieces gathered as if a toddler packed together all the toys in a box.     We are required to make sense of those pieces and, at the same time, be careful about White's attack in the center and the kingside. It has the fame of being the hardest line for a reason. }
9. O-O( 9...Qh4+ { is a very interesting try but both }10.Kf1 { and }10.g3 { are a real challenge to face as well. If I felt the mainline was a bit more shaky, I would've given it as an alternative, but I consider 9...  O-O  very reasonable and we create lots of chances for White to make a mistake. } )
10. Nf3
10. Na6{ We make use of the only drawback of this  Bb5 +- Ba4  idea, which is accessing to  b4  with the passive  b8 -knight. Usually, White plays  a2 - a4  only when black is threatening ... b5  with  a7 -... a6 , so here we see a smart workaround for black. Again, we keep prioritizing development. }
11. O-O{ The knight on  a6  shouldn't be captured at all. Remember, we have problems with space and also we want to open the queenside. Basically, white would make us a huge favor here.     In my 1.  d4  course, I recommend a line in the Benoni where we take on  c6 , but our focus is on the  d6 -pawn and basically changes the picture of the position. Here, White NEEDS to dominate and crush our counterplay. }
11. Nb4{ After getting this nice square for the knight we will follow up with ... a6  now, expelling the bishop, and depending on the different attacking plans White chooses we will react accordingly.     The knight looks very nice but also can have some issues related to being irrelevant and just 'covering air' so, for now, it is great but don't get too comfortable with it. }
12. Re1{ ALL DONE The main move. White makes room for the bishop after a very useful job, annoying our optimal development. At the same time, the rook puts more pressure on the  e4 - e5  push. }
12. a6{ We kick the bishop as usual. Since we are aiming to follow up with ... Re8 , it doesn't make much sense to take any unnecessary risk pinning the  d7 -knight. }
13. Bf1
13. Re8{ Now White has 3 relevant moves. }( 14.h3 { gets ahead of our plan and prevents eventual ... Bg4 . }( 14.Be3 { to reroute the bishop through  f2  to  h4 . } )( 14.Bd2 { to just develop the last piece. } ) )
14. h3{ This is the main old move. I faced it when I was twelve years old, and the oldest game is from 1970. }
14. f5{ White spent so many tempos to prevent our bishop from going to  g4 , and we are in time to break through the center. }( { I was about to write down that }14...Nf6 { is not great, since White can now play }15.Bc4 { (now that ... Nb6  followed by ... Bg4  is not a threat) and push for  e4 - e5 , but I realized that Black can 'tease' White with a move like }15...h6 { . The logical follow-up }16.e5 { runs into }16...Nd7! { and suddenly White cannot make any profit out of the intimidating center. If }17.e6 Nf6! { and Black is doing great (see how the  h6 -pawn covers the jump  Ng5 ). }( { In case of }17.Ne4 Nb6! 18.Nxd6 Nxc4 { and we will take on  d5  a move later with the Queen.      If White is a bit more patient with something like }{   }16.g4 { or even flexible moves like  Kh2  or  Bd2  we will eventually run out of teasing moves and end up playing ... Nd7  again. 🙂     I thought it was nice for you to be more wary of your opponent's intentions and try to play a bit around what your opponent wants to do! With that approach, I came out with tons of novelties and interesting ideas.  White has 5 different tries here but only 2 concerning ones. } ) )
15. exf5{ We weaken our kingside but take a look at White's pieces, how are both bishops and the  c3 -knight creating any kind of danger? On the other side, we take out White's intimidating center and get some valuable space for our pieces. }
15. Rxe1{ The key idea. White doesn't have a pleasant recapture. }
16. Qxe1( 16.Nxe1 gxf5 { from now on it is very easy. We just want to play ... Nf6 , ... Bd7  and look for  b7 -... b5  with the eventual  h7 -... h6  to prevent  Ng5 - Ne6  from happening. White doesn't have any appealing plans, and this has been very successful for Black in practice. } )
16. Nf6{ We prevent  Qe6 + and now ... Nc2  is a very demanding threat. White would need to tackle it, and we will happily take on  f5 , completing the development and having a great position. It is not common to see a correspondence game where black wins!:  0-1   (35) Helman,B (2090)-Dimov,D (2422) ICCF email 2015 . }
