15. Bd2{ This is the 'correspondence' move. I wouldn't say it is necessary to know all this in practice, but for the sake of completeness it should be checked and humans have already tested it. White 'calmly' develops a piece and practices stoicism to control the impulses to play  e5  or  exf5  or  Ng5 . }
15. fxe4
16. Nxe4
16. Nf6{ We keep developing. }
17. Nxf6+( 17.Neg5 { is a tricky idea. Taking on  d5  would mean a certain death after  Bc4 , we cannot defend the diagonal properly }17...Rxe1! { we make good use of the ... Nc2  idea, White needs to take with the bishop }18.Bxe1 h6! { we force the matters }19.Ne6 Bxe6 20.dxe6 d5! { we regain presence on the light squares and our center is pretty stable. The  e6 -passed pawn cannot do much on its own. } )
17. Bxf6
18. Qb3{ White keeps prioritizing development and tries to bring the  a1  rook quickly. If we are not careful, we will regret having the  a8 -rook still unused.  Bc3  is also a threat, exchanging our best piece, so we want to take immediate action. }
18. Rxe1
19. Rxe1
19. Bf5
20. g4{ A very risky move that relies on breaking the coordination between our  Nb4  and  Bf5 , which often causes us trouble due to lack of moves. }( { In the case of }20.Bc3 { we can admire the usefulness of  Bf5  after }20...b5! 21.axb5 axb5 { and White would not be able to take on  b5  as }22.Bxb5 Bc2! { , keeps the balance and would put our opponent into trouble. } )
20. Bd7
21. Ng5{ This has been the choice of a recent correspondence game. Again I emphasize all these lines should be used as an example of dynamics and for the sake of completeness, don't invest too much time here while other more relevant variations are waiting for you to be checked for the first time. White plans to invade the  e6 -square. }
21. Qa5{ Now that we are not tied to the defense of the  Bf6 , we can mess with black pressuring the  a4 -pawn. Dramatically weakening the dark-squares with ... Bxg5  doesn't look very appealing. }
22. Ra1
22. b5{ We use the pin to increase the pressure. }
23. Qg3{ White looks to attack the unattended kingside. }
23. Qd8{ After achieving the expansion on the queenside and making White misplace the rook, we come back with the feeling of a job well done. }( { We deviate from the correspondence game that resulted in a win for white after }23...bxa4 24.f5! {  1-0   (33) Bussoli,M (1800)-Bertrand,F  (1800) FICGS email 2021 . } )
24. Ne6
24. Bxe6
25. dxe6
25. Bxb2
26. Re1
26. Qe7{ We blocked the passed pawn, and we have excellent control of the dark squares. From this point forward, I find it very hard for white to crack our solid position. }
