13. Bxd7{ White has a very unusual idea. But considering most of the pawn chain is on white squares, it makes sense to exchange this 'pawn-ish' bishop for good and deprive us of the soothing ... Ne5  jump. Navara played it recently but lost with white. }
13. Bxd7{ We threaten the  f5 -pawn now, as white has fewer pieces to attack our king, and we are close to being fully developed. Also,  b7 -... b5  is obviously a way to go. }
14. Bg5
14. f6{ This move is somewhat of a sin for a Benoni player. We close the diagonal of our beloved  g7 -bishop in exchange for the juicy  f5 -pawn and the suddenly weak light squares, especially in the  b1 - h7  diagonal.     It's important as well to pay attention to both White's knights. We are about to open the position, and they are not really on the most menacing squares and have few jumps or harmony with the pawn structure. }( { Compare it with having them on  c4  and  f4 , for instance: }14...Bf6 { would mean trouble after simply }15.Qd2 { followed by  Rae1  and white is close to winning, and it is a great example of how the  b4 -knight can get out of place. We close the bishop, but we also need to consider that the bishop on  g7  is the only piece defending the King for now. } )
15. Bf4{ This move, pressuring  d6 , has been played every one of the 20 times this position arises, even by Kasparov!. }( { I wanted to give a brief note about }15.Bh4!? { . I found this rather obvious novelty, and I was a bit surprised, not even played in correspondence games. If we take on  f5  with }15...gxf5 { white plans to play }16.e5! { and thanks to the pin on the  f6 -pawn, we suddenly have both bishops closed. I wouldn't be the end of the world as something like }16...dxe5 17.Nxe5 Qe8!? { and we will look for  f5 - f4  push to free our bishop/s. } )
15. gxf5{ Again, we want to open the position asap. }
16. Nd2{ This has been played in correspondence. White wants to recapture the  e -pawn with the knight and collect the  d6 -pawn. I don't think it is very threatening, as our usual way to play solves quickly the position. Can you guess how we should proceed? }
16. fxe4
17. Ndxe4
17. f5{ Obviously! We open the  g7  bishop! }
18. Nxd6
18. b5{ We look for ... c4  and ... Nd3  as always, and white cannot really afford to take on  b5  without losing the  d5 -pawn. I really like how the Benoni always falls down to activity ideas and patterns and can highly increase your ability to swim across storms on the chessboard.     The game followed with some simplifications, but Black didn't even suffer, as is usual in correspondence chess.  ½-½   (33) Moreto Quintana,A (2286)-Bulgarini Torre,M (2256) ICCF email 2017 . }
