11. Nb4{ After getting this nice square for the knight we will follow up with ... a6  now, expelling the bishop, and depending on the different attacking plans White chooses we will react accordingly.     The knight looks very nice but also can have some issues related to being irrelevant and just 'covering air' so, for now, it is great but don't get too comfortable with it. }
12. Be3{ This David Martínez suggestion in LTR 1.d4 series he has. He's been a successful coach (for instance David Anton's years ago), and he definitely is known for being quite good with the space bar as we would say jokingly. 😜    With this move, White wants to accelerate  Bf2 - Bh4  and try to be also in time to prevent an eventual ... Bg4 . This move order requires us to be somewhat smart to deal with it. }
12. a6{ It feels great to use the same approach against every line. }( { After }12...Re8 13.Bf2 a6 14.Be2 f5!? 15.e5! { gets into a sweet spot for White, as we will be required to play under incredible pressure. I took the time to analyze it all the way and I felt too unreliable, and suddenly we were in the driver's seat having to block too many punches. } )
13. Bc4
13. Re8{ We both threat ... Nf6  and ... Nb6 . }( 13...Nb6 { followed by ... Bg4  was also decently fine. } )
14. Bf2
14. Nb6{ We use the threat on the bishop to develop our bishop, as usual. }
15. Nd2{ This setup allows this peculiar defense to challenge the patterns we know. What to do, know? If we take the bishop, the knight would have a pleasant square on  c4 , and we have no way to expel it from the altar. We have to bear in mind that now  a5 !, is a decent threat for white as we have no intention to take on  c4  nor an option to free the  c8 -bishop. }
15. Bd7{ We finally develop the bishop, and we want to play ... a6 -... a5  mostly to prevent White doing it whenever needed as the knight on  b6  is in a tricky spot, not being able to go back to  d7 . Once we consolidated the queenside we then looked for ... f5 , as White has less presence on the center due to  Nd2 . }( 15...f5?! { might sound reasonable, but White has some insane coordination with }16.e5! dxe5 17.fxe5 Bxe5 18.a5! Nxc4 19.Nxc4 Bxc3 20.bxc3 Nxd5 21.Qf3!+- { and we happen to be losing thanks to our weak dark-squares and exposed pieces in the center. It also shows how hard it is for White to justify his moves, as usually the way to win involves some degree of creativity and control over the board.     Many times it happened I won a game and someone told me 'Oh you were losing' and I'm like 'What? How? When?' and it was usually a sequence of active moves, now positional, now subtle. The key idea behind all this is to pay attention to White's forced ideas every move  (like  e4 - e5  or  f4 - f5 ) and if those are not obviously winning, we should be more than happy. } )
16. a5
16. Nxc4
17. Nxc4
17. Bb5{ All our minor pieces combine perfectly, and we will seize control of the center. }
