13. Be2{ This is the best move. White gives room for the knight on  c4  and also looks forward to playing  Bf2 - Bh4 . All this without spending a tempo on  h3  or  Re1 .     Let's evaluate our options now.      1 . If we go for ... Re8 , ... Nf6  to free the  c8 -bishop, white is in time to play  Bf2 ,  Nd2  and basically freezes all our counterplay, and  Bh4  or  Bg3  ideas are coming. }( {  2 . If we go for }13...f5 14.e5! { and we won't be able to recapture everything on  e5  as  Bxc5 !, awaits at the end taking advantage of the exposed  b4 -knight.      3 . Maybe we are in time for  b7 -... b5  then. } )
13. Nf6
14. Nd2{ Otherwise ... Bg4  would follow. }
14. Rb8{ We look for counterplay as White is playing a more controlled approach to the center. }
15. Bf2{ White finally looks for re-routing the bishop. }
15. b5
16. axb5
16. axb5
17. Nxb5( 17.Bh4 Qe8! { we unpin ourselves, prevent  e5  and defend  b5  in one move! Now we just want to follow up with ... c4 , ... Bd7  and  Ra8 . } )( 17.Bxb5?! Ng4 { white can easily regret trying to outsmart us, not playing  h3 . Now ... Nxf2  and ... Bd4  are a huge threat, and we are also looking for ... Bxc3  as the  b5 -bishop is loose. } )
17. Ba6{ Developing this bishop in the Benoni feels like when you're attending your descendant's graduation and realizing all the effort and suffering involved was worth it. }
18. Nc3
18. Bxe2
19. Qxe2
19. Nh5{ We open the  g7 -bishop, prevent  Bh4  and will follow with ... Nc2 -... Nd4 . Suddenly, the good-looking knight on  b4  got a main role in a Hollywood movie. We have pressure through the  b -file and might look for  f7 -... f5  later on to gain more presence in light squares. }
