13. Nf6
14. Nd2{ Otherwise ... Bg4  would follow. }
14. Rb8{ We look for counterplay as White is playing a more controlled approach to the center. }
15. a5{ Typical move to disrupt our pawn chain. We get to use the  b -file, so it also implies a concession. In general, it is a great idea when  Nc4  is available for White, as we would lose some tempos if we take with a major piece on  b6 . }
15. Re8{ We threaten ... Nfxd5  before going for  b7 -... b5 , maybe we catch someone off guard! }
16. Bf2
16. b5
17. axb6
17. Nd7{ We prevent  Bh4 , and we look for ... Nxb6  and then  f7 -... f5 . We can also include  h7 -... h6  to prevent the annoying  Ng5 - Ne6  ideas. Sometimes White can press forward with  e4 - e5  but can also be happy just 'letting it happen' and playing ... Bb7  and ... Kh7  to just hold it there, and it is not so easy to see a path forward for White, and the  d5  pawn is basically lost and will need to be justified.      Another approach would be to play ... Nxb6  and look for ... a5 , ... Ba6  and exchange the annoying  c8 -bishop, and we have an excellent placement of all our pieces then. Some details can be appreciated as if white starts with  h3  or  Nf3  has substantial differences as in the first case it still allows the  Nc4  idea so  Qxb6  is out of the equation.      Overall our play is very healthy and based on coordination and small ideas(exchanging our worst piece, preventing jumps, thinning the center), while White's play is based on finding the best move every move, so it is far less consistent. After reading what I wrote, I felt like, 'That's a good summary of the Benoni!' }
