15. Kh1{ We are still on Divis territory. If you ask, 'Why  Kh1 ? And why now?' it is hard to give any explanation more than 'our God and savior Stockfish has seen all the infinite futures, so it says so'. }
15. Re8{ I suggest this idea to change the course of the action. We can make some syllogisms here:      1 . White reached here because he knows it is one of the best according to the engine, not because of casual gameplay. It would be like getting stranded on the sea and magically appearing on Cocoa Island (yeah Google... I mean, Bing for it, you'll see). }( {  2 . It is quite likely that our opponent still knows how the mainline goes after }15...b5 16.axb5 axb5 17.Bg1! { , followed by  Ra7 .      3 . Then we can assume our opponent can be well-prepared, so maybe a different approach can help. For now, we threaten the  d5 -pawn, so our opponent needs to move the bishop. } )
16. Bf2{ White looks for  Bh4  and  e4 - e5  later on. }( 16.Bg1 { White might try to play the same way as against  b5  }16...b6 { again we look for ... Bd7 , ... b5  and the bishop on  g1  doesn't make much sense if the position is not open yet. Funnily enough,  Bf2  might be the best move, so we can easily transpose. } )
16. b5{ Since in the mainline white doesn't take on  b5 , here we force him basically. We want to give up a pawn to finally free the  d7 -bishop. }( { If we tried }16...b6 17.Bh4 { would be certainly annoying here. } )
17. axb5
17. axb5
18. Bh4
18. c4{ We achieved a lot on the queenside. Admire how the  Be2  and  Nd2  are severely limited, and how the  d3 -square is always a worry for white. }( { Another key factor here is that }19.b3 { is not a sensible threat to free all the minor pieces and challenge the  a6 -knight as }19...Nxe4!! { would be an insanely pleasant move to play. } )( { Honorable mention to }18...Qd7 { as it is a very healthy move as well. } )
19. e5{ Always check for  e5 . }
19. dxe5
20. fxe5
20. Rxe5
21. Bg3
21. Nd7{ White might gain an exchange for a pawn, but we are left with great minor pieces and the once famous White pawn center is gone.     The knight on  c3  and the bishop on  e2  are a bit out of place dynamically, and we can pressure quite well through the dark-squares combined with the ... b5 , ... c4  pawn chain. .... Qb6  and ... Re8  looks like a decent follow-up in general. }
