[White "2) Benoni With 6.e4, 7.h3, 8.Nf3 & 9.Bd3"]
[Black "7.h3, 8.Nf3 and 9.Bd3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. h3{ White prevents any ... Bg4  idea and just wants to develop peacefully. }
7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. Bd3{ I played this setup maybe 30 times, counting White and Black games. White has a very safe center, and the  c8 -bishop doesn't have an exit. Following it up with  O-O  and  Bf4  to have permanent pressure on  d6  is usually how it goes. }
9. b5{ The most direct and practical chance. We put into good use being castled fast, and White is one move short. I have plenty of games with ... a6 ,  a4 , and then ... Nh5  ideas, but I feel it was just pain and misery overall. White develops peacefully, and we have the  c8 -bishop stuck for a while without much chance to escape.      It is widely known as the best answer for black, and it is also the most played one. Now White can take on  b5  with both pieces, and we have different resources through the  e -file and with  Qa5 +. }
10. Bxb5{ I'd say this is quite harmless. }
10. Nxe4{ We'll recover the piece soon enough. }
11. Nxe4
11. Qa5+{ We recover the piece, and we put White into some trouble with castling. }
12. Nfd2{ The only reasonable chance. White puts his eyes on the  d6  pawn and the  c4  square to reroute the knight and castle short. }
12. Qxb5
13. Nxd6
13. Qa6
14. N2c4{ Only move to castle soon enough. }
14. Nd7{ Black needs to react quickly and eliminate both White knights. We have some pressure through the  h8 - a1  diagonal and through the  a  and  b files, so we focus now on eliminating the most active pieces. }( 14...Rd8 15.Bf4 { would only make it worse for black. } )
15. Bg5{ This is somewhat of a novelty, but not that stupid, as  Be7  is a serious threat. }
15. Ne5
16. Rc1
16. Nxc4
17. Nxc4
17. h6{ Now we force White to choose. }( { If }18.Be7 Re8 19.d6 { we just regain the pawn with  Be6 - Bf8 . } )( { If }18.Be3 Qxa2 { and  Ba6 - Rfb8  is a serious continuation to keep up with the pressure while we are not even a pawn down anymore. } )
