15. O-O
15. Ne5( { It's better than }15...Nb6 { as we prefer to keep the queen on  a6  to pressure  a2  as well as  b2 . } )
16. Nxe5
16. Qxd6( { Better than }16...Bxe5 17.Ne4! { because after  Nc3 , White can be decently happy with the extra pawn for now, as everything is well defended. } )
17. Nc4
17. Qa6{ We head back to our beloved square, allowing rooks and minor pieces to come into play. }
18. Qb3( { In case of }18.Qe2 Bb7! 19.Rd1 Bd4 { would be a quick way to recover the pawn, and claim full equality. } )( 18.Ne3 Rb8 { we are not really threatening ... Bxb2 , as we don't want to be left with the  c8 -bishop. What we are asking is, 'What's your next move?'.     The  a1 -rook cannot move, nor the  c1 -bishop and the  e3 -knight is on a passive schedule. Following with  h7 - h5  to reduce even further the mobility of White pieces, in this case, ... Ng4  idea and then just ... Re8 , ... Bd7  would be incredibly annoying for White, as there is no senseful plan even with a pawn up. } )
18. Bb7
19. Rd1( 19.Nd6!? Qxd6 20.Qxb7 c4 { and we want to thank White for the effort to exchange our worst piece. Suddenly, the pressure on  b2  and the queenside is mounting up for White, who might get into serious trouble soon. } )
19. Bd4
20. Ne3
20. Rfd8{ We'll retake the  d5 -pawn eventually, where the pressure through the  b -file would be unbearable. We are the ones pressuring, and some moves like  f7 - f5  and  a5 - a4  might put White under so much pressure.  1/2-1/2   (23) Neuer,T (2425)-Eschenko,V ICCF email 2007 . }
