6. g6( { In this chapter, we are gonna talk about }7.f3 { , }7.Nge2 { and }7.Bd3 { . Often they have similar patterns and positions, so we can put them all together.     Some key general ideas might be:     1 . White usually wants to secure the  e4 -pawn and negate any chance of development for the  c8 -bishop. -> Therefore, our go-to play is ... a6 , ... Rb8 , ... b5  after developing the knight.     2 . White is likely to reallocate the  g1 -knight to  f2  via  h3  or to  g3  via  e2 . -> So we often delay ... Nbd7  to dodge the first one and play  h7 -... h5  to annoy the second one.     3 . As a final touch, some tricks will be needed to know like  Nxe4 !, and  Qh4 +! It will make sense eventually, trust me. 🙂    Well, I only knew these general ideas when I was playing it, so maybe you can try to just get this simple knowledge and play some blitz games in this line or ask a friend to test it out and see how it goes. I highly encourage a lot of practice and 'sense' of the position, since we often do the same plans and ideas against every variation.    Finally, we'll see some model games as well to properly assess the feeling of these kinds of systems. } )
7. f3{ White reinforces the center and prepares to press through the  c1 - h6  diagonal. Usually white will face some issues to develop properly his kingside as both the knight and the bishop will be developed through  e2 . If white develops the bishop through  d3 , it would be weak to an eventual ... Nbd7 -... Ne5 , aiming to exchange a couple of pieces, which usually makes us pretty happy.     This Benoni is often a byproduct from the 3. f3  Grunfeld or even, to a lesser extent, the 5.  f3  Kings Indian. I even entered this Benoni through the King's Indian Defense (even if I don't play it a lot), so it is quite a popular outcome. }
7. Bg7
8. Be3
8. a6{ Maybe this move order is more efficient. }
9. a4
9. O-O
10. Qd2
10. Re8
11. Nge2( 11.Be2 h5 { transposes to the mainline. } )( { Now }11.Bc4 { would be absurd as the  h6 -pawn is not hanging as in  Ding - Carlsen  so ... Nbd7 -... Ne5  would be amazingly good. } )
11. Nbd7
12. Nc1
12. Ne5
13. Be2{ If we compare it to the mainline, we cannot play  g5  now! But we have a different approach available. }
13. Nh5
14. O-O
14. f5{ We prevent any massive influx of pawns on the kingside (like  g4 - g5 - f4 ), and we will keep up with our usual plan to push for ... b5 . }
15. f4( 15.exf5 { we can just take with the  g -pawn and enjoy how we thinned white's menacing center. But also }15...Bxf5 16.g4 Nxg4! 17.fxg4 Rxe3! { is an insane resource.     The rook cannot be captured as we have ... Bd4  winning the queen so White needs to choose which piece to take, but after ... Bd4  the king will perish soon enough as ... Qh4  will follow and mate would be quite likely. Remember, White has a useless rook on  a1  and both knights cannot access the kingside easily to defend. } )
15. Ng4
16. Bxg4
16. fxg4
17. N1e2
17. b6{ Since we have less presence in the center without the  f -pawn, it is wiser to reroute the rooks to the center through the 7th rank with style and later on look for ... b6 -... b5 , as White doesn't have any reasonable active plan.     Black won a very nice game in  0-1   (36) Agafii,V (2259)-Macovei,A (2454) Kishinev 2022 . }
