5. d6
6. e4
6. g6( { In this chapter, we are gonna talk about }7.f3 { , }7.Nge2 { and }7.Bd3 { . Often they have similar patterns and positions, so we can put them all together.     Some key general ideas might be:     1 . White usually wants to secure the  e4 -pawn and negate any chance of development for the  c8 -bishop. -> Therefore, our go-to play is ... a6 , ... Rb8 , ... b5  after developing the knight.     2 . White is likely to reallocate the  g1 -knight to  f2  via  h3  or to  g3  via  e2 . -> So we often delay ... Nbd7  to dodge the first one and play  h7 -... h5  to annoy the second one.     3 . As a final touch, some tricks will be needed to know like  Nxe4 !, and  Qh4 +! It will make sense eventually, trust me. 🙂    Well, I only knew these general ideas when I was playing it, so maybe you can try to just get this simple knowledge and play some blitz games in this line or ask a friend to test it out and see how it goes. I highly encourage a lot of practice and 'sense' of the position, since we often do the same plans and ideas against every variation.    Finally, we'll see some model games as well to properly assess the feeling of these kinds of systems. } )
7. f3{ White reinforces the center and prepares to press through the  c1 - h6  diagonal. Usually white will face some issues to develop properly his kingside as both the knight and the bishop will be developed through  e2 . If white develops the bishop through  d3 , it would be weak to an eventual ... Nbd7 -... Ne5 , aiming to exchange a couple of pieces, which usually makes us pretty happy.     This Benoni is often a byproduct from the 3. f3  Grunfeld or even, to a lesser extent, the 5.  f3  Kings Indian. I even entered this Benoni through the King's Indian Defense (even if I don't play it a lot), so it is quite a popular outcome. }
7. Bg7
8. Nge2{ Against this precise move order, I prefer a different way than the usual  a7 -... a6 . The reasoning behind it will be shown by comparison. This move order is a bit smarter in my honest opinion for white, as trying to fix the strange development in the kingside first feels more organic and logical but still a downgrade from 7.  Nge2 , as  f2 - f3  is not really achieving much yet. Usually, you get this position from the 3.  f3  Grunfeld, as black shifts to a Benoni with  c7 -... c5  instead of the usual  d7 -... d5 . }( { Since White already committed to  f3  starting with }8...h5 { allows too many extra moves, like }9.Bg5!? { (followed by  Nc1 - Be2 ) and even }9.Nf4 { is a safe spot for White to develop the knight for now, and the  h5 -pawn doesn't make that much sense. We are happy to face them against 7.  Nge2 , but since committed to  f2 - f3 , we can get much better positions. You see immediately the benefit of delaying  Be3 ( Bg5 )- Qd2  ideas. } )
8. Nbd7{ Against this White's move order, we get a specific benefit from delaying ... a6 - a4 . It will be easier for you to see later on, and we basically force 9.  Ng3 , so it is far simpler. }
9. Ng3
9. h5{ Immediately we want to challenge the  g3 -knight as it is usual. }
10. Be2{ White doesn't really prevent ... h5 -... h4  but frees the  f1 -square, so the knight can be rerouted. }
10. Nh7{ The main idea for black. }( { Preventing }10...O-O?! 11.Bg5! { and ... h5 -... h4  is not possible anymore. }( 10...h4 { and then going for a quick ... a6 , ... Rb8  is also interesting, but it is a lot about precision and I feel ... Nh7  is smarter and more precise. Later on, we want to go for  f7 -... f5  to thin White's pawn center and to get ahead of the eventual  f3 - f4  push that will come. } ) )
11. Nf1{ White plays it smarter and says: Why wait for Black to kick me when I can move it directly? Ding and Cheparinov are our main guests here. }
11. O-O
12. Ne3{ Now it is not clear how we need to play. We cannot go for ... a6 -... b5  plan easily, as we would need to have a knight on  e5 , so we can play ... Bd7  buuuuuuut White is really well-prepared to play  f3 - f4  against it. You can appreciate how smart White needs to be in order to prevent us from creating simple counterplay effectively. }
12. Qh4+{ This specific maneuver weakens a bit the Kingside, and it has already been tested with success in correspondence games. It is a pretty common theme in the Benoni, mostly seen in the  f4 +Bb5+ line. }
13. g3
13. Qe7
14. a4{ Again we find Ding!, and we can see another prophylactic idea. }( { Against }14.O-O { we had the typical break }14...f5! { with the idea to take on  e4  and go for ... Ne5 , ... Bd7 , ... Rae8  and finish all the development. White wants to play }15.exf5 { to crack our pawn structure, but we have the sweet }15...Bd4! { , pin, and while White defends the knight we will be able to retake on  f5  with the rook, keeping our pawn structure safe and sound. } )( 14.O-O f5 15.Nc4 Ne5 { now imagine  a6  and  a4  included. White would have  Nb6 !, and we would be much worse! It can be hard to remember all the orders, but in this chapter, we are pushing for great positions, so it is worth it. } )
14. f5{ Grischuk didn't know this precise idea. Again, remember that we don't want to just retake on  f5  with the pawn. It weakens our pawn structure, blocks the  f -file and also blocks our  c8 -bishop.  1-0   (77) Ding, L (2812)-Grischuk,A (2771) Shamkir 2019 . }
15. exf5
15. Bd4{ A sweet intermediate move. }
16. Qd2( 16.Nc2 { also runs into }16...Ne5 { while }16.Nc4 { we just can go for }16...Rxf5 { and we are more than happy. } )
16. Ne5{ Here we see how important it was to include ... Qh4 + so the  f3  pawn is weaker. }
17. f4( 17.fxg6 Ng5 { and White should resign as ... Nxf3  is coming. } )
17. Ng4
18. Nxg4
18. hxg4
19. fxg6
19. Nf6{ A single pawn completely shuts down the 4 pawns for White. Castle is not possible yet for White, and we are threatening ... Bf5  or ... Ne4  to increase the pressure on the exposed King and the lack of coordination for White. }
20. Qc2{ White covers our entry. }
20. Re8{ Now ... Bf5  is a serious threat as it cannot be taken due to ... Bxc3 + and ... Qxe2 ++. }
21. Bd2{ Only move to avoid resigning. }
21. Bxc3
22. Bxc3
22. Bf5
23. Bxf6
23. Qxf6{ We have excellent compensation, as White cannot do much with his 3 kingside pawns. We will try to make use of the  e -file with ... Re4 !, as it also allows us to go for ... Rb4  and pressure the queenside. }
