10. Nh7{ The main idea for black. }( { Preventing }10...O-O?! 11.Bg5! { and ... h5 -... h4  is not possible anymore. }( 10...h4 { and then going for a quick ... a6 , ... Rb8  is also interesting, but it is a lot about precision and I feel ... Nh7  is smarter and more precise. Later on, we want to go for  f7 -... f5  to thin White's pawn center and to get ahead of the eventual  f3 - f4  push that will come. } ) )
11. Be3( { An important trick about }Nh7 { is preventing the obvious follow-up }11.O-O? { as }11...Bd4+! 12.Kh1 h4! { and the knight would be funnily trapped on  g3 !. So with 11.  Be3  White wants to castle but loses all the flexibility. } )
11. h4{ We have some famous names like Gawain Jones and Li Chao for black. Now, White doesn't have  Nf1 - Ne3  idea but can go for  Nf1 - Nd2 , so it still makes sense. }
12. Nf1
12. O-O
13. Nd2
13. f5{ We want to immediately challenge our opponent. Here, we also can see how adding ... Nh7 ,  Be3  creates a huge difference. Our main strategic threat is to go for ... f4 , ... h3  and then use the incredible  e5 -square. }
14. O-O
14. f4
15. Bf2
15. h3{ Very important! Otherwise, white could close the kingside with  h2 - h3 , and it would definitely be harder to crack. }
16. g3
16. g5{ You can admire how the signaled minor pieces are completely countered by our pawn chain. We eventually want to pressure through the queenside, as always, while we have some perennial threats on the kingside with the  h3 -pawn and our strong  e5 -knight. }
