13. Bxh6{ Now it is a bit more interesting. A very good habit you should have is to free yourself from previous conclusions in complicated positions.     One subtle change can create a domino-effect and change completely the outcome of a 'trick that makes X move impossible'. In defenses like the Benoni it is specially required to be checking constantly and asking yourself 'OKAY OKAY BUT WHAT IF WE DO THIS NOW'. }
13. Nxe4
14. Nxe4
14. Qh4+
15. g3
15. Qxh6
16. Qxh6
16. Bxh6{ The inclusion of  Ne2  and ... Nd7  leaves the  e4 -knight free to move and not pinned to the king. How lucky are we that we prevented  Nf6 +! 🙂 }
17. Nxd6
17. Re5{ The  d5 -pawn will fall and we are doing great! }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Benoni With 6.e4 - Other 7th Move Options I"]
[Black "7.f3 and 8.Bg5 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6( { In this chapter, we are gonna talk about }7.f3 { , }7.Nge2 { and }7.Bd3 { . Often they have similar patterns and positions, so we can put them all together.     Some key general ideas might be:     1 . White usually wants to secure the  e4 -pawn and negate any chance of development for the  c8 -bishop. -> Therefore, our go-to play is ... a6 , ... Rb8 , ... b5  after developing the knight.     2 . White is likely to reallocate the  g1 -knight to  f2  via  h3  or to  g3  via  e2 . -> So we often delay ... Nbd7  to dodge the first one and play  h7 -... h5  to annoy the second one.     3 . As a final touch, some tricks will be needed to know like  Nxe4 !, and  Qh4 +! It will make sense eventually, trust me. 🙂    Well, I only knew these general ideas when I was playing it, so maybe you can try to just get this simple knowledge and play some blitz games in this line or ask a friend to test it out and see how it goes. I highly encourage a lot of practice and 'sense' of the position, since we often do the same plans and ideas against every variation.    Finally, we'll see some model games as well to properly assess the feeling of these kinds of systems. } )
7. f3{ White reinforces the center and prepares to press through the  c1 - h6  diagonal. Usually white will face some issues to develop properly his kingside as both the knight and the bishop will be developed through  e2 . If white develops the bishop through  d3 , it would be weak to an eventual ... Nbd7 -... Ne5 , aiming to exchange a couple of pieces, which usually makes us pretty happy.     This Benoni is often a byproduct from the 3. f3  Grunfeld or even, to a lesser extent, the 5.  f3  Kings Indian. I even entered this Benoni through the King's Indian Defense (even if I don't play it a lot), so it is quite a popular outcome. }
7. Bg7
8. Bg5{ This pin is a bit innocuous, but it kinda forces us to play ... h6 , because later on we might find trouble playing it after  Qd2  or white would have an extra option with  Bh4 . }
8. h6
9. Be3( 9.Bh4 { is terrible. We will go for ... a6 , ... Nbd7 , ... Ne5  and later on ... Rb8 , ... b5  and White doesn't have any coordination to face us. The knight is likely to be developed on  e2  and usually wants to go to  g3  to pursue a future mobilization.     The issue is having the bishop on  h4 , as an eventual  Ng5  would be faced with ... g6 -... g5  winning a piece. Basically, White position looks good statically but dynamically is terrible, and we have plenty of time to open the queenside and pressure with ... b5 -... b4  to then focus in the center. With 9.  Be3  White is happy to have  h6  as a target later on. } )
9. a6{ Doesn't matter much here, but let's include ... a6 ,  a4  as quickly as possible whenever we don't need to play some tricky ... b5  or ... Na6 . }
10. a4
10. O-O
11. Qd2
11. Re8{ The key trick in the position. We don't need to defend  h6  as it is tactically defended. }
12. Nge2( 12.Bxh6? { runs into }12...Nxe4! { and we will regain the piece with  Qh4 +. We will be left with a bishop pair, and White would miss a key pawn in the center as well. I'd say black is even better. }( 12.Nge2 { is the most played move by far, but I don't think it is good at all. } ) )
12. Nbd7{ Now White needs to decide where to move the knight to develop the bishop. }
13. Nc1
13. Ne5( 13...Nxe4 { is good and works nicely tactically, but this is very good as well and doesn't require memory, just follow the usual plan. I'll add the other variation, but I wanted you to know why this plan is harmless. } )
14. Be2
14. Bd7{ Surprisingly, this move is not very popular, but we always thrive for  b7 -... b5 . }
15. Bxh6( 15.O-O g5 { after White's castle, we don't have ... Nxe4 !, resource against  Bh6  anymore. With ... g5  we prevent  f3 - f4  and suddenly White is stuck.     The  c1 -knight has no future }{ ( Nd3  is awful as we can jump to  c4 ) }{ and  f3 - f4  would be severely weakening on the dark squares. We can follow up with ... Nh5 -... Ng6  and then aim for ... Rb8 , ... b5 , and we have insane control of the position. } )
15. Nxe4{ Here we have this common answer with a twist. }( { Pay attention!, we would be losing the exchange at the end of the line after }16.Nxe4 Qh4+!  )
16. Nxe4
16. Nxf3+{ Such a nice destruction move to play. }
17. Bxf3
17. Rxe4+
18. Bxe4
18. Qh4+
19. Kd1{ Only move. }
19. Bxh6
20. Qe1
20. Qg5{ We are a rook down, but the White king is very exposed, the rooks are so passive and our rook is coming. I'll give an example of how easily things can go wrong for White. }
21. Qf2
21. Re8
22. Bf3
22. Qf4{ And suddenly White is losing after ... Bxa4 +. }
