1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6( { In this chapter, we are gonna talk about }7.f3 { , }7.Nge2 { and }7.Bd3 { . Often they have similar patterns and positions, so we can put them all together.     Some key general ideas might be:     1 . White usually wants to secure the  e4 -pawn and negate any chance of development for the  c8 -bishop. -> Therefore, our go-to play is ... a6 , ... Rb8 , ... b5  after developing the knight.     2 . White is likely to reallocate the  g1 -knight to  f2  via  h3  or to  g3  via  e2 . -> So we often delay ... Nbd7  to dodge the first one and play  h7 -... h5  to annoy the second one.     3 . As a final touch, some tricks will be needed to know like  Nxe4 !, and  Qh4 +! It will make sense eventually, trust me. 🙂    Well, I only knew these general ideas when I was playing it, so maybe you can try to just get this simple knowledge and play some blitz games in this line or ask a friend to test it out and see how it goes. I highly encourage a lot of practice and 'sense' of the position, since we often do the same plans and ideas against every variation.    Finally, we'll see some model games as well to properly assess the feeling of these kinds of systems. } )
7. Bd3{ Usually White plays this move to follow up with 8.  h3 , but this would be checked in a different chapter. Here we will focus on the  Nge2  ideas. }
7. Bg7
8. Nge2{ Here we have the safe ... Nbd7 -... Ne5  jump, as the bishop is on  d3 , but White did not commit to playing  f2 - f3 , so we need to be very careful. I'd say this is far better for White than any version of  f2 - f3  lines. }
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. a6{ Here we play like this because the bishop on  d3  is targetable with ... Ne5 , ... Nxd3 . }
10. a4
10. Nbd7
11. Ng3{ White wants to go for  f4 - h3 , and we will suffer with the lack of space and real counterplay. }
11. Rb8{ I love that whenever White plays some smart move order we just say 'Okaaaaaay let's go for ... b5 ' and most of the time it is the correct play. Here, ... Ne8 -... Nc7  is a great complement to help the  b7 -... b5  push. }( { The usual approach with }11...h5?! { works badly as }12.Bg5 Qc7 { to play ... Nh7  and then ... h5 -... h4  }13.Kh1! Nh7 14.Bh4! { and White would crush us with  f4 , and we cannot even afford to win the piece with ... g6 -... g5  as  Nxh5+Qg4  leads to mate. } )
12. f4( 12.Bf4 Ne5! { an idea you will often see in the  h3 - Bf4  Benoni. If White takes, we just go for ... Ne8 -... Nd6  later on. Otherwise, we just go ... Re8  and  Bf4  was a bit useless, as  f2 - f4  is the plan. } )
12. h5{ Now it makes more sense, as the jump on  g4  is very useful, and we also look forward to playing  h4  sometimes. Going for ... b5 !, and then ... h4 !, to mess up with white pieces can be a great approach. }
13. Qe2
13. b5
14. axb5
14. axb5
15. Nxb5
15. h4
16. Nh1
16. Nb6{ White is very awkward. We'll go for ... c4 , ... Bd7 , ... Re8 , and we pressure a lot in the center. }
