6. g6( { In this chapter, we are gonna talk about }7.f3 { , }7.Nge2 { and }7.Bd3 { . Often they have similar patterns and positions, so we can put them all together.     Some key general ideas might be:     1 . White usually wants to secure the  e4 -pawn and negate any chance of development for the  c8 -bishop. -> Therefore, our go-to play is ... a6 , ... Rb8 , ... b5  after developing the knight.     2 . White is likely to reallocate the  g1 -knight to  f2  via  h3  or to  g3  via  e2 . -> So we often delay ... Nbd7  to dodge the first one and play  h7 -... h5  to annoy the second one.     3 . As a final touch, some tricks will be needed to know like  Nxe4 !, and  Qh4 +! It will make sense eventually, trust me. 🙂    Well, I only knew these general ideas when I was playing it, so maybe you can try to just get this simple knowledge and play some blitz games in this line or ask a friend to test it out and see how it goes. I highly encourage a lot of practice and 'sense' of the position, since we often do the same plans and ideas against every variation.    Finally, we'll see some model games as well to properly assess the feeling of these kinds of systems. } )
7. Nge2
7. h5{ This move directly questions White's knight on  e2 . It is quite a thematic idea. Whenever a knight is on  e2 (or  d2 ) ... h5 !? (or ... a5 !?) is a common answer in many openings, since the knight usually wants to access or control  g3  (or  b3 ).     It will be easier to showcase in the video. This has been played by experts like Indjic and Pantsulaia and Livaic as a more recent acquaintance of the Benoni. }
8. Bg5{ The only really logical continuation. White wants to wait long enough, so we castle, and  Ng3  is finally available as ... h5 -... h4  won't be possible anymore. }( 8.Ng1!? { is an interesting way to punish ... h5 , seen in many variations  (for instance the Najdorf with 6.  h3  and 7.  Nde2 ) but we can just play as usual and ... h5  might even be useful when we play ... Bg4 , ... Bxf3 , ... Nh7  later on, as we talked about in another chapter. } )
8. Bg7{ Now White has many options to fix the  e2 -knight. }
9. Qd2{ The most common generic move to wait for a tempo. But doesn't work here. }
9. O-O
10. Nc1( 10.Ng3 h4 { with the queen on  d2 , we have this sweet trick. Now }11.Bxh4 Nxe4! { immediately equalizes and something like }{   }11.Nge2 { is too passive and }11...Nbd7! { would already place us into the driving seat. } )
10. a6
11. a4( { Now }11...Qe8 { and ... Nh7  would be less attractive, as White can play  Bh6 !, in one go, since the Queen is already on  d2 . } )
11. Nbd7
12. Be2( 12.f3 Qc7 13.Be2 Rb8 { looking for ... c4 , ... b5  could be also a reasonable practical plan. Whenever the  g5 -bishop goes away }{ (let's say to  e3  to secure the  d4 -square after ... c5 -... c4 ) }{ we can play ... h4 !, and ... Nh5 !, to create even more counterplay. } )
12. b5
13. axb5
13. Qb6
14. O-O
14. Bb7{ We will force the exchange, and we have an excellent version of the  Benko Volga  with the pressure through the  b -file. }
