11. f3
11. Nh7
12. Bf4
12. Qe7{ I could leave it here and say yeah, play ... f5  and everything would be fine. But White has tons of pieces into the center, and it is not precisely obvious how to follow up later. }
13. O-O
13. Nd7{ We have many subtle ideas. Playing ... f5 !?,  exf5 , ... Ne5 !?, would be amazing as we will be able to take on  f5  with the  c8 -bishop thanks to the pin on the  f5 -pawn. But White would likely defend the  f4 -bishop out of normal development. }
14. Nd3{ White gets some presence into the center and more importantly, tries to bring back the knight into action. }( { Against }14.Qd2 { we can go for }14...g5! 15.Be3 f5! 16.exf5 Ne5! { and now retake on  f5  with the Bishop for maximum optimization. White aimed to play  Bh6 , so it also prevented our opponent's idea. } )
14. a6
15. a4
15. Rb8{ We want to push  b7 -... b5  and also kick the  d3 -knight away to get the  e5 -square. }
16. Nf2
16. Ne5{ And now ... g5 , ... f5  can be a very reasonable plan to challenge White's center and finish our development. White won't have the usual pressure, and we gained plenty of space for our pieces. For instance, ... Ng6 -... Nf4  is a serious plan later on to get more control over the dark squares. }
