3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3{ Let's check some weird variations for White after 6.  Nf3 . }
6. g6
7. Bg5{ This was played mostly by Bluebaum and Indjic as a transposition to the Kings Indian with  Nf3 - Bg5  without  e2 - e4 . In general, this plan is flawed as we get the bishop pair after ... h6 , ... g5 , ... Nh5  and we also exchange a couple of pieces on the way, so it basically solves all our issues in the early phase. }
7. h6
8. Bh4
8. g5
9. Bg3
9. Nh5
10. e3{ White usually wants to play this 'Kings Indian' with  e3  anyway, so it plays similarly. I don't think it has any special value over  e4 , but maaaaybe White can claim the  f5 -square with a bishop.     White can also look for some dreams with  f2 - f4  and pressure the dark squares, but in reality, we have an insane dark-squared bishop and White can never dream to play  e4 - e5 , which is the move that justifies all the pawn structure. }
10. Nxg3{ We'll go for ... Bg7 , ... Nd7 , ... Qe7  to play ... Ne5  with the option to recapture with the queen, as  h6  will be weak once we castle, and eventually ... a6 , ... b6 , ... Rb8  and slowly look for ... b6 -... b5 . White never has any threat to our king, even with  g5  played, so we can safely castle. White doesn't have meaningful resources to threaten  h6  or open the  h -file. }
