6. g6
7. Bg5{ This move combines very poorly  e2 - e4 . White doesn't even threaten  Ne4  or has any extra pressure on the pin, and our usual development is enough to defend it. }( 7.Bb5+ { is a very poor alternative here. We can just play ... Bd7  as White doesn't have any sensible follow-up, and we can use the information we have about the other openings to compare. We castle fast, and we'll have the option of ... Bg4  or even a more powerful  b7 -... b5 , as in the  h3 - Bd3  variation. } )
7. Bg7
8. f4{ The only logical follow-up is very bad as we already castle and White still needs to develop two pieces. }
8. O-O
9. Nf3( 9.e5 { fails miserably after }9...dxe5 10.fxe5 Re8 11.Nf3 Bg4 { and we'll take the pawn and have even more development. } )
9. Re8
10. Bd3( 10.Be2 { the outcome doesn't change,  after: }10...Qb6! { threatens  e4 , unpins on  f6  and looks for ... Qxb2  and ... c5 -... c4 . } )
10. c4{ After ... Qb6 , White cannot even castle, and our queenside pieces would come, and the position is basically lost for White. }
