7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. Bg4{ This move order makes more sense. Technically, the reason is that including ... a6  and  a4  the  Nd2 - Nc4  variation is more interesting for White, but it also makes sense to play ... Bg4  straightforward when there is no threat of  Qa4 +.     We want to take on  f3  and then secure the  e5 -square with ... Qe7  or ... Re8  and ... Nbd7 . After the first part of the plan, we have ideas with ... h5 -... Nh7  that are incredibly interesting and powers up our  g7 -bishop and also allows for some  Ng5  or even  Qh4 . }
9. Bf4{ This move is suggested by Swiercz. White aims to pressure  d6  and wants to play  Nd2 - Nc4 . }( { This precise move order benefits from }9...Bxf3?! { being a bit imprecise as we cannot insert ... a6 ,  a4  anywhere. }( { If we go for }9...a6? 10.Qa4+! { is incredibly unpleasant. } )( { If }9...Bxf3 10.Bxf3 O-O 11.O-O a6?! 12.e5! { and White is very happy to open the position for the bishops. } ) )
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. a6{ Now we can include this move. }
11. a4( 11.e5 { doesn't make much sense, as we did not commit to ... Bxf3  yet and don't give White the strong bishop pair advantage, Black is fine after }11...dxe5 { . } )
11. Bxf3
12. Bxf3
12. Qe7{ We want to play ... Nbd7  as  d6  is defended now and later on ... h5 , ... Nh7  combines very well. }
13. e5{ The only reasonable attempt for White to open the bishops. }
13. dxe5
14. d6
14. Qe6{ This position is a great example of how including or not ... a6 ,  a4  changes the outcome. If we tried to play ... Bxf3 , ... O-O , and ... Qe7  without ... a6 ,  a4 , now  Bxb7  would win the entire  a8 -rook. }
