[Round "?"]
[White "5) Benoni With 6.e4 - Other 7th Move Options II"]
[Black "6.e4, 7.Be2 with 8.Nf3 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. Be2{ Swiercz recommends this move order as it is based more on strategy and placing the pieces into the correct squares, and less on crushing us.     It is certainly dangerous as White's play is easier than in other variations, and we need to play precise. White wants to go for  Nf3 - Nd2 - Nc4  later on and include  Bf4  somewhere in the middle to pressure  d6  and finish the development. }( { White usually prefers it of }7.Nf3 { as we can go for }7...a6!? 8.a4 Bg4 { as an extra option. For instance, Hou Yifan opted for this approach on many occasions. This is a recurring theme for Black, as ... Bg4  directly has some issues with  Qa4 +!, and after ... Nbd7 ,  Nd2  would leave the  g4 -bishop completely out of position and lost to  h3 - g4 . } )
7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. Bg4{ This move order makes more sense. Technically, the reason is that including ... a6  and  a4  the  Nd2 - Nc4  variation is more interesting for White, but it also makes sense to play ... Bg4  straightforward when there is no threat of  Qa4 +.     We want to take on  f3  and then secure the  e5 -square with ... Qe7  or ... Re8  and ... Nbd7 . After the first part of the plan, we have ideas with ... h5 -... Nh7  that are incredibly interesting and powers up our  g7 -bishop and also allows for some  Ng5  or even  Qh4 . }
9. Bf4{ This move is suggested by Swiercz. White aims to pressure  d6  and wants to play  Nd2 - Nc4 . }( { This precise move order benefits from }9...Bxf3?! { being a bit imprecise as we cannot insert ... a6 ,  a4  anywhere. }( { If we go for }9...a6? 10.Qa4+! { is incredibly unpleasant. } )( { If }9...Bxf3 10.Bxf3 O-O 11.O-O a6?! 12.e5! { and White is very happy to open the position for the bishops. } ) )
9. O-O
10. Nd2{ We are still following Swiercz. White wants to reroute the knight to  c4  and increase the pressure on  d6 . We are very happy to have the  c8 -bishop exchanged already, so we look forward to creating some counterplay. }
10. Bxe2
11. Qxe2
11. Nh5{ We force back the  f4 -bishop, so we can develop the  b8 -knight. }
12. Be3
12. Nd7
13. O-O
13. a6
14. a4{ Main position, Swiercz. }
14. Bd4{ I played this move a couple of times in different positions of the Benoni and I feel it is a great time to explain its worth and the surrounding themes. First and foremost, to justify a move, we need to understand what was our opponent's goal.     In this case,  g2 - g4  is a usual threat to kick the knight and go back to  Nc4 - Bf4  pressuring  d6 . This way we make sure our bishop is out and now  g2 - g4  is bad overall. Once we stopped White's plan, we just need to play ... Re8 , ... Rb8  and look for  b7 -... b5  or even ... Ng7 , ... f5  sometimes.     White never really can take on  d4  as it will push the  c3 -knight away and give us some nice squares on  f4  and  c5  for our knights. Still, we need to pay attention as the game goes on, and this status quo can change, so we might need to exchange the bishops ourselves. }
15. g4( 15.Nf3 Bxe3 16.Qxe3 Rb8 { looking for ... Re8  and  b7 -... b5  break, and we are quite happy considering White delayed the annoying  Nd2 - Nc4  plan. } )
15. Nhf6
16. f3( 16.Bg5 Qc7 { and we will eventually push for  b7 -... b5  after ... Rfe8 . } )
16. Re8{ Whenever our opponent weakens too much the king, the sacrifice  b7 -... b5  can imply consequences later on, and it's a good way to create speculative counterplay that tends to work. We also need to consider how the  c3 -knight needs to defend  d5  from ... Nxd5 ! trick, so it makes even more sense. }
