10. Nxe4
11. a3{ White creates a counterplay that would seem harmless at first sight. Can you spot why is this move threatening at all? }
11. Bg7( 11...bxa3 { runs into }12.Rxa3! { and the rook is coming through the third rank. We still have some decent questions to ask ourselves, starting with: }12...Bg7 { then }13.Nd2! { is the idea and if we take there with }13...Nxd2 14.Re3!+ { and we lose the right to castle. }( { If we go for }13...f5 { incredibly }14.Nc4! { is very strong, and we suddenly realize that our queenside is paralyzed, and we cannot develop any piece to  d7  as the  d6 -pawn is failing. } )( { Considering all, that is not the typical resource you will ever face in the Benoni (even after }14.Re3!+ { White is better, but there is still some games), so it serves as a great example of how careful we need to be sometimes. } ) )
12. axb4
12. cxb4
13. Qd3
13. f5( { Now }13...Nf6?? { was losing against }14.Qe3+ { and  Nb6  as a follow-up! } )
14. Nd4{ White is looking for  e6  and  c6 . We cannot even develop the  b8 -knight, so we might get into trouble. }
14. O-O
15. Nc6{ We will give an example of how dynamics might work in this position. White creates a passed pawn. In case of a waiting move, we could follow with ... Re8  and then check if we prefer ... Nd7  or even ... Bxd4  first, so the best piece of our opponent doesn't get comfortable on  e6 -square. }
15. Nxc6
16. dxc6
16. Be6
17. O-O
17. Rc8
18. Qxa6
18. g5{ This way we release pressure from  d6  and free the  e5 -square for our bishop as well. }
19. Be3
19. Qe8
20. Nb6( 20.Rac1 f4! { , followed by ... f3 !, and the  e8 -queen will go to  h5 , and suddenly White is in trouble. } )
20. Rxc6
21. Bb5
21. Bxb2{ We see how it was useful to include ... g6 -... g5  and our bishop will be in a safe spot on  e5  to follow up with ... f5 -... f4  as the White king is a bit exposed. White is a bit uncoordinated, and we have plenty of compensation for the exchange. }
