1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ This is often considered the best and most reliable plan for White. This is what I recommend in my 1.  d4  Chessable course as White focuses on development and pressure on the  d6  weak point.     It is like 'the London' of the Benoni, so we need to play precisely to not allow an easy play for White. The general aim for White is to go for a less ambitious but reliable  h3 ,  e3 ,  Be2 ,  Bh2 ,  Nd2 , and  Nc4  or  f4 ,  e4  to crush us with  e4 - e5 . }
7. a6( { We want to prevent the extra option for white after }7...Bg7 8.Qa4+!? { It is technically fine for black, but doesn't make much sense to cover both.     The extra option we get from delaying ... a6  is to play an eventual ... Na6  and I felt it wasn't that great, as I cover this line in my Chessable course with White. 🙂 } )
8. e4( 8.Qa4+ { runs into }8...b5! 9.Nxb5 Bd7! { and we can appreciate how having the bishop on  f8  prevents the only way out for white with 10. Nxd6+ . It's also relevant to notice  Qa4 + idea to force black to block on  d7  and then retreat on  b3  and the  d6 -pawn would be under attack, but here it is not the case, so even a move like: }8...Nbd7 { would work.       In this variation, White prefers to take the extra tempo in the center to play  e2 - e4  in one take. Usually, White is forced to play  e2 - e3  and if we castle quickly, White will suffer to hold the center. } )
8. b5{ Obviously, we accept the invitation and expand our dominance in the queenside. Now we need to play a bit precisely to compensate for White's presence in the center. }
9. Be2{ Apparently, this move doesn't make much sense as it leaves  e4  undefended. The main take is that we are not castled, and we still have some moves to finish the development, as we paid attention to expanding on the queenside first. }
9. b4
10. Na4
10. Nxe4
11. a3{ White creates a counterplay that would seem harmless at first sight. Can you spot why is this move threatening at all? }
11. Bg7( 11...bxa3 { runs into }12.Rxa3! { and the rook is coming through the third rank. We still have some decent questions to ask ourselves, starting with: }12...Bg7 { then }13.Nd2! { is the idea and if we take there with }13...Nxd2 14.Re3!+ { and we lose the right to castle. }( { If we go for }13...f5 { incredibly }14.Nc4! { is very strong, and we suddenly realize that our queenside is paralyzed, and we cannot develop any piece to  d7  as the  d6 -pawn is failing. } )( { Considering all, that is not the typical resource you will ever face in the Benoni (even after }14.Re3!+ { White is better, but there is still some games), so it serves as a great example of how careful we need to be sometimes. } ) )
12. axb4
12. cxb4
13. Qc2{ White, a second-degree hidden double attack. Threats of the  e4 -knight and ... Nb6 ! It is fine for Black, but again pay close attention to how not being castled implies a lot of resources for your opponent. }
13. Nf6
14. Nb6
14. Qxb6
15. Qxc8+
15. Ke7{ Similarly to the  f4 - e5  line, we'll manually castle with ... Re8 , ... Kf8  and Black is more than fine. }
