4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ This is often considered the best and most reliable plan for White. This is what I recommend in my 1.  d4  Chessable course as White focuses on development and pressure on the  d6  weak point.     It is like 'the London' of the Benoni, so we need to play precisely to not allow an easy play for White. The general aim for White is to go for a less ambitious but reliable  h3 ,  e3 ,  Be2 ,  Bh2 ,  Nd2 , and  Nc4  or  f4 ,  e4  to crush us with  e4 - e5 . }
7. a6( { We want to prevent the extra option for white after }7...Bg7 8.Qa4+!? { It is technically fine for black, but doesn't make much sense to cover both.     The extra option we get from delaying ... a6  is to play an eventual ... Na6  and I felt it wasn't that great, as I cover this line in my Chessable course with White. 🙂 } )
8. e4( 8.Qa4+ { runs into }8...b5! 9.Nxb5 Bd7! { and we can appreciate how having the bishop on  f8  prevents the only way out for white with 10. Nxd6+ . It's also relevant to notice  Qa4 + idea to force black to block on  d7  and then retreat on  b3  and the  d6 -pawn would be under attack, but here it is not the case, so even a move like: }8...Nbd7 { would work.       In this variation, White prefers to take the extra tempo in the center to play  e2 - e4  in one take. Usually, White is forced to play  e2 - e3  and if we castle quickly, White will suffer to hold the center. } )
8. b5{ Obviously, we accept the invitation and expand our dominance in the queenside. Now we need to play a bit precisely to compensate for White's presence in the center. }
9. Qe2{ This popular move basically force us to switch our general approach. We need to consider that having ... a6  and ... b5  is already a huge achievement and the  Qe2  is not particularly great if  e4 - e5  is not a huge threat. }
9. Be7( 9...Ra7 { is an incredibly satisfying move to make, but it gets incredibly messy, so I prefer this simple way to counter White intentions. Since we have played ... a6  and ... b5 , we are very happy just castling and then solving the situation of the  e7 -bishop. } )( { Why not }9...Bg7 { you may ask }10.Bxd6!! Qxd6 11.e5! Qe7 12.d6! Qe6 13.Ng5! Qg4 14.f3! Qc4 15.Qxc4! bxc4 16.Bxc4! { If you didn't get the reasoning behind most of these moves, relax, it means your opponent would hardly find them on the board. It is a correspondence line and the main threat for White is  exf6 + and  fxg7 , that's the reasoning behind  d6 !  Ng5 !, and  f3 !, and that's why Black tried to block the  e -file or exchange the queens with ... Qe7 ! ... Qe6 ! ... Qg4 ! ... Qc4 !     At the end, White threatens  Nxf7  and black cannot even do anything with the extra piece. The best way to play would be to give it back immediately with }16...O-O { but then }17.exf6 { and white has a healthy extra passed  1-0   (38) Popelka,M (2105)-Bowers,H (2060) ICCF email 2004 .     Since the pawn is on  d6 , White can use the light squares, especially  d5 , to annoy us. Compare this position to having a black bishop blocking on  d6 , suddenly White  Nc3  and  Bc4  would be out of play. } )
10. Qc2{ White can argue that making us play ... Be7  is enough success and now shift to a classical approach. }
10. O-O
11. a4( 11.Be2 Re8 { and we follow up with ... Bf8  and ... Bg4  ideas. We have plenty of space, and White isn't really close to creating any threat in the center. Once again, having ... a6  and ... b5  on the board means not needing to worry that much about White intentions as the threat of ... b5 -... b4  or ... c5 -... c4 .      With  a2 - a4 , White tries to outsmart us. Whenever we play ... b5 -... b4  we would be leaving the  c4 -square forever weak (as we obviously cannot go for ... b7 -... b5  AGAIN). In exchange, we have a substantial lead on development, so we want to react relatively quickly to disrupt the White's plan to play  Nd1 - Ne3 - Nc4 ,  h3 ,  Bd3 ,  O-O . } )
11. b4
12. Nd1
12. b3{ We kick the Queen quickly so  Bd3  is not a move later on. }
13. Qd3
13. Re8
14. Be2
14. a5{ We want to play ... Ba6  to exchange our poor light-squared bishop, and also play ... Bf8  to increase the pressure on  e4  and make it harder for White to focus on the  b3 -pawn. Then looking for ... Nbd7 , ... Rb8  or even ... Na6 -... Nb4  are very good options to improve the last pieces. }( 14...Nh5 { to follow up with ... Nd7 , ... Bf6  doesn't work very well, as White can go for  Be3  and take on  b3  or play  Nd2  at convenience. White still gets some benefit from having the knight on  d1 . }( { For instance }14...  Nh5  plan would work very well against  12.Nb1 b3 13.Qd3 Re8 { and here }14.Be2? { loses against }14...Nxe4! { ... a6 ,  a5  was a decent option }15.Qxe4 Bf6! { and we will take on  b2  being the  a1 -rook trapped. } ) )
