1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ This is often considered the best and most reliable plan for White. This is what I recommend in my 1.  d4  Chessable course as White focuses on development and pressure on the  d6  weak point.     It is like 'the London' of the Benoni, so we need to play precisely to not allow an easy play for White. The general aim for White is to go for a less ambitious but reliable  h3 ,  e3 ,  Be2 ,  Bh2 ,  Nd2 , and  Nc4  or  f4 ,  e4  to crush us with  e4 - e5 . }
7. a6{ I recommend this move to prevent  Qa4 +, but in reality, it is not that dangerous but requires a huge amount of memory and precise knowledge.     If you know your opponent goes for  h2 - h3 , you can try to play ... Bg7  straightforward as it allows a different version of our plan with ... Ne8 -... Nd7 -... Ne5  as the queenside structure is radically different. I'll show a game from our god Indjic against your master, me, to showcase the differences. }
8. a4
8. Bg7
9. h3( 9.e3?! { allows }9...Bg4! { and we get rid of the boring bishop. } )
9. O-O
10. e3( { Going for }10.e4 { would be overly ambitious, as }10...Re8 { followed by ... Nxe4  and ... f5  would make sure White regrets not castling sooner. } )( 10.Nd2!? { can be countered with }10...Nh5! { and then  f7 -... f5  to close the  h2 - b8  diagonal with  f5 -... f4 . } )
10. Ne8{ We defend the  d6 -pawn and prepare to go for ... Nd7 -... Ne5  to eventually leave room for the  e8 -knight to  d6  and have a kind of King's indian.     It is the weirdest Benoni variation, and I would like to thank Indjic again for reviving the spirit of the Benoni solely on his own at the top level. He used ... Nd7 -... Ne5  plan, and even beat me recently in the World Rapid in Kazakhstan with it. }
11. Be2( { Trying to be smart with }11.Nd2 Nd7 12.Nc4 { runs into the usual }12...Nb6 { . Even ... Ne5  would be playable, so we are not worried. } )
11. Nd7( { Another interesting idea might be to start with }11...b6!? { I think it is a bit worse as White has many extra options, but it is a good idea in practice to test someday. } )
12. a5{ White can start with preventing  b7 -... b5 , and it has a smarter idea. }( { Remember we play }12.O-O Ne5 13.Nd2 b6! { to prevent  a4 - a5 , but here White already achieved that, so we switched the approach. } )( { If you want, you can play it anyway as now   }12...Ne5 13.Nd2 b5 14.axb6 Qxb6 { is also reasonable, but it has some significant differences, and switching now might be more reliable. } )
12. Rb8
13. O-O
13. b5
14. axb6
14. Rxb6
15. Qc2
15. Qe7{ We want to play ... Ne5  and after exchanging the  b -pawn, the idea with ... dxe5  is less appealing as our pawn structure would be too broken. }
16. Nd2
16. Ne5{ We control  c4 , and we aim to play ... Nc7 , ... f5 , ... Bd7 , so we have pressure on the queenside while preventing White from a fast attack on the kingside. }
