[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Nd2{ One of the key topics about the Benoni is the  c4 -square. If White manages to put a Knight and secure the spot it would be beneficial in many ways. Pressuring our weakness on  d6 , controlling the queenside (and the key square  b6  in case of  a7 -... a6 + a4 , ... a5  inclusion) and helping the center to push  f4 - e5  eventually.     A hidden idea that appears not too often is being able to jump to  a5  after an eventual  b7 -... b5 ,  axb5 ,  axb5 , as the  c6 -square might be somehow exposed. With this move order, we need to pay special attention to our moves to kick or counter the  c4 -knight at the right time, or we will be left tangled without much space and the  c8 -bishop complaining. }
7. Bg7
8. Nc4{ White usually enjoyed great advantage in this line historically. As we were forced to concede against the domination of the  Nc4  and the pressure on  d6  of the bishop. }
8. O-O
9. Bg5
9. Nbd7{ White's evil idea was to tease us with  h7 -... h6  and then go back to  f4 . That way, we might have issues with the  h6 -pawn being exposed later on. The suggestion feels like a rule: Whenever White develops the bishop and has the knight on  c4 , we play ... Nbd7 . We want to go for ... Nb6 , so White needs to be creative or quick. }
10. Nxd6( { Against }10.e4!? { White has the extra option to face }10...Nb6 { with }11.Ne3!? { and our knight on  b6  is a bit awkward and weak to ... a4 ,  a5 . White spent too much tempis without castling, so we obviously have counterplay. } )( { The move is   }10...h6! { and when we kick the bishop out of pinning our  f6 -knight, we follow with the stylish ... b5 !, making good use of the  e4 -pawn being targetable. } )
10. Qb6
11. Nxc8( { If }11.Nc4 { now }11...Qb4! { is excellent as White cannot prevent ... Qxb2  or ... Nxd5 . } )
11. Raxc8{ Here we follow up with ... Qa5 - and ... b5  ideas, and White would eventually need to give up on holding the center. We can also look for ... c4 - , ... Nc5  or even jumps with ... Ne4  if White doesn't allow us to go for ... b5 . Our counterplay is very easy I would say and White has tons of bad choices. }
