8. Nc4{ White usually enjoyed great advantage in this line historically. As we were forced to concede against the domination of the  Nc4  and the pressure on  d6  of the bishop. }
8. O-O
9. Bf4
9. Nbd7{ You definitely should remember this position. Otherwise, White has a very comfortable play. Usually, GMs rely on remembering key positions and can reconstruct the rest by thinking, so you don't need to overload memorizing each and every move.     The glue to build it all is the logic or sense of the position, therefore, you must try to make sense of what are you reading in your own words or approach. Friendly reminder to ask whenever you feel something is not really well explained, or it is not clear.      We give up a pawn, but White is still 3 moves away from castling. }( { The usual plan }9...Ne8 { and then going for ... b6  and ... Ba6  to exchange our passive bishop is in general playable, but White retains a decent edge. I had a very nice game against a strong opposition many years ago.  ½-½   (44) Jankovic,A (2536) -Alonso Rosell,A (2285) Barbera del Valles 2007 . } )
10. Nxd6{ A must. }( { If }10.e3 { obviously }10...Nb6 { is excellent, and we will exchange the best piece from White and still create havoc due to the lack of development. } )( { A funny attempt is }10.g3!? { as our usual answer }10...Nb6 { is a light mistake after }11.Nxd6! { This is usually how novelties and theories progress: you find a move, it doesn't matter if it looks good or bad, if the known answer or plan fails somehow, then it turns into an interesting novelty. }( { Just }10...Nh5! { would solve all our issues. } )( { Even }10...Ng4 { works well. }{ It is also noticeable how barely anyone played this move, and I feel it is quite more challenging. } ) )
10. Nh5{ Now White has 3 retreats that we face in very creative ways. }
11. Be3
11. Qb6( { ... Qxb2  is a very serious threat, even against }12.Nxc8 { . } )
12. Nc4
12. Qa6( { In comparison to another line, }12...Qb4 { White still has }13.Qb3 { and there is no ... Nxd5  now. Still Black should be okay, but I prefer 12... Qa6 . Now we just want to play  b7 -... b5  and achieve great counterplay. } )( { For instance, a move like   }13.Qb3 { would only slow us a bit as we follow up with }13...Nhf6 { and  b7 -... b5  is already a threat. Even against }14.a4 b5!! { works well as }15.Qxb5 Rb8! { and we expose White's queenside. } )
