7. Nd2{ One of the key topics about the Benoni is the  c4 -square. If White manages to put a Knight and secure the spot, it would be beneficial in many ways. Pressuring our weakness on  d6 , controlling the queenside (and the key square  b6  in case of  a7 -... a6 + a4 , ... a5  inclusion) and helping the center to push  f4 - e5  eventually.     A hidden idea that appears not too often is being able to jump to  a5  after an eventual  b7 -... b5 ,  axb5 ,  axb5 , as the  c6 -square might be somehow exposed. With this move order, we need to pay special attention to our moves to kick or counter the  c4 -knight at the right time, or we will be left tangled without much space and the  c8 -bishop complaining. }
7. Bg7
8. e4{ White prevented the usual ... Bg4  maneuver and now leaves us wondering what to do. }
8. O-O
9. Be2
9. Na6{ After some consideration, I feel this plan is the easiest and more straightforward. Since White fortified his center pretty well, we will try to speed up our counterplay on the queenside with ... Nc7 , ... a6 , and  b5 . Usually Black would go for ... Nbd7 , ... Re8  ... Ne5  and ... g5  plans, controlling the dark squares.     But White has a very reliable plan with  a4 ,  Ra3 ,  Qc2 ,  Nd1 ,  Re1 ,  Nf1 ,  Ng3 , making use of our weak  f5 -square and the lack of counterplay. I happen to practice this Benoni with some grandmasters and felt too annoying and conceptual to deal with. White doesn't really need to remember much, just the general trend and be aware of simple one or two-movers. }
10. O-O( { Now }10.Nc4? { would be too early as we have the usual counter }10...b5! { ready. } )( 10.Bxa6 bxa6 { is excellent for Black. } )
10. Nc7{ ... a6 , ... Rb8  and ... b5  is the go-to plan. }
11. a4( 11.f4 { was played a decent amount of times but mostly due to a transposition from the 6. f4  variation with  Nf3  and  Be2 . There we have }11...b5! 12.Nxb5 Nxb5 13.Bxb5 Ng4! { and the threat of ... Bd4 + or ... Ne3  or even ... c4 !, to play ... Qb6 + puts White in a very bad situation already. } )
11. a6{ Usually wouldn't be advisable to play this move so quickly, as the rook is on  a8 . }( 12.Nc4 { would imply we cannot play  b7 -... b5 , as the  b5 -pawn would end up falling. But it works tactically at the end of the line, as the  e4 -pawn would be undefended. If we needed to play }12...Rb8 { then }13.Bf4 Nfe8 14.a5 { would mean suffering and calamities for us. } )
12. Nc4{ Shankland stated in his course that White should be much better as ... b5  is not possible, but lucky for us, it turns out to be fine, and recently Black findfound some success with it. In general, I find 7.  Nd2  is a very good recommendation as we need to play precise from very early on, or we get strategically crushed. }( { In case of }12.f3 b6!? { looks like an efficient way to play as }13.Nc4 Rb8 { we cannot go for ... b5  as  e4  is defended }14.Bf4 Nfe8 { and we will be playing ... b6 -... b5 , and it is quite menacing in practice for White. } )( { You could also consider }12...Rb8 13.a5 Nd7!? { and trying to be aware of the  d2 -knight and mirror it with the  d7  open could be a decent option as well. } )( 12.Re1 Rb8 13.a5 Re8!? { increasing the pressure on  e4  and allowing  Bf8  later on in case of  Nc4 , }14.f3 Bd7! { followed by ... Bb5  to exchange the typical bad bishop, and we have a very easy way as mentioned to parry the threats on  d6 . } )
12. b5{ Yes sir! }
