4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. g3
7. Bg7
8. Bg2
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ With this move we aim to control the center, maybe going for ... Ne4 , but not necessarily. ... Re8  is the most flexible move, as it allows us to go for ... Bf5 /... Bg4  or ... Nbd7  on demand. We prefer to also have the extra option to play  b7 -... b5  in one take, so we don't want to include ... a6 ,  a4 . }
10. a4{ White has many move orders, and even this one can be tricky to face. }
10. Ne4{ I don't see any issue now with this move. We liberate the  g7 -bishop and exchange a couple of pieces. Now we need to pay attention to how we deal with the maneuver  Nd2 - Nc4 . }
11. Nxe4
11. Rxe4
12. Nd2
12. Rb4{ We control the key  c4 -square and increase the pressure on  b2 . The rook looks really nice, but it is also a bit exposed, so we need to go a bit deeper. }( 12...Re8? 13.Nc4 { . } )
13. Qc2( 13.Ra2 { basically transposes to  Qc2  eventually. } )
13. Nd7
14. Ra2
14. a5( { We start with this move since }14...b5?! 15.axb5 Rxb5 16.b3 { and we are not in time to break with ... a5 -... a4  as in the mainline, so we will have a very weak pawn on  a5  which is quite obvious to target for White. } )
15. b3{ With all this maneuvering, White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops and be in time to play ... Rfa1  to have pressure on the  a -pawn whenever we play  b7 - b5 . }
15. b5
16. Ba3
16. bxa4{ If White tried to play the same idea without including  Qc2 , we would be doing exactly the same kind of sacrifice. }
17. Bxb4
17. axb4{ The bishop on the grand diagonal, the marvelous pawn chain, and the silly bishop on  g2  give plenty of compensation for the exchange. }
18. Rxa4
18. Rxa4
19. bxa4
19. Ba6{ ... Qa5  and ... Nb6  are coming, and White would suffer extremely to hold a draw against those passed pawns in my honest opinion. }
