9. Re8{ With this move we aim to control the center, maybe going for ... Ne4 , but not necessarily. ... Re8  is the most flexible move, as it allows us to go for ... Bf5 /... Bg4  or ... Nbd7  on demand. We prefer to also have the extra option to play  b7 -... b5  in one take, so we don't want to include ... a6 ,  a4 . }
10. h3
10. Bd7{ This idea is still pretty new and unused and has excellent results in practice. Since  h2 - h3  hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, it is even more convenient to remember. We don't really want to play ... Ne4  yet, as the rook won't have the ideal square on  b4  with the pawn on  a2 . }
11. a4
11. Ne4{ Now it's a better way to approach it. We want to open the  g7 -bishop and exchange a couple of pieces. But in this setup, we get ahead of typical White responses. }
12. Nxe4{ Otherwise, we calmly go for ... Na6 -... Nb4  and get space for every piece. We get an efficient way to develop our pieces. }
12. Rxe4{ You might be asking, Àlvar, why does including ... Bd7  and ... a4  matters? }
13. Nd2
13. Rb4{ We have an excellent square on  b4  for our rook, and we deny White to achieve the desired  Nc4 . We look for ... b7 -... b5 . We'll check out an excellent game from Iturrizaga. }( 14.Ra2 b5 15.axb5 Bxb5 16.b3 a5 17.Ba3 Na6 18.Bxb4 Nxb4 19.Ra3 Bb2 20.Ra4 Bxa4 21.bxa4 Bg7 22.Nc4 Na2 23.Qd2 Nc3 24.Rc1 Nxa4 25.Bf3 Qc7 26.e3 Qb8 27.Nxa5 Bc3 28.Rxc3 Rxa5 29.Rc4 Nb6 30.Qxa5 Nxc4 31.Qa6 Qb1+ 32.Kh2 Qc2 33.Bg2 Kg7 34.g4 Qc3 35.Kg1 Qc1+ 36.Kh2 h6 37.Bf3 Qc2 38.Kg3 Qd3 39.Qa1+ Ne5 40.Bg2 c4 41.Bf1 Qxd5 42.Be2 Kg8 43.Qc3 Qh1 {  0-1   (43) Gleizerov,E (2510)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2624) Dresden 2016 . } )
