[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. g3
7. Bg7
8. Bg2
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ With this move we aim to control the center, maybe going for ... Ne4 , but not necessarily. ... Re8  is the most flexible move, as it allows us to go for ... Bf5 /... Bg4  or ... Nbd7  on demand. We prefer to also have the extra option to play  b7 -... b5  in one take, so we don't want to include ... a6 ,  a4 . }
10. Nd2{ White prevents ... Ne4  and tries to reroute to  c4 . }
10. Nbd7{ A very typical 'dance' with the knights in the Benoni. }( { It doesn't change much if we play }10...a6 { first, but this move order might catch some unexpected customer playing }11.Nc4 { carelessly, as many did already. } )
11. h3{ White does a calm waiting move, getting ready to answer ... Ne5  with  f2 - f4 . }
11. a6
12. a4
12. Rb8( 12...b6 { is also a serious contender, and it has shown very good results in practice. } )( { Well, turns out }12...Rb8 { has excellent results in practice, and it is the best move objectively. } )
13. a5{ Usually this idea is great for White as it destroys our ambitions to have a very sweet pawn chain  (that's why moves like 11...  b6  are tempting, to prepare the ... b5  push). In this case, though, the  d2 -knight gets punished, as we will deny it. }
13. b5
14. axb6
14. Nxb6{ White stopped the pawn chain from expanding, but the knight on  d2  has some issues as the  c4 -square is under control. }
15. Kh2{ White gets ready to push  e4 - f4 . }( 15.e4?! { White leaves some holes in the position }15...Nfd7! { looking for the  d3 -square }16.f4 c4 { White's pawn center is worthless and the  c1 -bishop won't enter the action. I'd say white is lost in practice here, and the results in practice are splendid. We will sneak the knight on  d3  and enjoy all the pressure through the  h8 - a1  diagonal and the  b  and  e -files. } )
15. Nfd7{ We get ahead of White's idea and plan some traps. It's a good idea to 'tease' the opponent. }
16. f4{ White needs to start with this weird move, otherwise, ... Ne5 -... Nd3  would be a winning plan for us. }
16. f5
17. e4
17. c4( { We'll go for ... Nc5  or ... Qc7, ...Nc5  if white plays something like }18.Ra5 { with the evil idea to sacrifice the exchange and push  e4 - e5 . White doesn't have a clear plan ahead and the knight on  d3  will wreak havoc, I don't expect White to survive here. } )
