[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. g3
7. Bg7
8. Bg2
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ With this move we aim to control the center, maybe going for ... Ne4 , but not necessarily. ... Re8  is the most flexible move, as it allows us to go for ... Bf5 /... Bg4  or ... Nbd7  on demand. We prefer to also have the extra option to play  b7 -... b5  in one take, so we don't want to include ... a6 ,  a4 . }
10. Nd2{ White prevents ... Ne4  and tries to reroute to  c4 . }
10. Nbd7{ A very typical 'dance' with the knights in the Benoni. }( { It doesn't change much if we play }10...a6 { first, but this move order might catch some unexpected customer playing }11.Nc4 { carelessly, as many did already. } )
11. h3{ White does a calm waiting move, getting ready to answer ... Ne5  with  f2 - f4 . }
11. a6
12. a4
12. Rb8( 12...b6 { is also a serious contender, and it has shown very good results in practice. } )( { Well, turns out }12...Rb8 { has excellent results in practice, and it is the best move objectively. } )
13. Nc4
13. Ne5
14. Na3{ Here you can appreciate the usefulness of including  a4 , ... a6  for White. }{ Here, White aims to play  f4- e4 -Nc4 , taking advantage of our poor knight on  e5  and our inability to play the logical move }( 14...Bd7 { since }15.f4! { traps the knight. So we need to react quickly. } )
14. Nh5{ This is the best move by far. It's been known for quite some time, and Black's results are excellent. I even played it more than 10 years ago. }( { Even considering my first assumption, I highly recommend you to know you can play }14...b5!? { if you like Benko-ish approaches. }15.axb5 axb5 16.Naxb5 Qb6!? { followed by ... Ba6  gives an excellent compensation and might be a very easy way for you to just play this line.      Now that you know a way to deal with this variation, and you checked the other lines BEFORE CONTINUING HERE (I highly encourage you to first get a decent answer against every setup for white  g3  variation and then come back here to enjoy the flashy dynamics of this variation). } )( { Having said that, with }14...Nh5 { we aim for  f7 -... f5  to prevent white from expanding in the center. A word of advice here: from now on, all sacrifices look appealing for Black, so be careful not to get confused about where we do each. } )
15. g4{ It seems reasonable for White to kick our knight, but comes at a price. Here we have some interesting options to create some havoc, but it requires a lot of investment in knowing every sacrifice.  Qh4  is a wonderful way to dig in, but since  g3 - g4  has been barely played, and we can assume White doesn't 'casually' land here after this  Nf3 - Nd2 - Nc4 - Na3  maneuver, I prefer to suggest a playable line. }
15. Nxg4
16. hxg4
16. Bxg4{ We have many pieces pointing to the exposed king, and we also want to push for  b7 -... b5 . For now, ... Bxc3  and ... Bxe2  is a direct threat. }
17. Qe1{ Is the only move that keeps White in the game. }( 17.Qd2 h6! { preventing  Qg5  and wanting to play ... Qh4  and after }18.Qe1 { preventing  Qh4  due to  f3 ! }18...b5 19.axb5 axb5 20.Naxb5 Rxb5! 21.Nxb5 Rxe2 22.Qa5 Qh4 23.Qa8+ Kh7 { and white resigned in an old correspondence game.  0-1   (23) Vidalina,F-Daurelle,H LSS email 2006 . } )( 17.Re1 { basically loses after }17...Qh4 { and the threats of ... Bd4  or ... Be5  win the game. } )
17. Qd7{ Funnily enough, having the pawn on  h7  makes the same idea as 17.  Qd2 ? failed, as we will need to play ... Bf8  to cover the back rank, and we need the bishop to mate our opponent. }( 17...b5?! 18.axb5 axb5 19.Naxb5 Rxb5?! 20.Nxb5 Rxe2 21.Qa5 Qh4 22.Qa8+! { forcing }22...Bf8 { and now something like }23.Ra4 { would easily win as we need the bishop to play ... Be5  and mate our opponent. } )
