9. Re8{ With this move we aim to control the center, maybe going for ... Ne4 , but not necessarily. ... Re8  is the most flexible move, as it allows us to go for ... Bf5 /... Bg4  or ... Nbd7  on demand. We prefer to also have the extra option to play  b7 -... b5  in one take, so we don't want to include ... a6 ,  a4 . }
10. Re1{ White improves the  f1 -rook and maaaaaybe looks forward to playing  e2 - e4 . It is all about the move orders for White in this Benoni. There is no immediate threat at any point, but the shadow of getting strategically crushed with an eventual  Nd2 - Nc4 - e4 - f4  needs to be checked. }
10. Nbd7( { Now }10...Ne4 { doesn't work as well as against 10.  a4  since we don't have the  b4 -square secured for the rook. }10...Bd7 { is also less appealing since }11.e4! { followed by  e5  is a huge threat. } )
11. Bf4{ Now it is more exciting for White to play this move as there is a threat on  d6 , and we are not in time to play ... h6 , ... g5  as usual. }( { In case of }11.h3 { , as a waiting move, we can just force }11...a6 12.a4 { and now }12...Ne4! { as we have the excellent  b4  for the rook, and we can see in this chapter many examples of this maneuver. } )
11. Ng4{ The key idea. We want to conquer the  e5 -square, and White cannot take on  d6 . Usually, this plan can face some issues with the bishop on  c1 , as White might go for  Nd2  and the  e5 -knight might be completely out of moves after  h3 - f4 . Basically, in a nutshell, White usually benefits from us having issues adjusting our pieces with very little space for them.     The key difference is considering the  Bf4  is a possible target, which makes this plan more viable and makes it hard for White to play  f2 - f4 . In general, we want to play ... Nde5  and maybe later ... h6 , ... g5 , or  f7 -... f5  if there is a knight on  e4  to pressure  d6  to get all the space back.      Finally, it doesn't matter that much that we included ... a6  and  a4  to enter this line, I would say. I feel it is a bit more precise, but I wouldn't say it is life-changing. }
12. Bg5{ This move has been tested in correspondence games, and it is getting attention on GM level, so we need to briefly talk about it. }
12. Qb6{ If we are following a game from Shevchenko, that usually means we are on the correct path. }
13. Qb3( 13.Qc1 c4 { now we got to play ... Nge5  and later on ... Nc5 . We might need to play  a7 -... a6  later on to move back the queen and look for  b7 -... b5 .     It is very important to have  f7 -... f5  as a good alternative whenever  f2 - f4  might be a threat. }{ Kirill played }14.Rf1 Nde5?! { that works poorly since we let the  d4 -square for White. }15.Nxe5! Nxe5 16.Be3! { followed by  Qd2 - Bd4  would've been excellent for White. } )( { That's why we would be playing }14...Nge5 15.Nxe5 Bxe5! { to have ... Nc5  as an option later on.  0-1   (60) Pranav,A (2525)-Shevchenko,K (2684) Bucharest 2023 . } )
13. a6{ We cover the  b5 -square, as  Nb5  is usually a huge threat without the queens on the board, pressuring  d6  and the  c7  double. We aim for ... Qc7  and ... Rb8 , ... b5  as usual. }
14. Qxb6
14. Nxb6
15. Bf4{ We have a bit of an awkward position. }( { If we play }15...Rd8 16.h3! { and we cannot go for ... Ne5  comfortably as we don't want to take with the  d -pawn. } )
15. Bxc3{ This precise solution just fixes everything. }
16. bxc3
16. Nf6{ We'll take on  d5  and then on  c3 , and we are into the game. }( { This subtle starting move fixes our knight first and }17.Bxd6?! { would be imprecise, thanks to }17...Ne4! { and we are already better. } )
