15. e4( 15.Bf4 { runs into }15...Nh5! { and doesn't allow White to improve the setup. } )( 15.Qc1 { was played and was the only decent result White got (3 losses and a draw don't speak very well for White), trying to understand the reasoning behind, I figured out that after }15...Kh7 16.Bf4 Nh5 { would be far less inspiring as now White can easily take on  g4  as the  f4 -bishop is defended in comparison to 15.  Bf4 . } )( { We can also make use of what changes in the position if the Queen is on  c1 , so after }15.Qc1 Kh7 16.Bf4 a6! 17.a4 Qe7! { and the key difference is apparent when white plays }18.e4 Nbd7 { and the  g4 -pawn is not threatened as it would be with the Queen on  c1 . I think it is a great example of how we need to be aware of subtle changes but since White usually always wants to play  e2 - e4 - e5  or  Nd2 - Nc4  in good conditions we are simply required to pay attention to how White could do it.      Finally, if White prefers to start with 15.  Nf1  we have plenty of time to go for ... Nbd7 -... Ne5  and later on focus on the queenside expansion. } )
