[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. Nf3( { Other moves like }3.g3 { or }3.Bg5 { are just too bad after ... cxd4 , losing control of the center and having to waste tempos with the queen early on. } )
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5{ As usual in this course, we aim for the most challenging line. We want to directly take control of the center. Now, white has two main paths. }( { The passive moves like }5.Nb3 { , }5.Nf3 { and }5.Nc2 { , where we want to get space in the center with no opposition and the critical one with }5.Nb5 { . } )
5. Nb5{ White threatens  Nd6 + (so we cannot play  a7 -... a6 ) and also  N1c3  (so we cannot get too comfortable playing the usual ... Nc6 ). So we react very shockingly. }
5. d5
6. cxd5{ Otherwise ... a6 , ... d4  would be almost winning. }
6. Bc5{ We cannot retake on  d5  as there is a double check in  c7 . So we accelerate our development instead. White has somewhat weird development ahead as both knights want to go to  c3  and the  d2 -square would also be busy developing both the  b1 -knight and the  c1 -bishop.     All that plus the need to develop the kingside and be a bit more exposed, as both knights belong to the queenside for now. Basically, we want to develop quickly and make use of White situational problems. }
7. N1c3{ Trying to develop normally will be awful as the  b5 -knight will get out of play. }
7. O-O{ Playing an early ... a6  would let white reroute the  b5 -knight sooner. }
8. g3( 8.e3 a6 9.Na3 e4 { we want to keep up with the ideal setup. ... Qe7 , ... Nbd7 , ... Rd8  and whenever white tries something like  Nc4 , ... b5 !, would be our answer. White barely has any space as the  e4 -pawn restricts all the space. Eventually, we will have two options, to go for the attack with ... Ne5 , ... Bf5 , ... Bd6 , or to just chill with ... Bb7  and retake on  d5 . } )
8. Bd7{ This way, if we go for ... b5 -... b4  ideas, White cannot win a tempi with  Nc3 - a4 . }
9. Na3
9. b5
10. Naxb5( { If }10.Nc2 b4 11.Nb1 Ng4 12.e3 Bf5 { we have the same style of position, having the pawn on  b4  restricting even more White's development. } )
10. Qa5{ We enter a dynamically forced line and White will be worse at the end of it. }
11. Qb3
11. Na6
12. Bd2
12. Rab8
13. e3
13. Bb4
14. Na3
14. Nc5
15. Qc2( 15.Qc4 { or }15.Qd1 { would be even worse for White, as ... Nce4  is stronger and would be followed by ... Rfc8 . } )
15. Nce4
16. Bg2
16. Nxd2
17. Qxd2
17. Rfc8{ Now ... Rxc3 ! is a huge threat, and we can stop for a bit to admire how active are our pieces! }
18. Rc1
18. Qa6{ We play around not letting White castle now. }
19. Bf1
19. Qa4{ We have a hidden trick now. }
20. Bg2
20. Rxc3
21. Rxc3
21. Bxc3
22. Qxc3
22. Ne4{ White is busted. }( 23.Bxe4? Qxe4 { and now }24.O-O Bh3 25.f3 Qxd5 { and White would lose even more material. }( { If }24.Rf1 Bg4 { and the control on light-squares is too much for White. } ) )( 23.Qc2 { is torture after }23...Qb4+ { and it doesn't matter where the king goes, as ... Bf5 !, would threaten ... Nxg3  and likely force White to resign. } )
