1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. Nf3( { Other moves like }3.g3 { or }3.Bg5 { are just too bad after ... cxd4 , losing control of the center and having to waste tempos with the queen early on. } )
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5{ As usual in this course, we aim for the most challenging line. We want to directly take control of the center. Now, white has two main paths. }( { The passive moves like }5.Nb3 { , }5.Nf3 { and }5.Nc2 { , where we want to get space in the center with no opposition and the critical one with }5.Nb5 { . } )
5. Nb5{ White threatens  Nd6 + (so we cannot play  a7 -... a6 ) and also  N1c3  (so we cannot get too comfortable playing the usual ... Nc6 ). So we react very shockingly. }
5. d5
6. cxd5{ Otherwise ... a6 , ... d4  would be almost winning. }
6. Bc5{ We cannot retake on  d5  as there is a double check in  c7 . So we accelerate our development instead. White has somewhat weird development ahead as both knights want to go to  c3  and the  d2 -square would also be busy developing both the  b1 -knight and the  c1 -bishop.     All that plus the need to develop the kingside and be a bit more exposed, as both knights belong to the queenside for now. Basically, we want to develop quickly and make use of White situational problems. }
