9. f5{ Allez-hi! }
10. Be2{ The best move for White. }( 10.h3 { this move feels easy to make, but would weaken the kingside in the long term, }10...Nf6 11.Bg2 e4 { going for ... Nbd7  and ... b6 , ... Ba6  or just  Ne5  is excellent. White never really wants to play  f2 - f3  as it would mean weakening  e3  and  g3  immensely, so the bishop on  g2  is a bit pointless. }( { In case of }11.Be2 { we can play }11...Nbd7 { and now ... Kh8  }{ (to get away from the  a1 - g8  diagonal) }{ and look for ... Nb6  or ... b6  , ... Bb7  might be very good, and White feels helpless and without a clear plan to make use of the extra pawn. } ) )
10. Nd7{ We keep adding pieces into the mix. }( 10...Nf6 { would be too slow, as  Nd2 - Nf3  +  a3 - b4  would interrupt our hopes and dreams to take back the center. } )
11. a3{ This waiting move is somewhat useful as ... Bb4  is prevented, and the dark-squared bishop is completely countered by White's pawn chain. }
11. Ndf6{ Now that the  g4 -knight is well defended,  f5 - f4  is a severe threat. }
12. b4
12. Bb6
13. h3
13. Nh6{ As usual, we want to finish developing all the pieces, so our opponent pays the price of having an extra knight on the queenside and a weak kingside. }( { If you like craziness, }13...Nxf2!? 14.Kxf2 f4 { is a very interesting alternative. Remember to not be too optimistic about the attack and play  Bd7 - Rc8  at some point. Sacrificing a piece is not an excuse to forget development! } )
14. Na4{ White really needs to do something about the  f5 - f4  threat. Playing it without 12.  b4  would mean giving us the healthy alternative of playing ... Be7  and looking for ... Nf7 -... Nxd5  extra ideas. }
14. Bd7
15. Nxb6
15. axb6{ Suddenly, White's position is very weak on the light-squares, and we exchanged the 'worse piece'. Now, a couple of plans are reasonable. ... Qe8 -... Qg6 , ... f4  or ... Nf7 -... Nd6 , ... f4 , both mean a great threat to the exposed kingside. }
