3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5{ As usual in this course, we aim for the most challenging line. We want to directly take control of the center. Now, white has two main paths. }( { The passive moves like }5.Nb3 { , }5.Nf3 { and }5.Nc2 { , where we want to get space in the center with no opposition and the critical one with }5.Nb5 { . } )
5. Nb5{ White threatens  Nd6 + (so we cannot play  a7 -... a6 ) and also  N1c3  (so we cannot get too comfortable playing the usual ... Nc6 ). So we react very shockingly. }
5. d5
6. cxd5{ Otherwise ... a6 , ... d4  would be almost winning. }
6. Bc5{ We cannot retake on  d5  as there is a double check in  c7 . So we accelerate our development instead. White has somewhat weird development ahead as both knights want to go to  c3  and the  d2 -square would also be busy developing both the  b1 -knight and the  c1 -bishop.     All that plus the need to develop the kingside and be a bit more exposed, as both knights belong to the queenside for now. Basically, we want to develop quickly and make use of White situational problems. }
7. N5c3
7. O-O{ We castle, and we put the pressure on White's side. }( { What to do, know? }8.g3 { , }8.h3 { , }8.a3 { and }8.e3 { are the reasonable White options here. Can you spot what's wrong with }8.Bg5?  )
8. g3( 8.e3 { is a bit too slow, as we can just go for }8...Bf5 { + ... Nbd7  and there ... Nb6  or ... Bb4  to take back the  d5 -pawn. We also have the option to go for }8...e4 { safely (as the  c1 -bishop is not going anywhere) and there go for the usual plan with ... Qe7 , ... Nbd7 , ... Ne5 , ... Rfd8 , ... Rac8  while White can only watch passively. } )
8. Ng4{ Feels like the typical move you would complain if your student played it. Don't just try to do threats in one and speculative attacks, you might say! This case is different as White misses a knight on the kingside and the development is so awkward. }
9. e3
9. f5{ Allez-hi! }
10. Be2{ The best move for White. }( 10.h3 { this move feels easy to make, but would weaken the kingside in the long term, }10...Nf6 11.Bg2 e4 { going for ... Nbd7  and ... b6 , ... Ba6  or just  Ne5  is excellent. White never really wants to play  f2 - f3  as it would mean weakening  e3  and  g3  immensely, so the bishop on  g2  is a bit pointless. }( { In case of }11.Be2 { we can play }11...Nbd7 { and now ... Kh8  }{ (to get away from the  a1 - g8  diagonal) }{ and look for ... Nb6  or ... b6  , ... Bb7  might be very good, and White feels helpless and without a clear plan to make use of the extra pawn. } ) )
10. Nd7{ We keep adding pieces into the mix. }( 10...Nf6 { would be too slow, as  Nd2 - Nf3  +  a3 - b4  would interrupt our hopes and dreams to take back the center. } )
11. O-O
11. Ndf6
12. h3
12. Nh6
13. Nd2
13. Nf7( 13...f4 { looks more attractive, but waiting first with ... Nf7  gives even better results, as we can play ... f5 -... f4  in the perfect moment. Giving the  e4 -square might not be too good, and }14.Kh2 { is more or less forced, and White gets easier play. } )
14. Nc4( 14.Kh2 b6 { since White took so long, we are in time to just take the  d5 -pawn. ... Nf7  is helpful as usually,  Nd2 - c4  wins a tempo as it threatens  e5  and then White is on time to defend  d5  somehow, and now it is not the case. } )
14. f4{ White would miss not having  Nde4 . }
15. g4
15. b5
16. Nxb5
16. Ne4{ The Queen is coming to the action and White is ready to resign. }
