1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. e3{ I never really checked this move. Once you realize White's best move is always  d4 - d5  from now on, it is a bit silly to start with  e2 - e3 . }( 3.Nf3 { also holding the center, other moves like }3.g3 { or }3.Bg5 { are just too bad after ... cxd4 , losing control of the center and having to waste tempos with the Queen early on. } )
3. g6
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. Be2
5. O-O
6. O-O{ White kinda played as if it was a Queen's Gambit reversed. Now we get to some known theory in the shape of a reversed Tarrasch. }
6. cxd4
7. exd4( 7.Nxd4 d5 { and our  g7 -bishop does quite a lot more than the one on  e2 . We have a very typical Catalan position. } )
7. d5{ We will get the isolated  d4 -pawn and a very pleasant position. Our goal changes drastically from the original Benoni, now we will cherish blocking the  d4 -pawn with pieces on  d5 . }
8. Nc3
8. Nc6
9. h3
9. dxc4
10. Bxc4
10. Na5{ Now we will follow with ... Be6 , and White cannot create any initiative with the isolated pawn on  d4 . You have tons of classical games to check and a ridiculous 70% win rate with black in over 300 games. }
