2. c5
3. dxc5{ Since the theory is in constant evolution, we often talk about reversed colors. This move, which would be considered bad, can be interesting as we realize White is playing a Queen's Gambit Accepted reversed. }
3. e6{ As usual, we just want the pawn back. }
4. Nf3( { Against }4.Be3 Qc7 { should be good enough. Friendly reminder that  b4  is never an option as ... a5 ! would force White to push forward and weaken even more the dark squares. } )
4. Bxc5
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Nc3
6. b6( { If you don't feel like playing an isolated pawn with }6...d5 { you can also choose to play first this move.     ... Bb7 , ... d5 , ... Be7 , and then ideally we would have both knights on  d5  and  c5  and push for  Bf6 . It is a very well-known answer against the QGA and can be of use if you don't have experience in this 1.  d4  structures. } )
