[White "11) White Avoids the Benoni - 2.Nf3 With 3.d5"]
[Black "4.e4 Nxe4 5.Bd3 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3{ White wants to keep many options open. I noted in my Catalan course that it is a great move to have a more practical repertoire. }( { Against }2...g6 { white could set up a London }3.Bf4 { or a Torre Attack }3.Bg5 { or going for setups like Zukerkot }3.e3 { or some new trends like }3.Nbd2 { . That way, White can have a more practical approach to the Grunfeld and Kings Indian, which are commonly known as tricky to fight against and very committing. } )( { Against }2...d5 { or }2...e6 { white still can choose to look for setups or switch to main lines with  c2 - c4 . } )( { Usually, White opts for this move to dodge more unbalanced defenses like the Volga/Benko gambit (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 { ) and precisely the Benoni defense. Overall, it's far less committing than 2.  Bf4 , but we will answer it the same way. If you bought this course, you should be ready for trouble. } )
2. c5{ Of course, we challenge directly the center! }( { Starting with }2...e6 { is obviously fine, but it would allow white to do more solid setups like the ones mentioned before (Zukerkot }3.e3 { , London }3.Bf4 { ...), and we will be forced to play more strategic positions. I think it makes more sense to go all-in on unbalanced positions when you start playing the Benoni.     Well, what can I say, It is what I did, and made sense and was obviously more fun. The more you learn and improve in chess you might appreciate calmer positions or different styles, but for a start, it makes sense to stick to similar ideas.     That's why variations like the Accelerated Dragon or the Benko are very appealing for beginners, as you acquire an easy blueprint to focus on learning the other skills required to play better at chess. } )
3. d5{ Looks a bit uncoordinated for White to play  Nf3  and then still play  d5  as White would love to play  e2 - e4 , but it actually has some pros. }( { If we were to follow with the usual plan ( }3...e6 { ), White would have the annoying extra }4.Nc3 { option. After something like }4...exd5 5.Nxd5 Nxd5 6.Qxd5 { White will follow simply with  e2 - e4 ,  Bc4 ,  O-O , and we have a huge hole on the  d5 -square that puts us into the backseat directly.     The  d -pawn will always be weak and exposed, and White's plan is basically developing both bishops and putting the rooks in the center. Whenever your opponent's best plan is to play according to the most basic dogmas (Developing to natural squares, rooks to the center...) it usually means bad news for you if you don't have a very precise answer. } )( { Another question you might have is, what's the difference for White to have the pawn on  c4  or on  c2 ? Let's say we play }3...e6 4.Nc3 { but here we delay ... exd5 , and we go for }4...d6 { as White has less 'presence' on the central squares. Here our opponent would go for }5.e4 { and the missing  c4 -pawn actually serves as a great outpost for the  f3 -knight later on.     Plans like  Nd2 - Nc4  followed by  a2 - a4  constrict a lot of our counterplay on the queenside and put the attention on the  d6 -square. If we exchange the  e -pawns, White would have a pleasant pressure with  Bf4  and if we want to close it up with ... e5 , White would definitely push for  f2 - f4 .     Overall, it is accepted that this setup is far easier and more rewarding for White to press against the Benoni ideas. That's why, against }{   }2.Nc3 { we will definitely not go for }2...c5 { as after }3.d5 { we are left without a proper version of the two main ideas (... b5  and ... e6 ). } )
3. b5( { Since }3...e6 { is not an option, and we rather not let White keep up with  Nc3 - e4  setup, this active move is what we are left with! } )
4. e4{ This is the most challenging variation, given by Le Quang in his course. White gives up a pawn to accelerate the development. Remember, we don't have much presence in the center yet, as we focused on the queenside expansion.     In general, we will be a pawn up and if we defend correctly, White would even suffer as we will pressure  d5 . }
4. Nxe4
5. Bd3{ Taking on  b5  was losing to ... Qa5 +! }
5. Qa5+( { This was needed as }5...Nf6?! 6.Bxb5! { and White has the same outcome as in the variation with 4.  c3 , where our opponent will have a very easy play after  c4 ,  O-O ,  Nc3 ,  Re1  and having in mind to play  dxe6  anytime we try ... e6  or ... e5  push. } )
6. Nbd2{ Our opponent keeps accelerating the development, ours is far from promising for now. }
6. Nf6( 6...Nd6 { was beautifully punished by Le Quang against Firoujza with }7.O-O c4 8.Ne4!! { and White's initiative is decisive. White needs to know very well what he's doing, as punishing our mistakes is far from obvious. } )
7. O-O{ Now White threatens  c2 - c4  (and taking back with the  d2 -knight) and  Re1 , immobilizing us. }( { Taking on  d5  was awful as }7...Nxd5 8.Be4 { we cannot hold the pin any longer, as  Nb3  is on the menu, threatening the queen and  d5  at the same time. } )
7. c4{ We make the bishop occupy the  e -file. We also concede the  d4 -square, so it is definitely a very imbalanced position still. }
8. Be4
8. d6
9. a4{ White keeps the pressure everywhere. This is a very engine move as it technically doesn't threaten anything (the  a4 -pawn is pinned) but forces our queen to stay on  a5  as otherwise the pawn chain ( a6- b5 -c4 ) would break and the  c4 -pawn would fall. }
9. g6{ Once we stop the effect of  Re1  pressuring  e7 , we can try to castle and finish our development. Now, White will try to pressure our exposed queenside pawn structure. }
10. Nd4{ This standard move puts more pressure on Black's queenside pawns. }
10. Bd7( { Better than }10...a6 { . Trust me, I'm an economist. Why would I lie to you? } )
11. Re1
11. Bg7
12. Bf3{ Smoothly, White did manage to renew the pressure on  e7 , and we need to give it up to be safe. }
12. O-O
13. Rxe7{ Le Quang leaves it here, mentioning  Nf1 - Bf4  idea, which can be very annoying. Remember, we need to care about the queenside unstable pawn structure as well. With some precision, I feel Black is more than fine. }
13. Re8
14. Rxe8+
14. Nxe8
15. Nf1
15. bxa4{ We don't want to hold the tension any longer. Our  a4 -pawn would be defended for a while and if our opponent is not careful we will manage to go for ... Na6 -... Nc5  having a menacing threat to White. }
16. c3
16. Qb6{ We don't allow the  c1 -bishop to move, and we aim to take on  d4 !, usually it is bad news for our dark-squares, but doubling the  d -pawn makes it so the  a1 - h8  diagonal is not weak at all, and we can focus on pressuring the weak pawn on  d5 . }
17. Ne3
17. Bxd4
18. cxd4
18. Na6{ We will go for ... Nac7  and there just ... Rb8  or pressuring  d5  or even ... Nb5 !?, is a threat to tackle  d4 . We can admire how both bishops feel a bit stupid and lack activity. }
