3. b5( { Since }3...e6 { is not an option, and we rather not let White keep up with  Nc3 - e4  setup, this active move is what we are left with! } )
4. c3{ I discovered this move thanks to Yosha Iglesias playing against Tregubov and showing how this move order is funnily suggested by the engine. It is also recommended in the KIS 1.  d4  by Sielecki. So, what's the point of  c3 ?, let's see what happens if we play the normal 4... g6 . }
4. g6( 4...Bb7 { runs into the same idea. } )
5. e4{ White sacrifices the central pawn to speed up the development. }
5. Nxe4
6. Bxb5{ If the pawn was on  c2  still, we would have ... Qa5 +!, and we would win a piece. }
6. Bg7
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. Re1
8. Nf6
9. c4{ White wants to keep up with  Nc3  and then see where the  c1 -bishop goes. The most important piece of knowledge for White is to take on  e6  whenever Black plays  e7 -... e5  or  e7 -... e6 , because all the pieces are smoothly pointing to the center and black would regret being so behind on development on the queenside.     It would be very hard to push through the center as usual with  d7 -... d5  after  dxe6 , ... fxe6 . Knowing all this, we understand why 4.  c3  has some serious danger. }
