3. d5{ Looks a bit uncoordinated for White to play  Nf3  and then still play  d5  as White would love to play  e2 - e4 , but it actually has some pros. }( { If we were to follow with the usual plan ( }3...e6 { ), White would have the annoying extra }4.Nc3 { option. After something like }4...exd5 5.Nxd5 Nxd5 6.Qxd5 { White will follow simply with  e2 - e4 ,  Bc4 ,  O-O , and we have a huge hole on the  d5 -square that puts us into the backseat directly.     The  d -pawn will always be weak and exposed, and White's plan is basically developing both bishops and putting the rooks in the center. Whenever your opponent's best plan is to play according to the most basic dogmas (Developing to natural squares, rooks to the center...) it usually means bad news for you if you don't have a very precise answer. } )( { Another question you might have is, what's the difference for White to have the pawn on  c4  or on  c2 ? Let's say we play }3...e6 4.Nc3 { but here we delay ... exd5 , and we go for }4...d6 { as White has less 'presence' on the central squares. Here our opponent would go for }5.e4 { and the missing  c4 -pawn actually serves as a great outpost for the  f3 -knight later on.     Plans like  Nd2 - Nc4  followed by  a2 - a4  constrict a lot of our counterplay on the queenside and put the attention on the  d6 -square. If we exchange the  e -pawns, White would have a pleasant pressure with  Bf4  and if we want to close it up with ... e5 , White would definitely push for  f2 - f4 .     Overall, it is accepted that this setup is far easier and more rewarding for White to press against the Benoni ideas. That's why, against }{   }2.Nc3 { we will definitely not go for }2...c5 { as after }3.d5 { we are left without a proper version of the two main ideas (... b5  and ... e6 ). } )
3. b5( { Since }3...e6 { is not an option, and we rather not let White keep up with  Nc3 - e4  setup, this active move is what we are left with! } )
4. c4{ White can try to transpose to the Benko/Volga gambit. }( { In case of }4.a4 { , you'll notice how in every variation we always play ... b5 -... b4  voluntarily, so you can imagine how good it is for us if White spends an extra tempo to force it! } )
4. b4{ I feel this is the most practical approach as we have a very easy plan moving forward. Otherwise, you might even need to know the full extent of the Benko/Volga, and it doesn't make much sense here to extend ourselves in that quest.     Now we just want to play as if it was a Delayed Benoni (without quick ... e6 ) as we already got so much ground on the queenside, and we might even go for  e7 -... e5  later on to transpose to King's indian-ish structures without needing to worry about the usual  a3 - b4  attack White needs to perform. }( { I played many years ago }4...Qa5+ { with success, which has the same idea to play against }5.Bd2 b4! { . But after }5.Nbd2 bxc4 6.e4! { the engine is very happy, and we can easily be out-prepared. If you don't expect your opponent to know this (I mean this is a very weird move to enter the Benko/Volga, so it is quite likely this is not a feasible option) it can also be a very practical option. } )
5. Nbd2{ If White is not ambitious, it can get quickly into trouble. }
5. g6
6. e4
6. d6
7. Bd3
7. Bg7
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Re1{ This is the most logical sequence of events. }
9. a5{ We will follow up with ... Na6  to fully control the queenside, and then we can proceed with  e7 -... e5  and ... Nh5  to switch our attention to the kingside without having to worry at all for the queenside. }
