1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5{ I'll use this sidelines file to explain to you some strategic concepts and make it worth your time 🙂. You obviously should expect to equalize easily if White doesn't commit to  d4 - d5 , but White has some easy plans that can annoy us some moves away, so I'll try to explain the moves suggested by what White might be thinking. }
3. g3{ White loses the control of the center. We get a reversed Grunfeld where we did not commit to ... Nc6 , so we will gain many tempos thanks to White's knight. }
3. cxd4
4. Bg2{ White might want to delay  Nxd4  until we play ... Nc6 . But we have a very sweet trick that gives us an immediate advantage. }
4. e5{ The pawn is defended due to ... Qa5 +!, now we need to be a bit careful with White giving back the pawn immediately. }
5. c3
5. Nc6( 5...dxc3 { still gives us an edge but after }6.Nxc3 { followed by  Bg5  and  Nd2  white has very good control of the light-squares and can claim some degree of compensation. } )
6. cxd4{ Otherwise we are ready to play  dxc3  followed by  d7 - d5 . }
6. e4
7. Ne5
7. d5{ Look at this majestic pawn center. We can just go for ... Bd6 , ... O-O , ... Re8  and eventually kick the  e5 -knight and proceed with an attack through the kingside as we have full control of the center. }
