2. c5{ I'll use this sidelines file to explain to you some strategic concepts and make it worth your time 🙂. You obviously should expect to equalize easily if White doesn't commit to  d4 - d5 , but White has some easy plans that can annoy us some moves away, so I'll try to explain the moves suggested by what White might be thinking. }
3. c3{ White might hope for a pure London, and we have a couple approaches. }
3. e6{ As a professional chess player I want to suggest as well a very subtle move order that kills the spirit of the London in very few moves, and it is very reliable. Who doesn't love to see a London player regret his choice?, Keymer and Jaime Santos are some strong users of this smart idea. }( 3...Qc7 { this move has the only purpose of dodging the London setup. We will keep up with the usual ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... d6 . It is pretty useful to play like this in fast-paced time controls, especially. }( 3...Qb6 { has a similar effect as it prevents the  c1 -bishop from moving, but it is a bit more punishing if White goes now for  d5 . Funnily enough, NO ONE ever switched to  d5 , so this approach of 'not letting my opponent play his setup' is very effective in practice.     I'd highly recommend you just practice these couple of moves and get a feeling of the positions. It is more focused on annoying our opponent than playing accurately, so it doesn't make much sense for me to give you 'theory' from this point on. } ) )
4. Bf4( { The Torre Attack with }4.Bg5 { is not really scary as we want to play ... h6  anyway }4...d5 { followed by ... h6  should be more than enough. } )
4. Nc6
5. e3
5. h6{ We threaten ... Nh5  getting the sweet dark-squared bishop. }
6. h3
6. d5{ Suddenly we transpose to the usual London including ... h6  and  h3 . Why is that important? White usually wants to play  Bg3  as an answer to ... Bd6  to recapture with the  h -pawn and activate the  h1 -rook, but now it is not an option. }( { It is well-known in the Slav the following variation where Magnus got some good wins,   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 Bg4 5.Nc3 e6 6.Be2!? { threatening  Nh4  }6...h6 7.Bd3! { , I love this small but smart idea that makes our life easy. } )
7. Nbd2
7. Bd6
8. Bxd6( 8.Ne5 { is a bit too much, as after }8...Qc7 { we can play ... Nd7  when needed to free the center and get a pleasant edge as we have more space. } )
8. Qxd6{ Just don't let yourself get  a5 'd like Ding did to Nepo in the World Championship and everything would be fine as we already have more space in the center. }
