4. d6{ In general we prefer to go for  d7 -... d6  so the  f4 -bishop gets out of the game for a while. Plans with ... Be6  and ... Nd5  or  b7 -... b5  are usual to create imbalances where the  f4 -bishop cannot do much about it. }( { Taking on }b2 4...Qxb2 { allows }5.Nge2 { and White has decent compensation. I'd say black is fine as well, but doesn't make much sense to go for those kinds of lines, in my honest opinion. We are happy to have a badly placed knight on  c3 . } )
5. Bb5+{ This is recommended in Alex Banzea's London System. Nothing very special for deviating so much from the average London position. }
5. Bd7
6. a4
6. a6
7. a5{ White wants to get the  b6 -square, so we cannot push  b7 -... b5  and keep a huge island of pawns. }
7. Qc7
8. Bxd7+
8. Nbxd7
9. d5
9. g6{ White already has concrete problems. }( { In the case of }10.Nf3 Nh5! { we get the bishop, so the dark-squares are weak for the rest of the game. } )( { If }10.e4 { we can go for a quick }10...b5! { and after }11.axb6 Qxb6 { white cannot play the smooth }12.Ra2 { (to defend to pawn and prepare for a future pressure on the isolated a pawn) as }12...Nxe4! { is a known trick, }13.Nxe4 Qb4+! { and we gain back the piece. } )
