1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bf4
2. c5{ Obviously. }
3. e3{ The most played move. White wants to maintain his hopes in playing the mighty London setup. }
3. Qb6{ I prefer this move as we move White away from the usual London scheme. }
4. Na3{ This looks like a better version of 4. Nc3  as it allows a future  c2-c3  to fix the pawn structure. }( { The main point after }4.Nc3 Qxb2 { was }5.Nge2! { . }( { Now, White doesn't have anything better than }4.Na3 Qxb2 5.Nb5 Nd5! 6.Rb1 Qxa2 7.Ra1 Qb2 { and White is forced to draw as  a7 -... a6  is coming. } ) )
4. d6{ If you want to play for a win, this is very good as well. }
5. Nc4
5. Qc7
6. c3
6. g6{ We just want to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O . What's up then?     We have 3 points to tackle.      1 . ... Nh5  threatens to win the bishop pair, so White needs to play  h2 - h3  at some point.      2 . ... b5  expansion using the  c4  exposed knight, so White needs to play  a2 - a4 .      3 . If White prevents all our thoughts, we can go for ... Be6  and ... cxd4  (now we get the  b4 -square in case of  cxd4  and in case of  exd4  we have a very sweet plan with ... Bd5 , ... Nc6 , and ... e5 ). }
