1. Nf6
2. Bf4
2. c5{ Obviously. }
3. dxc5
3. e6( 3...Na6 { can find trouble against }4.f3! Nxc5 5.e4 d6 6.Nc3 { and we are in a very weird Sicilian.     I don't think it is logical for me to explain to you the intricacies of the Sicilian, but feel free to try it out! With ... e6 , we threaten the  c5 -pawn. It is intuitively wrong, as it allows 4. Bd6 , but White doesn't have enough development to back it up! } )
4. Bd6( { Trying to get space in the center with }4.Nc3?! Bxc5 5.e4 Qb6! 6.Nh3 d5! { and the  h3 -knight would be exposed later on. } )
4. Bxd6
5. Qxd6( 5.cxd6 Qb6 { we'll get back the pawn as  Qxb2  +  Ne4  getting back the  d6 -pawn are impossible to avoid at the same time. We would be left with a position with a flexible center majority, which is most of the time good news to create imbalances. } )
5. Na6{ We threaten  Qe7  or  Qa5  to get back the  c5 -pawn. }
6. c3( 6.Nc3 Qe7 7.Nb5 Kf8 { looked fancy for White, but in reality, we will just take the  c5 -pawn and White is very far back in development. } )
6. Qe7
7. b4{ White defends the pawn, but it also gets a very poor pawn structure. }
7. b6{ Obviously taking on  d6  and ... Ne4  would get back the pawn, but might be slightly annoying to play around with those weird knights on  d6  and  a6 . }
8. Qxe7+
8. Kxe7
9. cxb6
9. axb6
10. e3
10. d5{ We will follow with ... Bd7  (improving the most important piece to make room for another ones) ... Rfc8  (when would be the  h1 -rook able to play?), and finally we fix the  a6 -knight with ... Nc7 -... Ne8 -... Nd6 , so we get an amazing blockade of the weak  c3 -pawn and full control of  e4  to not allow counterplay. Another idea could be ... Bd7 , ... Nc7 , ... Ra7 , and ... Rha8  to press the  a -pawn.     I wanted to give you this kind of position as an example, as it is present in plenty of openings whenever White or Black takes the  c5  or  c4  pawn and tries to defend it with a pawn. }
