1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3{ In this Benoni course, I don't want to deviate too much from the ideal ... Nf6 , ... c5  against everything, but this move order is hard to justify against 2. Nc3 . White would play  d4 - d5 , and we won't be able to play ... e6  as normally (we said that we don't want to allow White to have a Benoni without  c2 - c4  played, as  exd5  is not even a threat anymore) and  b7 -... b5  won't be a possibility as the  c3 -knight prevents us from it.      Since White committed to 2. Nc3 , playing  c2 - c4  would be significantly harder, therefore our opponent would have a harder time controlling or putting pressure in the center.       Considering all the above, I feel 2... d5  is too good to pass, and we will generally look for ... g6 , ... Bg7  anyway, and  c7 -... c5 . If you are familiar with my courses, you'd like the similarities between the Catalan and this approach. }
2. d5
3. Bg5( { Transposes to the Trompowsky after }3...c5 { . Now we even have an extra option with: } )
3. h6{ Found it on the board. Usually, White wants to play the Trompowsky and follow up with  c2 - c4  after taking on  f6  to seize control of the light squares and have all the pawn chain on the dark squares. It has a similar vibe as the Caro-Kann, where black usually exchanges a bishop and then puts the pawns in the same color to power up the other one.     In this case, the  c3 -knight doesn't combine very well with the setup. Another comparison could be made with the Dutch, in which I have a published course. Black gets a playable position but with the  f7 -pawn on  f5 , which severely limits the flow of the pieces as we could never play ... f6 -... f5  and ... Nd7 -... Nf6  to control the  e4 -square. }
4. Bxf6
4. exf6
5. e3
5. c6
6. Bd3
6. f5
7. Qf3
7. g6
8. h3
8. h5
9. Nge2
9. Nd7
10. Nf4
10. Nf6{ Followed by ... Qc7 , ... Bd6 , and ... O-O .  0-1   (51) Fernandez Soriano,R (2134)-Alonso Rosell,A  (2540) Barcelona 2015 . }
