1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3{ In this Benoni course, I don't want to deviate too much from the ideal ... Nf6 , ... c5  against everything, but this move order is hard to justify against 2. Nc3 . White would play  d4 - d5 , and we won't be able to play ... e6  as normally (we said that we don't want to allow White to have a Benoni without  c2 - c4  played, as  exd5  is not even a threat anymore) and  b7 -... b5  won't be a possibility as the  c3 -knight prevents us from it.      Since White committed to 2. Nc3 , playing  c2 - c4  would be significantly harder, therefore our opponent would have a harder time controlling or putting pressure in the center.       Considering all the above, I feel 2... d5  is too good to pass, and we will generally look for ... g6 , ... Bg7  anyway, and  c7 -... c5 . If you are familiar with my courses, you'd like the similarities between the Catalan and this approach. }
2. d5
3. Bf4{ We enter the famous Jobava London. Lately, it has become very trendy to challenge 1... Nf6  players as it guarantees White to have a somehow solid position and to get away from more critical openings as the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, with little to no effort in preparation.     A couple of years ago I played the World Rapid and Blitz and decided to play only the London (a more aggressive one I might say) as I had no time to prepare much working full time and studying in the university.     I chose this approach to face ... Nf6 , ... g6  players, and I was kinda happy with the outcome. Nowadays, most of the games are decided on the last couple of hours as everyone is really well-prepared, so it is good to have in mind how important are these setups to play games without exhausting yourself too much in the previous hours of the game. }( { White has a couple of silly moves here with }3.e4? Nxe4! { and we don't have any issues developing normally and defending  e4 . } )( { If }3.Nf3 c5! { transposes  to the 1. d4  + 2. Nf3  chapter . } )
3. g6{ As said before we are looking for a fianchetto and castle, then look for the breakthrough  c7 -... c5  as White cannot make use of the  c -file pawn. }
4. Qd2{ This truly is the Jobava London as he played in many occasions. Longcastle quickly, play  Bh6 ,  h4 - h5  and feel like a rockstar. But as the dogma would say, you need control of the center to make a side attack. }
4. Bg7
5. Bh6
5. O-O{ Now  c7 -... c5  is a great counterplay. Allowing ... Qa5  to pressure  a2  and also expand into the center with the ... d5 -... d4 . }
6. h4
6. c5
7. Bxg7
7. Kxg7( { After }8.e3 h5! { once White took control of the center,  h4 - h5  can be an interesting threat. Now we stop it, and we'll go for ... Qa5 , ... Nc6 , ... Rd8  ideas as usual.  0-1   (57) Thorfinnsson,B (2453)-Pichot,A (2548) Chess.com INT 2017 . } )
8. h5
8. cxd4
9. Qxd4
9. Nc6
10. Qh4
10. d4{ The White attack goes nowhere and White is more or less busted as the complete kingside is underdeveloped.  0-1   (50) Bortnyk,O (2598)-Alumert,O (2301) Lichess.org INT 2021 . }
