3. g6{ As said before we are looking for a fianchetto and castle, then look for the breakthrough  c7 -... c5  as White cannot make use of the  c -file pawn. }
4. e3
4. Bg7{ Now, White has 3 main ideas. }( { The intimidating }5.h4 { , the positional }5.Nb5 { and the conventional }5.Nf3 { . } )
5. Nb5{ This is the other approach White looks for. This one is more related to the pure London.     White wants to put our  b8 -knight in a weird spot, so we cannot go for ... c5 , ... Nc6  harmoniously and then do the usual: Playing  h3  to make room for the  f4 -bishop and then finish the development calmly in the kingside to follow up with  e3 - e4  or  c2 - c4  depending on the situation.     It is not scary, but the idea is just to have a simple game with all the pieces on the board without much effort. So we'll try to create a challenge quickly, so our opponent cannot relax too much. }
5. Na6
6. Nf3
6. O-O{ ... Nh5  is a serious threat now. }
7. Be2{ White can ignore our threat, but with a great cost. }
7. Nh5
8. Bg5
8. f6{ This move would be very efficient to play  e7 -... e5  later on. }
9. Bh4
9. g5
10. Bg3( 10.Nd2!? { doesn't change much, the outcome after }10...gxh4 11.Bxh5 e5 12.c3 c6 { and we have all the control in the center again. Black could've adapted including ... Kh8 , ... Rg8  quickly to justify the open  g -file. The position is incredibly good without it anyway, having a bishop pair and the center.  0-1   (31) Touzane,O (2270)-Garriga Cazorla,P (2445) Barcelona 2019 . } )
10. c6
11. Nc3
11. e5{ Suddenly we got so much space in the center and a very promising position. Taking on  a6  is not very appealing as we'll get the  b -file and also can reroute the  a -rook into the kingside as we'll try to take on  g3  and play ... e5 -... e4 , ... f5 -... f4 , and huge attacks.     An interesting prophylactic approach would be to take on  g3  and then put the  a8 -rook on  e7  and queen on  e8 , why?, because White would eventually need to play  f3  or  f4  to stop our attack, so we will be able to take and then pressure the exposed  e3 -pawn. }
12. Nd2
12. Nxg3
13. hxg3
13. Nc7{ A small weakness on the kingside (the  h5 -square) means nothing if we have all the space in the center and White pieces cannot access the kingside at all.  0-1   (42) Nihal,S (2670)-Giri,A (2764) Chess.com INT 2022 . }
