2. Nc3{ In this Benoni course, I don't want to deviate too much from the ideal ... Nf6 , ... c5  against everything, but this move order is hard to justify against 2. Nc3 . White would play  d4 - d5 , and we won't be able to play ... e6  as normally (we said that we don't want to allow White to have a Benoni without  c2 - c4  played, as  exd5  is not even a threat anymore) and  b7 -... b5  won't be a possibility as the  c3 -knight prevents us from it.      Since White committed to 2. Nc3 , playing  c2 - c4  would be significantly harder, therefore our opponent would have a harder time controlling or putting pressure in the center.       Considering all the above, I feel 2... d5  is too good to pass, and we will generally look for ... g6 , ... Bg7  anyway, and  c7 -... c5 . If you are familiar with my courses, you'd like the similarities between the Catalan and this approach. }
2. d5
3. Bf4{ We enter the famous Jobava London. Lately, it has become very trendy to challenge 1... Nf6  players as it guarantees White to have a somehow solid position and to get away from more critical openings as the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, with little to no effort in preparation.     A couple of years ago I played the World Rapid and Blitz and decided to play only the London (a more aggressive one I might say) as I had no time to prepare much working full time and studying in the university.     I chose this approach to face ... Nf6 , ... g6  players, and I was kinda happy with the outcome. Nowadays, most of the games are decided on the last couple of hours as everyone is really well-prepared, so it is good to have in mind how important are these setups to play games without exhausting yourself too much in the previous hours of the game. }( { White has a couple of silly moves here with }3.e4? Nxe4! { and we don't have any issues developing normally and defending  e4 . } )( { If }3.Nf3 c5! { transposes  to the 1. d4  + 2. Nf3  chapter . } )
3. g6{ As said before we are looking for a fianchetto and castle, then look for the breakthrough  c7 -... c5  as White cannot make use of the  c -file pawn. }
4. e3
4. Bg7{ Now, White has 3 main ideas. }( { The intimidating }5.h4 { , the positional }5.Nb5 { and the conventional }5.Nf3 { . } )
5. Nf3{ White can also just stick to the common London, with the extra investment in  Nc3  to force us to play  d7 -... d5 . }
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c5( { Obviously }6...Nh5 { could also be possible, but White has better development, so we stick to a Catalan-ish development. We also have a trick in mind, as now 7. Nb5  is very appealing. } )
7. Nb5{ It is not a problem to defend  c7 , the real problem after  Na6  is how are we stuck in the queenside and the  b5 -knight freezes both the  a6 -knight (to defend  c7 ) and the  a8 -rook (to defend  a7 ). }( { As usual, }7.dxc5 { can be countered by }7...Qa5 { . } )( { Now }7.Ne5 { is less threatening as there is no attack in the kingside but taking on  d4  and looking for the usual with ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 , ... Rc8  is excellent. I want to extend a bit in this kind of position, as I cover it extensively in my Catalan course.     After we achieve step one, we might be one to secure the  f5 -bishop position, as playing  e7 -... e6  might imply trapping it. So we'll need to consider ... h6 , ... g5  as a safe way to give cover to the light-squared bishop, and eventually push for ... Ne4 , ... f5  later on. } )
7. cxd4{ Such a huge surprise for White! }( { Why do we want to take instead of }7...Nc6 { you might ask. Because now }8.Nc7 { really forces a draw as }8...Nh5 { doesn't really treat the  f4 -bishop entirely. } )
8. Nc7( { After }8.exd4 Nc6 { and we'll aim to play ... Ne4 , ... a6 , ... f6 , ... e5 . The draw threat with ... Nc7 -... Nb5  doesn't really work, as we can always go for ... Nh5  and take the  f4 -bishop while the knight is left stuck on  a8 . } )
8. dxe3{ We rely on the  a8 -knight not getting away and getting as many pawns as possible in exchange for the exchange down. 🙂 }
9. Nxa8
9. exf2+
10. Kf1{ Taking on  f2  would inevitably face the consequences of ... Ne4  or ... Ng4 +. }( { After }10.Kxf2 e5! 11.Nxe5 g5! { and we get back a piece and the  a8 -knight is still trapped. } )
10. Nc6{ We already have great compensation, as not being allowed to castle makes it incredibly hard for White to put the rooks into play. }
11. Nc7
11. d4{ As ... Nh5  fails against  Nxd5 ! }
12. h3
12. Nh5
13. Bh2
13. e5
14. Nb5
14. a6
15. Na3
15. e4{ Black is a rook down but tell me one thing, when would be those rooks relevant? Now ... Nf6 -... Nd5  and aiming for ... Ne3  or threats through the  a7 - g1  diagonal is crushing. }
