1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3{ In this Benoni course, I don't want to deviate too much from the ideal ... Nf6 , ... c5  against everything, but this move order is hard to justify against 2. Nc3 . White would play  d4 - d5 , and we won't be able to play ... e6  as normally (we said that we don't want to allow White to have a Benoni without  c2 - c4  played, as  exd5  is not even a threat anymore) and  b7 -... b5  won't be a possibility as the  c3 -knight prevents us from it.      Since White committed to 2. Nc3 , playing  c2 - c4  would be significantly harder, therefore our opponent would have a harder time controlling or putting pressure in the center.       Considering all the above, I feel 2... d5  is too good to pass, and we will generally look for ... g6 , ... Bg7  anyway, and  c7 -... c5 . If you are familiar with my courses, you'd like the similarities between the Catalan and this approach. }
2. d5
3. Bf4{ We enter the famous Jobava London. Lately, it has become very trendy to challenge 1... Nf6  players as it guarantees White to have a somehow solid position and to get away from more critical openings as the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, with little to no effort in preparation.     A couple of years ago I played the World Rapid and Blitz and decided to play only the London (a more aggressive one I might say) as I had no time to prepare much working full time and studying in the university.     I chose this approach to face ... Nf6 , ... g6  players, and I was kinda happy with the outcome. Nowadays, most of the games are decided on the last couple of hours as everyone is really well-prepared, so it is good to have in mind how important are these setups to play games without exhausting yourself too much in the previous hours of the game. }( { White has a couple of silly moves here with }3.e4? Nxe4! { and we don't have any issues developing normally and defending  e4 . } )( { If }3.Nf3 c5! { transposes  to the 1. d4  + 2. Nf3  chapter . } )
3. g6{ As said before we are looking for a fianchetto and castle, then look for the breakthrough  c7 -... c5  as White cannot make use of the  c -file pawn. }
4. e3
4. Bg7{ Now, White has 3 main ideas. }( { The intimidating }5.h4 { , the positional }5.Nb5 { and the conventional }5.Nf3 { . } )
5. h4{ This is a modern trend popularized by the young Indians and Bortnik (an online specialist). White wants to push  h4 - h5  and sacrifice the exchange. Suddenly after  Qxh5 - Bd3 - Nf3 , White minor pieces surround all the Kingside and the rooks are somewhat useless as the White pieces spread quickly through the board and the White queen has a great impact. }
5. h5{ We want none of that. White claims that including both moves ( h4 , ... h5 ) is a benefit for White and also works as a way to prevent the typical ... Nh5  winning the dark-squared bishop. But in general, I would recommend my students to just castle and then go for ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 , and White is never really prepared to take on  c5  and get something out of it.     We have an insane control of the  g4 -square, so this breakthrough is very far away and even if White manages to play  g4 , we also have  h5 -defended, so another layer of defense is needed to break our kingside. }
6. Nf3
6. O-O
7. Ne5{ The main goal for White might be playing  Qd2 - f3 - O-O-O  and then trying to push  g2 - g4  or even  e3 - e4  if we are too passive. }( { White has an alternative move order in }7.Qd2 c5! 8.dxc5 Nbd7! { and we will regain the pawn, and we'll have too much presence in the center. Including  h4 , ... h5  also means it is kinda forced for White to castle long, so losing control of the center makes it worrisome, as our attack on the queenside would be very easy in comparison. If }9.Nxd5?? Nxd5 10.Qxd5 Bxb2 { and Black is almost winning after ... Bc3 + and trying to capture the  c5 -pawn later. } )
7. c5{ As usual, we aim for striking the center as if it was a Catalan. }
8. Qd2
8. Nc6{ What I like about this line, is that it is kind of similar to the Benoni. We just want to develop pieces, and we don't care about anything else. After ... Bf5  and ... Rc8 , we have all the pieces developed ideally. I'll show you a game I lost where I learned the hard way how effective is this simple approach. }( 9.f3 Bf5 10.dxc5 Qa5 11.Bb5 Nxe5 12.Bxe5 a6 13.Bd3 Bxd3 14.Qxd3 Qxc5 15.O-O-O e6 16.Kb1 Rac8 17.Qe2 Nd7 18.Bxg7 Kxg7 19.g4 Rh8 20.g5 Ne5 21.Rde1 Nc4 22.Nd1 Rhd8 23.Qd3 d4 24.exd4 Rxd4 25.Qc3 Nd2+ 26.Kc1 Qxc3 27.Nxc3 Nxf3 28.Re4 Rcc4 29.Re3 Nxh4 30.b3 Nf5 31.Rf3 Rc8 32.Re1 Rg4 {  0-1   (32) Alonso Rosell,A (2570)-Ivic,V (2606) Warsaw 2021 . } )
