[White "15) Trompowsky"]
[Black "3.Nc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5{ The Trompowsky is known as a cheap way to face the Indian variations after 1... Nf6 . Looks menacing, but usually relies on strategical imbalances, considering the doubled pawns or giving up the bishop pair for more space in the center. }( { I'd say we have many good moves, like }2...d5!? { or even }2...e6!? { but I wanted to keep up with the spirit of the Benoni and also feel we will have more interesting positions with }2...c5!? { as we will force our opponent to play precisely and not relax and develop calmly. } )
2. c5{ I've been playing this line for as long as I have memory. It reaches some weird positions, and we aim to pressure immediately the queenside through ... Qb6 . White has a couple of approaches at first glance. Going for  d4 - d5  ideas or looking for a sideline. I like to follow the spirit of the Benoni as much as I can, and this is no exception. }
3. Nc3{ I remember facing this line many times in online games when I was 12-13, and it always intimidated me when I took on  d4  and suddenly the queen came out, and then  Qh4  came next, and suddenly long castle is the next, AND HOW I WAS GETTING MATED AGAIN.     With precise play (that involves ... h6  and unpinning yourself with ... Rg8 ) you could play it, but I feel it is a great excuse to go back to  d7 -... d5  and immediately challenge the center and take advantage of a suboptimal knight on  c3 . Since we play it against 2.  Nc3 , it shouldn't come as a surprise for you. }
3. d5( 3...Qb6 { now faces the annoying }4.d5! { and after }4...Qxb2 5.Bd2 { is an extremely risky variation that EVERY Trompowsky player dreams of playing.  e4 - f4  is coming and White would enjoy an attacking game.     Now White has different ways to mess with our recently acquired center. We mostly want to retake on  f6  with the  g -pawn, but there is an interesting exception. } )
4. Bxf6
4. gxf6
5. e3{ Usually, White is very happy to make us double the  f -pawns and wants to proceed with  Qh5  and long castle. }( { In the case of the hungry }5.dxc5? { we are very happy to get even more space with }5...d4! { and White is already facing severe problems of development (as  e2 - e3  is practically impossible, White doesn't want to have an isolated pawn on  e3 ), and we will take  c5  whenever we want, as we can simply follow up with ... Nc6 , ... f5 , and ... e5 . } )
5. cxd4
6. exd4
6. Bf5{ With this subtle move we are into a very smooth play after ... e6 , ... Nc6 , ... Qc7 , ... O-O-O , and eventually a push into the center. Having no dark-squared bishop and a poorly placed knight on  c3  makes it very hard for White to create any kind of threat through the queenside. We might also enjoy the  g -file for late fights. }
