7. Qxc5
8. Qa4+
8. Nc6{ Here White realizes that  Qxe4  is not possible as the  g5 -bishop is hanging. }
9. Be3{ Luckily for White, we have no way to keep the extra pawn, as the logical ... Qe5  is faced with  Bb5 !, and  O-O-O , and suddenly the engine praises significantly what White is doing. }
9. Qa5
10. Qxe4
10. g6{ We'll put both bishops in the diagonals pointing  a1  and  b1  and the Queen likely would end up con  c7  and our rooks on  c  and  d . It's a very solid and nice setup for all our pieces. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Trompowsky"]
[Black "3.Nc3 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5{ The Trompowsky is known as a cheap way to face the Indian variations after 1... Nf6 . Looks menacing, but usually relies on strategical imbalances, considering the doubled pawns or giving up the bishop pair for more space in the center. }( { I'd say we have many good moves, like }2...d5!? { or even }2...e6!? { but I wanted to keep up with the spirit of the Benoni and also feel we will have more interesting positions with }2...c5!? { as we will force our opponent to play precisely and not relax and develop calmly. } )
2. c5{ I've been playing this line for as long as I have memory. It reaches some weird positions, and we aim to pressure immediately the queenside through ... Qb6 . White has a couple of approaches at first glance. Going for  d4 - d5  ideas or looking for a sideline. I like to follow the spirit of the Benoni as much as I can, and this is no exception. }
3. Nc3{ I remember facing this line many times in online games when I was 12-13, and it always intimidated me when I took on  d4  and suddenly the queen came out, and then  Qh4  came next, and suddenly long castle is the next, AND HOW I WAS GETTING MATED AGAIN.     With precise play (that involves ... h6  and unpinning yourself with ... Rg8 ) you could play it, but I feel it is a great excuse to go back to  d7 -... d5  and immediately challenge the center and take advantage of a suboptimal knight on  c3 . Since we play it against 2.  Nc3 , it shouldn't come as a surprise for you. }
3. d5( 3...Qb6 { now faces the annoying }4.d5! { and after }4...Qxb2 5.Bd2 { is an extremely risky variation that EVERY Trompowsky player dreams of playing.  e4 - f4  is coming and White would enjoy an attacking game.     Now White has different ways to mess with our recently acquired center. We mostly want to retake on  f6  with the  g -pawn, but there is an interesting exception. } )
4. e3
4. cxd4{ This concrete approach makes it quite simple to remember everything. }
5. exd4( 5.Qxd4!? { having invested a tempo with  e2 - e3  makes this move less frightening }5...Nc6 6.Qh4? { now it suddenly loses }6...Ne4 { White cannot retake twice on  e4  as ... Qa5 + wins a piece and also ... f6 , ... e5  is coming, letting the  Qh4  out of the game and seizing complete dominance in the center. The queenside would be extremely exposed without the bishop and the queen being able to defend. } )
5. Nc6( { Now }5...Bf5 { with the aim of transposing with 6.  Bxf6  might be faced with }6.Bd3!? { and White might enjoy retaking on  d3  with the queen and castling long to have decent attacking chances. } )
6. Bxf6{ Other moves might be answered with  Bg4 - e6 , completing the development. As long as the  c3 -knight is there, we enjoy a very comfortable strategic advantage, as it is close to useless. }
6. exf6{ This move is technically a novelty at this point. }( { We don't want to allow White to have }6...gxf6 7.Qh5!? { we should be fine there, but it makes it far easier for White to play. }{ What's the point of playing 6... exf6  and isolating the  d5 -pawn, you might ask? Usually, it is considered a risky capture as it allows White in some move orders to play  dxc5  and just focus on attacking the isolated  d5 -pawn. The engine can hold it but looks very bad in practice as we barely have any counterplay.     In this case, though, White has a pawn on  d4 , so the attack on  d5  is less relevant and the isolated pawn is far less exposed. Our general plan is very simple as our bishops would cover  e6  and  d6  and the rooks would go to  e8  and  c8 . The knight likely goes to  e7  later on to control  d5  better, but some other destinations might be interesting depending on how White plays.  Qb6  would always be tricky to face as we pressure  b2  and  d4 .       In general, we have a very solid kingside and White has no real play to progress at all, so we have the pace of the game. } )
