8. Nd7{ Now we have maximum flexibility and White has different ways to play. You need to know some things here.        1 . Moving our queen away to  a5  or  b4  and then looking for a Benko/ Volga with  b7 -... b5  is very tricky for White in practice. Bear in mind, that we also have an exposed pawn on  f5 . }( {  2 . The first point also threatens  Bxc3+! , you might be familiar with the line   }1.d4 g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c5 4.d5 Bxc3+!? 5.bxc3 f5!? { , where Black gives up the bishop pair but in exchange completely shuts down the main  a1 - h8  diagonal and severely weakens the pawn structure of the opponent.     The mentioned line usually gets into trouble as Black is a bit late to control the center or a flank attack with  h2 - h4 , but in the case of the Trompowsky, we already have good control of the center and even better development.      3 . White win condition is not really clear. It relies on securing all our threats and finishing the development. Only then pressure the  f5 -pawn to force us to react with  e7 -... e6  for instance, and then make use of how inflexible our pawn structure is (as we don't really want to play ... exd5  and let the  f -doubled pawns isolated). It's a really long-term hope, as both  Nc3  and  Bf1  are completely defensive with the  c4 - d5  structure. } )
9. Nf3
9. Nf6{ Now the knight on  f3  would have a better square in case of ... Qb4  with  Nd2  and the ... Bxc3  threat would be far less annoying. With 9... Nf6  we aim for ... Ne4  to make use of the great  h8 - a1  diagonal. }
10. Bd3( 10.Nd2 { doesn't even prevent ... Ne4 . } )
10. Ne4
11. Bxe4
11. fxe4
12. Nd2
12. f5{ Now we have two ideas. I'd start with ... Bd7  and ... Qa5 , so we can just castle short and go for ... a6 , ... b5 . If White tackles the center quickly with  f2 - f3 , we can even castle long and go for  e7 -... e6 . We'll be gifted with an excellent dark-squared bishop and the  g -file to attack our opponent. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Trompowsky"]
[Black "3.Bxf6 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5{ The Trompowsky is known as a cheap way to face the Indian variations after 1... Nf6 . Looks menacing, but usually relies on strategical imbalances, considering the doubled pawns or giving up the bishop pair for more space in the center. }( { I'd say we have many good moves, like }2...d5!? { or even }2...e6!? { but I wanted to keep up with the spirit of the Benoni and also feel we will have more interesting positions with }2...c5!? { as we will force our opponent to play precisely and not relax and develop calmly. } )
2. c5{ I've been playing this line for as long as I have memory. It reaches some weird positions, and we aim to pressure immediately the queenside through ... Qb6 . White has a couple of approaches at first glance. Going for  d4 - d5  ideas or looking for a sideline. I like to follow the spirit of the Benoni as much as I can, and this is no exception. }
3. Bxf6
3. gxf6( { I really despise }3...exf6 { as }4.dxc5 { makes it incredibly hard for black to crack White's position and the isolated  d -pawn would ALWAYS be a target for our opponent. } )
4. d5{ White doesn't really have a pleasant alternative. }( { In case of }4.c3 d5 { would give us a fantastic center. } )( { If }4.e3 { we can even go further with }4...cxd4 5.exd4 Qb6 { and White is already worse and facing problems to defend. } )( 4.dxc5 { deserves a light commentary as it is quite forced after }4...e6 5.Nd2 Bxc5 6.Ne4 { to occupy the  d6 -square }6...Bb4+! 7.c3 d5! { and we get an impressive center, or we keep the bishop pair. } )( { Finally }4.Nc3 { doesn't do much with the  Bxf6  move already made, as now }4...cxd4 5.Qxd4 Nc6 6.Qd2 e6 7.e4 a6 { would give us an insane advantage as it is like a Taimanov where we own all the dark-squares and the flexibility of the Sicilian. }( 6.Qh4 { is less effective }6...f5! { , and  e7 -... e6  would just seize control of everything: light-squares, dark-squares, center, and bishop pair. } ) )
4. Qb6{ The most challenging approach. We could calmly go for ... d6 , ... f5 , ... Nd7 , and  Nf6 , but White has some claims of advantage. The real issue of our doubled pawns relies on not being able to expand easily. If we want to play  e7 -... e5 , the  f5  hole would be very punishing.     If we do it instead with the pawn already on  f5 , White often can tackle that pawn anyway or force us to play ... e5 -... e4  to keep it alive. With that, we achieve the excellent  e5 -square for the knight or the dark-squared bishop, but we also need to be aware of the doubled  f -pawns. We are fine overall, but it is important to be conscious of the weakness of our position. }
5. Qc1{ The most played move and the one usually recommended in chess courses for White. }( { With }5.b3 { , White weakens the dark squares, so we are just happy to go for }5...f5 { and keep up with ... Qg6 , ... Bg7  and then ... d6 , ... Nd7 - Nf6 - Ne4  }6.e3 Qg6 { .     After  b2-b3 , our queen already did his job on  b6  and will be more helpful to coordinate our exposed pawns on the kingside. }( { In case of the odd sacrifice, }5.Nd2 { you just take on  b2  and remember to play ... Bh6  and ... d6  to finish the development quickly as we are spending a lot of tempos with the Queen. } ) )
5. f5{ We immediately open the  a1 - h8  diagonal and also open up the possibility for ... Bh6 !?. }( { Here }5...Bh6 { has been played many times taking advantage of the  Qc1  being forced to defend  b2  and had an interesting vibe as }6.e3 f5!? { threatening ... f5 -... f4 . But overall it did not age well as just }7.Ne2 { is very good and logical, and we played the less flexible move order of all. } )
6. c4{ White makes room for the knight on  c3 . It weakens the dark-squares, but it also makes it very hard for us to ever compete for the  d5 -square. We need to play actively accurate. }
6. d6
7. Nc3
7. Bg7
8. e3
8. Nd7{ Now we have maximum flexibility and White has different ways to play. You need to know some things here.        1 . Moving our queen away to  a5  or  b4  and then looking for a Benko/ Volga with  b7 -... b5  is very tricky for White in practice. Bear in mind, that we also have an exposed pawn on  f5 . }( {  2 . The first point also threatens  Bxc3+! , you might be familiar with the line   }1.d4 g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c5 4.d5 Bxc3+!? 5.bxc3 f5!? { , where Black gives up the bishop pair but in exchange completely shuts down the main  a1 - h8  diagonal and severely weakens the pawn structure of the opponent.     The mentioned line usually gets into trouble as Black is a bit late to control the center or a flank attack with  h2 - h4 , but in the case of the Trompowsky, we already have good control of the center and even better development.      3 . White win condition is not really clear. It relies on securing all our threats and finishing the development. Only then pressure the  f5 -pawn to force us to react with  e7 -... e6  for instance, and then make use of how inflexible our pawn structure is (as we don't really want to play ... exd5  and let the  f -doubled pawns isolated). It's a really long-term hope, as both  Nc3  and  Bf1  are completely defensive with the  c4 - d5  structure. } )
9. Qc2{ Is the best move for White and the most played. White improves the queen and keeps the flexibility of the  g1 -knight, so he can adapt. }
9. Qa5( { For instance now }9...Nf6?! 10.Bd3! Ne4?! 11.Nge2! { is perfect for White, and the  f5 -pawn would suffer eventually. With 9... Qa5  we have some extra options in comparison with  Qb4  directly. } )
10. Nge2
10. b5{ As announced, we shift to more spicy positions. Now we want to prevent White from castling quickly and to consolidate the queenside. }
11. cxb5
11. a6
12. bxa6
12. Bxa6
13. Nf4
13. O-O{ Taking on  f1  would help White, as  g3 - Kg2  fits perfectly in White structure. }
14. Bxa6
14. Qxa6{ White NEEDS to castle quickly. }
15. Nfe2
15. Bxc3+
16. Nxc3( { If }16.bxc3 Qc4! { and we'll be getting back material. } )
16. Ne5
17. Rd1
17. Kh8{ White doesn't really have a quick way to castle, and we have both ... Rfb8  and ... Rg8  to increase the pressure. }( { In the case of }18.Qxf5 Rg8 19.g3 Rg5! { would be a great way to punish White for having the king in the center. } )
