12. Nf8{ We adapt quickly and aim to play ... Ng6  and fix our pawn structure. Now White needs to free the  c2 -Queen from being chained to the defense of the  c3 -pawn, or we would win strategically as White would be left with the worst pawn structure without anything in exchange. }
13. Rc1
13. e4{ We defend the  f5 -pawn, and White still needs to do something about ... Ng6 . }
14. g4{ Only move. }( { Playing   }13.g3?! Ng6 14.Ng2 { would mean assuming a passive role for the rest of the game. We can just castle long and then look for pressure with ... Ne5  in both flanks.     Don't be too much in a hurry with  h7 - h5 , as it will be left permanently attacking for a while if White can simply play  h2 - h4 . Now we need to play accurately as we have all our pieces in the first rank. } )
14. Rg8
15. Nxf5
15. Bxf5
16. gxf5
16. O-O-O{ We finish the development and White is left with the king in the center and a very bad bishop. But Àlvar, we lose 2 pawns here! Let's take a look. }
17. Qxe4
17. Nd7{ As usual, we focus on improve the worst piece, one at a time. }
18. Qc2
18. Rde8{ The knight is ready to jump when needed, and we'll keep up with ... Qd8 !, and after prophylaxis like ... Kb8  to have it all defended, our queen would infiltrate into the exposed kingside.     Funny how White would love to exchange the queens now as it is not easy to access the Kingside. White has too much freedom and no obvious plan at all, so it is definitely a tricky position, as both extra pawns don't translate to any significant advantage. The  h1 -rook is very sad, and the piece coordination is completely lacking for White. }
