[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5{ The Trompowsky is known as a cheap way to face the Indian variations after 1... Nf6 . Looks menacing, but usually relies on strategical imbalances, considering the doubled pawns or giving up the bishop pair for more space in the center. }( { I'd say we have many good moves, like }2...d5!? { or even }2...e6!? { but I wanted to keep up with the spirit of the Benoni and also feel we will have more interesting positions with }2...c5!? { as we will force our opponent to play precisely and not relax and develop calmly. } )
2. c5{ I've been playing this line for as long as I have memory. It reaches some weird positions, and we aim to pressure immediately the queenside through ... Qb6 . White has a couple of approaches at first glance. Going for  d4 - d5  ideas or looking for a sideline. I like to follow the spirit of the Benoni as much as I can, and this is no exception. }
3. d5
3. d6( 3...Qb6 { is the most played move, but without  Bxf6  ... gxf6  included it doesn't appeal to me as much as White can go for }4.Nc3! { I discovered ... d6  many years ago thanks to David Antón. The concept is simple, we just want to play as a delayed Benoni where White's dark-squared bishop is not really optimally developed. } )( { I wanted to mention }3...Ne4 { as it is quite trendy recently, but not as simple as this one, and we get special benefit from knowing the structures very well!. } )
4. Nc3
4. h6{ Since we don't really mind White taking on  f6 , we force the bishop to look for a better square, and none of them are really attractive. }
5. Bc1{ We get to a technically bad position (as we don't play 2... c5  against 2. Nc3  for that reason) but with a couple extra tempos that help us immensely. }
5. g6
6. e4
6. Bg7
7. Bc4( 7.Bb5+ { is a common theme but with the extra tempo we are in time to play ... Bd7 , castle, and  e7 -... e6  with ease. } )
7. O-O{ Here White has a couple of options. }
8. Nge2( { If }8.Nf3 { simply going for }8...Re8 { and  e7 -... e6  is more than enough. Having the tempo  h7 -... h6  for free makes it, so we don't need to worry about futures where White gets access to the  d5 -square (in this case we would want to play ... Bxe6  and ... Rxe6 , as playing ... fxe6 +... d5  is a dream with White's setup) and also is allowed to play  Bg5  to lose it up even more. } )
8. Nbd7{ Now we go for ... Nb6  and ... e6  instead, as White needs to pay attention to ... Nb6 +... c4  threat. }
9. Ng3
9. Nb6
10. Be2
10. e6
11. a4
11. exd5
12. exd5
12. a6{ Our goal is to play ... Ne8 - ... Kh7  and  f7 -... f5 . We will get a lot of key squares in the center and also more space for our pieces. Later on, we will push for the queenside as usual. ... Ne8  and ... f5  are very common plans in these structures, but usually White is some tempos ahead, or we need to worry about  Ng5  or  Nf4  making use of the  e6  hole we leave. }
