9. Bd3
9. Nc6
10. O-O
10. b6( 10...Nd4 { has been considered the mainline, mostly thanks to Kasparov winning with it, but this simple move makes it very easy. I love the idea of playing ... Rb8 -... Rb7  and defend the 7th rank efficiently.     One of the most typical attacking patterns I learned with White was to play  Ng5  combined with  e4 - e5 . Then the  f6 -knight, leaving the king vulnerable to  Nxh7 !, and  Qh5 + following. This won't be possible with the  c6 -knight alive, and White doesn't really have many active plans, as  e4 - e5  would always create a very weak and exposed pawn on  e5 . } )
