1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. g6{ The Delayed Benoni has many benefits and some drawbacks. First and foremost, it allows you to dodge entirely the critical lines on the  f4 - Bb5 + variation.     Let's say you need to have a challenging game, but you are playing against an obsessed Chessable course-devourer, you might want to dodge that bullet and have a longer game for a very little price I would say. This turned out to be a very practical approach, and I faced it many, many times.  Delaying  e7 -... e6  has a main drawback: It allows White to play  e2 - e4  in time to recapture on  d5 .      Why is that a problem?  The pawn structure would be less imbalanced and basically white would just have more space. We won't be worrying much about the  e4 - e5  push, but we won't be able to create any significant counterplay through the queenside either.      Why is it problematic?  Technically we would still need to have some extra space for the  Bc8  and  Nb8 , so exchanging a couple of pieces would be, as usual, a priority. White can put us under severe pressure but requires quite a lot of practice.       Why did I add this alternative?  I think it makes a lot of sense to have it as it definitely has the Benoni flavor, and you might transpose it to what's shown in the main lines. Maybe you want to play the Benoni next week quicker, and you are worried about critical lines, maybe you want to confuse your opponent.     It's often been considered the worst version, but recently Aronian, Sindarov, and Rapport specially have been testing it extensively, therefore some charm must have! }
4. Nc3
4. Bg7
5. e4
5. d6{ Now, White has many options at stake. We prefer delaying castle, as some transpositions require us to play a quick ... e6  before castling. }
6. h3{ This is one of the most played variations. White prevents any kind of ... Bg4  exchanging bishops and wants to keep up with  Bd3 - Nf3  setup. }
6. O-O
7. Bd3
7. e6
8. Nf3
8. exd5
9. exd5( { After }9.cxd5 b5! { and we get into our theory. I have 7 classical games in this position with White.     I will give 3 different approaches that can be of use. This is one of the critical positions, and you might find yourself here pretty often. } )
9. Re8+
10. Be3( 10.Kf1 { doesn't make much sense now, as we can counter through the queenside with ... Na6 , ... Bd7 , ... b5 . } )
10. Rxe3+{ This bizarre idea was first tested with success by Klaus Bischoff in the 80s. Then it went undercover until Morozevich visited the idea from time to time. Recently, Rapport, Duda, and Eirigaisi toyed with the idea in some games. Black gives up the exchange and tries to seize control of the dark squares and the powerful  g7 -bishop.     This is super hard to crack for White in faster time controls. Objectively it should be bad for Black, but you can score many surprising results if you know what you are doing here. }
11. fxe3
11. Qe7
12. O-O( { The first common mistake is now playing }12.e4?? { after }12...Nbd7 { Black is already in control and ... Nh5 , ... Ne5  plan would make sure we invade White position with success. Surprisingly Wojtaszek, a really well-known theorist and player, played it not once but twice!, so it might definitely still surprise your opponent. } )
12. Nbd7{ As in  Bh6 , we want to secure the dark-squares, not opening the  e -file to face the White rooks. }
13. Qd2
13. Nh5( 13...b6 { is the most solid and practical approach. Black wants to develop the  c8 -bishop (likely to  a6  to pressure  c4  to avoid  Bc2 - Ba4  maneouvre) and then play ... Rf8  to secure the  f7 -pawn as  Rf2 - Raf1  is coming.     Later on, looking for ... Ne5 , exchanging knights, and then trying to play again ... Nd7 -... Ne5  would always be the dream to achieve. There, White would have a very hard time trying to make use of the rooks without files open.     I'd say you can play this move blindly and later on look for 13...  Nh5  if you prefer it. }13...Nh5 { has been the move chosen by Rapport and Panstulaia (an institution in all the lines after  d4 -... c5  I would say).     It is even riskier and 'worse' objectively, but it creates so much havoc and confusion. Black wants to play ... Ng3  and then ... Ne5 . The dream would be following it up with ... h5 -... h4  having immense control of the dark-squares. } )
14. Ne2{ White can prevent us from playing ... Ng3 , but we can brute force it. }
14. Bh6
15. Nf4
15. Ng3
16. Rfe1
16. Nf6{ We suddenly have a great blockade on  e4  and both White knights are pretty much useless. Our next moves are pretty simple and White has decent chances to screw it up quickly.     0-1   (42) Thybo,J (2525)-Berkes,F (2666) Skopje 2019 . }
