4. Nc3
4. Bg7
5. e4
5. d6{ Now, White has many options at stake. We prefer delaying castle, as some transpositions require us to play a quick ... e6  before castling. }
6. Bd3{ This setup followed by  Nge2  can also be a possibility with White. Whenever we have issues developing the  c8 -bishop, it is interesting. }
6. e6
7. Nge2
7. exd5
8. exd5
8. Ng4{ I'd say this is the easiest way to counter White's plan. Ideally,  O-O - Bg5 - f4 - Ng3  would be crushing as  f4 - f5  is too big of a threat, and remember we have no counter-plan on the queenside as ... b5  is completely secured by our opponent. We will play castle and then  f5  to get some space in the center for our pieces.     Ideally, the setup would be ... Ne5 , ... Nd7 -... Nf6  and there, look for a push on the kingside or timidly play ... Bd7 , ... b6 , ... a6 , ... Rb8  to tease with ... b6 -... b5  whenever White gets too funny on the kingside. The position is very solid for both, so take your time, pick up a nice beverage, and grind for the win! }
