[Black "1...c5!? with 3.Nc3 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. c5{ This move order has often been discarded as allowing to play  Nc3  without  c2 - c4  was historically considered very good for White. White has the amazing  c4 -square for the  g1 -knight, and Black doesn't really have too much counterplay yet. But it also runs into safer Benoni's and can be an interesting complement to this course. }
2. d5
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. Bg7
4. e4
4. d6{ Here we will go for ... e6  or  b7 -... b5  depending on our opponent's setup. }
5. Bb5+{ I even played this move. White gives an annoying check and forces black to decide. I wouldn't say it is specially tricky, but you need to know how to regroup the pieces. }
5. Bd7
6. a4{ White consolidates the queenside and playing ... a6  would be detrimental for the  b8 -knight after  Be2 ! }
6. Nf6
7. Nf3
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Bxb5{ This is the most consistent plan, and I don't like fancy ... Bg4  ideas that much in these structures. }
9. axb5
9. Nbd7
10. Qe2
10. Ne8
11. Bf4
11. Nc7{ Now ... Nb6 , ... Qd7 , ... e6  is a very clear plan, and White will struggle to create any counterplay or pressure while having to worry about the exposed queenside. }
