1. d4
1. c5{ This move order has often been discarded as allowing to play  Nc3  without  c2 - c4  was historically considered very good for White. White has the amazing  c4 -square for the  g1 -knight, and Black doesn't really have too much counterplay yet. But it also runs into safer Benoni's and can be an interesting complement to this course. }
2. d5
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. Bg7
4. e4
4. d6{ Here we will go for ... e6  or  b7 -... b5  depending on our opponent's setup. }
5. Nf3
5. Nf6
6. Bc4{ I think this is the best objectively. With reversed colors and the pawn on  e6  still, it is one of the best setups for Black, so imagine how good it should be here. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Na6{ I prefer not to dive into ... Bg4  every time. Without a clear counterplay on the queenside it is a bit harder to pull off, and here White is happy to collect the bishop pair and then look for pressure into the center or with  h4 - h5 . }
8. Re1
8. Nc7{ Now  e7 -... e6  is the idea. }
9. Bf4{ White prevents ... e6  for now, as  d6  would fall. }
9. Nh5
10. Be3
10. a6
11. a4
11. Bg4{ Now ... Bg4  has excellent timing and ... b5  is an immediate threat due to  b2  hanging. }
