[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. c5{ This move order has often been discarded as allowing to play  Nc3  without  c2 - c4  was historically considered very good for White. White has the amazing  c4 -square for the  g1 -knight, and Black doesn't really have too much counterplay yet. But it also runs into safer Benoni's and can be an interesting complement to this course. }
2. d5
2. g6
3. c4
3. Bg7{ Finally, we are going to take a brief look at the Benoni options when our opponent plays  c4  anyway. This chapter is just an alternative, so you enjoy all the options through the Benoni.     Adding a chapter on the Benko/Volga would be a bit too out of topic, maybe if it is requested a lot we can dig into it, but this setup can be used to surprise someone. Recently, Magnus and our God in these setups, Pantsulaia, have been finding success with it. }
4. Nc3
4. Bxc3+{ This apparently 'absurd' idea has a deep strategy behind it. Black 'closes' the  a1 - h8  diagonal, so the  c1 -bishop would be a bit silly. Afterward, we aim to control the center to prevent White from opening it and making room for the bishops. }
5. bxc3
5. f5( 5...e5 { would likely transpose to the mainline, as }6.d6?! { would be a bit dubious, the pawn won't do much on his own, and it doesn't really restrict us any development. } )
6. e4{ Is the other way to play for White. White gives up a pawn to accelerate the kingside development and to open the  e  and  f -files. }
6. fxe4
7. f3
7. d6{ We prefer to close the position a bit. }
8. fxe4
8. e5{ We will play ... h6 , ... Qe7  and then ... Nf6 , ... Nbd7 . Our king would end up on the queenside, likely via ... Kd8 -... Kc7 , and we have a very sound and solid position. Later on, trying to go for ... Qg7 , ... g5 , ... Nh5 , ... Nf4  could make a lot of sense as we are very strong in the dark squares. }( { If White doesn't play }9.Nf3 { we could even sneak ... Qh4 + first, so White weakens the kingside a bit more. It is a very dark position and schematic, and you can get a lot of benefit from having practice with it. } )
