1. d4
1. c5{ This move order has often been discarded as allowing to play  Nc3  without  c2 - c4  was historically considered very good for White. White has the amazing  c4 -square for the  g1 -knight, and Black doesn't really have too much counterplay yet. But it also runs into safer Benoni's and can be an interesting complement to this course. }
2. d5
2. g6
3. c4
3. Bg7{ Finally, we are going to take a brief look at the Benoni options when our opponent plays  c4  anyway. This chapter is just an alternative, so you enjoy all the options through the Benoni.     Adding a chapter on the Benko/Volga would be a bit too out of topic, maybe if it is requested a lot we can dig into it, but this setup can be used to surprise someone. Recently, Magnus and our God in these setups, Pantsulaia, have been finding success with it. }
4. Nc3
4. Bxc3+{ This apparently 'absurd' idea has a deep strategy behind it. Black 'closes' the  a1 - h8  diagonal, so the  c1 -bishop would be a bit silly. Afterward, we aim to control the center to prevent White from opening it and making room for the bishops. }
5. bxc3
5. f5( 5...e5 { would likely transpose to the mainline, as }6.d6?! { would be a bit dubious, the pawn won't do much on his own, and it doesn't really restrict us any development. } )
6. h4{ The most conventional plan. White tries to break through the weakened kingside. }
6. Nf6
7. h5
7. Rg8{ We don't want to take on  h5 . White would be happy to sacrifice an exchange and then go for  e4 !, preparing  Qxh5 .     The relative value of the exchange sacrifice has to take into account how closed the position is and how hard it is for Black to bring his queenside into action quickly. Technically, White would have a material advantage for a while and would usually mean a quick victory in this case. }
8. hxg6
8. hxg6
9. d6{ Otherwise, we play ... d6 , ... Qa5 , ... Nbd7  and then try to protect the king with ... Kd8 -... Kc7  or go for ... Nb6 , ... Bd7 , ... O-O-O . White doesn't have any obvious way to push through the center, and the doubles pawns are extremely inconvenient for the bishops.     Later on, we can even push for  e7 -... e6  to claim the light-squares in the center or even turn the tables in our favor, getting back the  h -file with ... Rh8 . White has a hard time combining both flanks, and that's why I think this setup can be tested. }
9. Nc6{ We will follow with ... Ne4  and later on, it highly depends on what White plays. Overall, is a safe position, and it is extremely hard to play and assess with White. It is a really nice surprise weapon and even stronger in lower time controls. }
