17. Na6{ One important take I wanted to give in the Benoni. Pay attention how development just "works". Remember to "try" moves in your head, specially in the Benoni. Sometimes my students would struggle to find a move and it is usually because the "most appealing" moves would cast a shadown into the other possibilities. Don't stop at "NEED TO MOVE THE ROOK, IT'S BEEN THREATEN", think for "What if I develop the knight and suddenly I threaten the rook? Can I get back the rook and be more developed at the same time?". Keep looking for opportunities and moves and try to go further everytime when you self-impose a restriction to yourself. "Do I really need to move the rook? Is this really a threat? Does my opponent really prevent my move?".   This is relatively easy to do in the first couple of moves of a calculation, but imagine when you are 5 moves deep, it's incredibly hard and your brain wants to give you quick solutions and get out of that stress :) so keep looking and get a bit better every game, it will add up! }
18. Bxb4
18. Nxb4
19. Ra3
19. Bb2{ Voilà! We get back the rook and White still has the passive bishop on  g2 . }
20. Ra4
20. Bxa4
21. bxa4
21. Bg7{ This is a great example on how small tactics work. You see 22.  Nc4  is a threat and you retreat preemtively so you can counter that move. You let your opponent play the move they been dreaming of. }
22. Nc4
22. Na2{ Now the knight is not just a safe outpost and from  c3  we will be pressuring all the key pawns }
23. Qd2{ Here the "recommended" way to play with  e2 - e4  is to allow Black  Nc3  and  Bd4 , which is highly suspicious as  Rb8 - Rb4  is a follow up threat hard to counter. }
23. Nc3
24. Rc1
24. Nxa4
25. Bf3{ You might be thinking "but Àlvar, White just gave up the pawn without any resistance!, why is this a model game!" and i'll kindly answer to that statement: "Well, tell me how Black makes any progress now". This is another important lesson in small tactics or how to assess positions. Material/ intuition/structure, all superficial knowledge is reliant on dynamics. Here Black cannot move the  a4  knight without allowing  Rxc3  or  Nxa5 . With 25.  Bf3  White defends  e2  preemtively as  Qf6 !  Nxa5   Nc3 ! followed by  Ra4  or  Ra2  was a serious dynamic threat. }
25. Qc7
26. e3{ 26.  Kg2 ! was a must. Now Iturrizaga sees a dynamic solution. }
26. Qb8
27. Nxa5
27. Bc3( 27...Qb4 28.Nc4⇆  )
28. Rxc3
28. Rxa5{ Strategically this is a good move. Black has a passed pawn with a Knight, that usually shines when all the pawns are in one flank. }( 28...Nxc3! 29.Qxc3 Qb5!! 30.Nc6 Qb1+! 31.Kh2 ( 31.Kg2 Ra1! { White is forced to give up the Queen. } )Ra2! { Likely the move Iturrizaga missed. Is not that obvious to see that after 32.  Bg2   Rxf2  White is defenceless whenever the knight is on  c6  or  c4  (as 30.  Nc4  is an extra option that would make Black think a bit more) . } )
29. Rc4
